<HEADLINE>
REELING 'EM IN  
 ATHLETES, PRO TEAMS TAKE ADVANTAGE OF PHOENIX'S CLIMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you noticed that it's getting more crowded around here?
</P>
<P>
   Mini-mart gas stations and fast-food restaurants on every
corner. Malls popping up like mushrooms. Housing developments
gobbling up open spaces. And traffic, lots of traffic. Even the
carpool lanes are developing arterial sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   But we haven't become LA _ not yet, anyway. And that is part of
the allure. The sky is still clear, for the most part, the sunsets
are heavenly and snow shovels aren't a big seller.
</P>
<P>
   People from around the country and the world have discovered
what once was native Arizonans' secret: It's a great place to live.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the record, athletes are people, too.
</P>
<P>
   From the Diamondbacks' Randy Johnson and Matt Williams to golfer
Tom Lehman and dozens of other top-flight athletes, the Arizona
lifestyle, and Arizona's pro sports opportunities, have proved an
irresistible combination.
</P>
<P>
   Jyrki Lumme left Vancouver. The Suns' Rex Chapman and Danny
Manning migrated. Heck, even Mike Tyson wants to live here.
</P>
<P>
   That's a trend _ one that should keep Arizona's sports teams
competitive in all fields.
</P>
<P>
   What has led to this major league immigration of talent?
</P>
<P>
   It's different from sport to sport, and from player to player. A
competitive organization, a charismatic owner _ and, of course, top
money _ can be integral to attracting athletes as well. The
Republic's Sunday Special report looks at some of the factors that
have led the state to become a sports magnet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
