<SLUG> BC-PHOENIX-HOME-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE THAT GREEN: MONEY, GRASS  
 CARDINALS ARE DRAWN TO PLAYING SURFACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Bob Ferguson would rather have great weather than
not have it, although he acknowledges an undying love for Buffalo,
N.Y., where he once worked.
</P>
<P>
   He figures that most free-agent pro football players he tries to
hire see it the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else being equal, the Valley's mild autumn and winter
weather offers one advantage: Grass. Green grass. Green, soft grass
that doesn't cause pounding on sensitive joints or create
three-inch carpet burns that take a month to heal.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals practice on, and play home games on, the real
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been used here over the years,'' said Ferguson, the
Cardinals vice president for player personnel. ``The climate is
more a factor in football than in a lot of other sports in this
city. No. 1 is, we play on grass. That's something guys think about
even if it's in Cleveland. It's more important in free agency in
our business than others.''
</P>
<P>
   The climate, which encourages those pristine playing fields, can
be a deal-closer but not a deal-maker, according to Ferguson. In
the NFL, and other professional sports, the bottom line for a
free-agent isn't the opportunity to get in a round of golf in
February in a light sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe money dictates all of it. No question,''
Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley is off-season home to many NFL players, but not all
of them are beating a path to the Cardinals. For example, safety
Mark Carrier, a Scottsdale resident, took a look at Arizona but
signed with Detroit because he got a better contract offer.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin concurs with Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most decisions are determined by the contract offer,'' Tobin
said. ``But when you get into intangibles, if a player has two or
three offers that are similar, it might make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've heard players tell me playing on grass is important
to them, then they sign where you can't practice outside and where
you play on turf because they got more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said he was happy to see the Diamondbacks sign pitcher
Randy Johnson to a whopping free-agent contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to see them get Randy,'' Ferguson said. ``I love
that kind of thing. I'd love to see the Diamondbacks succeed.
Success helps all the teams in the Valley. It attracts attention
for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``For baseball players, this city is an attractive place to
live. There are so many training camps in Arizona. Now they have a
beautiful stadium. Those things are important. When we have our
stadium, we'll have more to offer, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I sell us, and the program, and the organization more
than the weather,'' Ferguson said. ``Players make those decisions
on their own. You don't want to oversell.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Eric Swann, for example, wanted to stay with
the club when he became a free agent last winter not only because
he saw a young defense with the potential to dominate. He also
wanted to play on natural grass because of his arthritic knees.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Chris Gedney said the climate was a factor in his
signing with the Cardinals after his contract in Chicago expired
two seasons ago. He moved his family to the Valley year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of the Cardinals still live elsewhere in the
off-season, but many NFL players live here, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the weather was a bonus but not the determining
factor, Gedney said. ``Obviously it is easier on your body to play
on grass in warm weather. That alone isn't enough to put it over
the top. I know a lot of players who live here, have houses here,
who play for other teams would like to stay here to play, too.''
</P>
<P>
   If the club gets its new stadium _ voters in May will help
determine that _ Ferguson said that will give the club additional
sources of revenue to make better offers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
