<SLUG> BC-PHOENIX-HOME-SUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY SUNS, IT'S CO LANGELO  
 FIRST-CLASS OPERA TION ATTRACTS NBA PLAY ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Look around on the Valley's golf courses, and you're
likely to see any number of former or current NBA players,
especially in the winter of the NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Former Suns such as Charles Barkley, Dan Majerle and Joe Kleine
make their homes here. So does former NBA great Bob Lanier, who now
works for the league. Former NBA Coach Dick Motta resides here, as
do current Suns, such as Danny Manning.
</P>
<P>
   But is it the Valley's warm weather, it's golf courses and low
taxes that attract athletes?
</P>
<P>
   Suns Coach Danny Ainge, who has been recruited and done the
recruiting, said those factors may be the reasons players decide to
make their permanent homes here, but it isn't why they come here to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge was signed by the Suns as a free agent in 1992 and played
three seasons in the Valley. He made his home in Gilbert and
remained there after his playing career ended while he worked as an
analyst for Turner Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a coach, Ainge is on the other end, trying to convince
free-agent players that this is the place to live and play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this sounds corny, but I came to Phoenix because I felt
like they had a good team, I felt they needed me and wanted me at
the time,'' Ainge said. ``Every athlete wants to be wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you want me to say it was the golf courses and the warm
weather and all that, but if Phoenix wasn't a good basketball
organization and didn't have a good team, none of that would have
meant anything. Ultimately, what got me here was Jerry Colangelo.''
</P>
<P>
   Players have cited the America West Arena facility, which
includes an on-site practice gym, top-of-the-line weight room,
saunas and a giant Jacuzzi whirlpool. The Valley's lifestyle also
is attractive because of the warm winters.
</P>
<P>
   But Ainge said it takes more. He said recent signings by the
Arizona Diamondbacks, which also are under Colangelo's umbrella,
prove that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of this (NBA) lockout, I've had an opportunity to talk
to Todd Stottlemyre and Steve Finley, and both of those guys told
me one of the main reasons they were coming here was Jerry
Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry's a powerful man, yet he's approachable and he wants to
win. That comes across in his conversations, and you have
confidence that he knows what he's doing. You can see in his eyes
and hear in his voice that he's going to do everything he can to
have a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had other opportunities to coach before Phoenix, and I went
in to talk with Jerry about this job knowing what he was going to
ask and thinking I wasn't going to do it. I had a great job at TNT,
a great lifestyle. He convinced me this was the time, and this was
the place. He has a passion for what he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, guys coming here to retire is a whole different scenario.
That's where the weather and golf courses are a factor. But I'll
maintain that players go where they think they'll have success,
where they feel wanted and where they'll be treated like
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all about sun and golf. Los Angeles is very similar
in that way. There's plenty of great weather and golf courses, but
I don't see anybody dying to go play for the Clippers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
