<SLUG> BC-PHOENIX-HOME-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY COMES FIRST  
 DOLLARS, FACILITIES ALSO IMPORTANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - One could almost feel the parched throat of Randy
Johnson, the Diamondbacks' tall drink of water, as he talked about
playing for the team and residing in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can make it through the summers here,'' he said, followed
by a pause, ``I'll probably live here the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Seattle Mariners for the bulk of his career,
Johnson hasn't had the opportunity to bake here. But $52.4 million
will buy a lot of thirst quenchers. Pitching in air-conditioned,
retractable-roof Bank One Ballpark also should help.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is family. That is one of the reasons why Johnson
moved here in 1996, long before he became a Diamondback. It is a
good place for families, he said, and when his wife and kids are
happy, he is, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look in the stands and see family, it motivates me,
makes me dig down a little bit deeper,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   It impressed him, Johnson said, to learn that third baseman Matt
Williams would ask to leave a World Series team in Cleveland to be
with his children in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It would be naive to think that it's just about the living
conditions. In the case of the Diamondbacks and Suns, both operated
by Jerry Colangelo, it's about the working conditions and how much
the team is willing to pay the players to work in those conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound like we're patting ourselves on our
backs, but I think a lot of our success and the reason that people
want to play here is that we treat athletes the way they want to be
treated and not like a pound of flesh,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   The tide began to turn, he said, when the Suns moved from
Veterans Memorial Coliseum to America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the practice court there, the locker area, all the
amenities. . . . We created something that is self-perpetuating,''
Colangelo said. ``We wanted the plan to be the same for the
ballpark, and that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams moved here in 1987 while playing for the San Francisco
Giants and their Triple-A affiliate, the Phoenix Firebirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do anything at any time of year here,'' he said. ``You
really can't beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other major-leaguers live here, as well as many
Firebirds alumni. Diamondback-turned-Dodger Devon White, Tony
Phillips, Terry Mulholland, Jeff Fassero, Mike Fetters, Bill Swift,
Cal Eldred and former major-leaguers such as Ryne Sandberg share
our freeways.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time that Williams moved here, catcher Kirt
Manwaring, his buddy with the Giants and Firebirds, made the move
from Horseheads, in west-central New York state. Williams and
Manwaring, a free agent who likely will return to the Colorado
Rockies next season, have the same agent. They still live near each
other in Scottsdale and hang out together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have moved to the Bay area, but it was hard not to
want to live here,'' Manwaring said. ``The cost of living is a
little better and it's a great place for families. You can do so
much.'' Eldred, the Milwaukee Brewers right-hander, moved from Iowa
to Chandler in 1995, near what was then the team's spring-training
site, to work on rehabilitating his injured elbow. He and his
family remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're Christians. Our faith is very important to us, and we
found a Christian fellowship here that is fantastic,'' Eldred said.
``The family atmosphere and the weather are important. Being away
from the kids most of the summer is difficult, but the weather is
so good here that the winter is like a second summer to us, going
out and doing all sorts of activities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
