<SLUG> BC-PHOENIX-HOME-COYOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRANCHISE ON THE RISE  
 FOR COYOTES, BIG DRAW IS SHOT AT CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Hockey players, by nature, seem to be excellent
golfers. They say it might have something to do with the
similarities of the swing of a driver to the slam of a slap shot.
</P>
<P>
   But golf, and the abundance of quality golf resorts in the
Valley, really has nothing to do with wooing potential National
Hockey League free agents to Phoenix to play for the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even have time for golf,'' said defenseman Jyrki
Lumme, one of the most coveted unrestricted free agents in the
league last summer, who chose to sign with the Coyotes over a
half-dozen other clubs. ``During the season, you don't really have
enough time to play, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the summer, when I do have time, I'll probably go back
to Finland like I always do, or maybe go spend some time in
Vancouver.''
</P>
<P>
   Lumme, who played in Vancouver for the past nine seasons, had
never played for a team in the United States before. His first two
seasons in the NHL were spent in Montreal. He hemmed and hawed
about leaving Canada, but like many Coyotes players interviewed, he
said his first and foremost reason for coming to Phoenix was
because he felt the franchise was on the rise and capable of
challenging for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and down their roster and I really liked what I
saw,'' Lumme said. ``That was the biggest thing for me. I felt by
coming here, I had a real chance to win. Everything else, like the
weather, the good facilities, the quality of life, that was nice.
But it was kind of secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto with veteran power forward Rick Tocchet, who won a Stanley
Cup in Pittsburgh and could have signed with just about any team
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, one of the factors actually ``was'' the weather,''
said Tocchet, who has said the cold and snow he encountered while
playing back East made his battle with minor back problems tougher.
``But I liked the way the roster looked, too. They had some good
young players here, some quality veterans, and a team that wants to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lumme and Tocchet, and others, offered various reasons why
playing in the Valley has its advantages over other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The affordability,'' said center Jeremy Roenick, who didn't
really have a choice in coming to the Valley. He was traded to the
Coyotes two seasons ago by the Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying houses or buying land is excellent in Arizona. It's a
great place, financially, to live. You've still got your taxes, but
it's nothing like you pay in other places, like Canada, for
instance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lumme said hockey players don't live in a fishbowl here like
they do in the Great White North. That, to him, was also a plus,
especially after the disappointing season the Canucks had a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a little healthier atmosphere in Phoenix,'' Lumme
said. ``The stuff I had to go through last year . . . every day it
was people in my face asking questions. I don't need that. The
pressure is still there. That never goes away. But now, when I go
to the grocery store, you don't have everyone asking you what is
going on if you lost one or two games.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenick and Tocchet said they plan to make Phoenix their
permanent homes, regardless of where their hockey careers take
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've consolidated, man. I moved everything here. I'm a Phoenix
guy now,'' Tocchet said. ``I've got no more properties back in
Pennsylvania like I used to have. I just really love it here.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the golf . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Roenick, who sports a 1 handicap, ``it doesn't
hurt.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
