<SLUG> BC-PHOENIX-HOME-GOLFERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, IT REALLY IS THE GOLF AND WEATHER  
 PRO GOLFERS FIND CONDITIONS IDEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -For Hale Irwin, Arizona was not his first choice when
he decided to relocate from his longtime residence near St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, my wife (Sally) and I bought a piece of property in
Florida six years ago, but we never really knew what to do with
it,'' said the Senior PGA Tour star of the lot he bought in North
Palm Beach. ``Jack and Barb (Nicklaus) kept telling us that we
needed to live by the water, and so we just kept sitting on it (the
lot) trying to decide what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I said to Sally, we need to go out and look at
Phoenix one more time before we sink that much money into (a new
lot by the water). We took a trip to Arizona and really liked the
desert. The climate and the golf courses, plus future
considerations with my golf course business, just kind of dictated
us moving here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Irwin said there were a few other considerations to the
Irwins' move to Paradise Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis always gets a little chilly. Actually it's downright
cold this time of year,'' she said. ``And Hale needed a place
conducive to practice in the winter, and we'd always loved the
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona and Florida have a similar climate, but it's less
windy in Arizona and it rains a lot more in Florida. Once our house
is done, everything will be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Raising Arizona to the top of their list obviously works for
other pros, too. More than 40 LPGA players, five other seniors and
19 PGA Tour players called Arizona home during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Of those three tours, the PGA Tour might be the most
representative when it comes to the preference of professional
golfers. Only Florida (64 PGA Tour players), California (29) and
Texas (29) are called home by more pros than Arizona. And Florida
and Texas have a special allure _ no state income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Calcavecchia is well aware of the Arizona-Florida debate
that faces many professional athletes. He owns a home in Ahwatukee,
but also keeps a second home in West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's mainly a tax thing,'' said Calcavecchia, who
claims residency in Florida even though he spends most of his time
in his 90-door mansion nestled into the foothills of South
Mountain. ``I mean, there has to be a reason why Tiger and all of
those guys are living in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I can come up with is the weather advantages.
Florida is just not as consistently nice as Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's another reason Calcavecchia enjoys Arizona,
said his wife, Sheryl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really the one that loves Arizona, having grown up here in
the Valley and still having all of my family here,'' she said.
``But Mark has come to love it, too, now that we've got all the
professional sports covered and he can go to the games when he's
not playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, he's got some pretty good memories, having won the
Phoenix Open twice.''
</P>
<P>
   For Tom and Melissa Lehman, the choice was easy. Minnesota or
Arizona? OK, next question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great weather, a great city, great people, and it's
convenient for both of us with our parents and family,'' the
Scottsdale pro said. ``It's a nice big city, yet it has a little
bit of a small-city feel to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf is great, and it's got a great airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee, the Chamber of Commerce could not have said it better. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
