<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ASU-GONZAGA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU WOMEN TOP GONZAGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - It's one thing for Arizona State to win the first
game of a women's basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing the job is another story.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils (3-2) get another chance at 7 tonight in the
final of the Wells Fargo Classic against St. Joseph's (3-3), which
downed Pacific in the late game Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ASU is on an eight-tournament title drought over three-plus
seasons, including a loss to 11th-ranked Rutgers a week ago in the
championship game of the Rutgers Coca-Cola Classic.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Devils' 96-52 blowout of Gonzaga on Saturday was a
better win than the 71-48 decision over Southwestern Louisiana at
Rutgers, ASU Coach Charli Turner Thorne said. And on paper St.
Joseph's is not as good as Rutgers although the Hawks beat the
Scarlet Knights, 67-54, last season.
</P>
<P>
   That adds up to a chance for the Sun Devils to capture their
holiday tournament for the first time since 1994, but only if they
can put a complete game together at Wells Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what it takes,'' said freshman forward Leah Combs, in
double-figure rebounds (12) for the fourth time of her brief
college career. ``We need to put the whole thing together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be ready,'' Turner Thorne said. ``If we do what we do
well, we'll be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even coming off consecutive losses to Rutgers (67-48) and Texas
(77-75), ASU needed something of a wake-up call halfway through the
first half. Gonzaga (1-5) used an 8-1 run to pull within 21-16 at
9:07 and force an ASU timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ASU scored the next 10 points, four of those by backup forward
Aubrey McFadyen in what was her best game of the season, then
buried the Bulldogs, 52-27, by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's way too late (to break away),'' Combs said. ``We can't
come out slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Sun Devils reached double-figure scoring, including point
guard Natalie Tucker with a team-high 17, but the game was most
significant for the return of Ebony Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the first game of the Wells Fargo Classic last year
that Edwards, the two-time Arizona Player of the Year from Chandler
High School, blew out her right knee. Her return this season was
delayed because of arthroscopic surgery, her third such procedure
on the same knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about that (timing coincidence) the other day,''
Edwards said. ``I'm not worried about my knee. I just have to take
it little by little, and I have to make sure my legs are warmed up
before the game. I'm just looking forward to getting through a full
season. I can help the team out. My talent hasn't been seen yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards played three minutes per half against Gonzaga and hit a
pair of second-half jumpers. She also flashed the intense defense
that makes her a valuable addition to a guard lineup, which with
the uncertain availability of Georgie Lang, was at least one player
short.
</P>
<P>
   Three of those guards _ Tucker, Kitch Kitchen and Shelly Tom _
combined for 41 points as ASU shot 53.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
