<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS DENY TIFFS WITH STARS' COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, we told you things weren't looking so rosy down in
Dallas, where sources said the Stars were in danger of possibly
blowing up because of some apparent backbiting over their coach,
 &UR; Ken
 &UR; Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Dallas players responded by saying there are no
problems whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really hard to believe,'' Stars defenseman  &UR; Shawn
Chambers told ``The Dallas Morning News.'' ``To me, it's
humorous,'' ``Guys talk all the time, saying things like, `Hitch is
on a rampage.' But the next day, everything is fine. That's part of
the little stuff, and it happens all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Richard Matvichuk said the team has no beef with
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect Hitch for what he's done for this team,'' he said.
``He's brought us to where we are, from not making the playoffs a
few years ago, to winning the President's Trophy last year.
Somebody's just trying to stir the pot. From the players to the
coaching staff, we've got a pretty good relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Darryl Sydor said, ``I think someone's fishing for
something, trying to get something stirred up here. Maybe it's the
playoffs starting a little early.'' &QL; 
Warning, Mr. Robinson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They say things are dandy in Dallas, but it's definitely lousy
in Los Angeles, where the Kings have stumbled to 10 losses in an
11-game stretch and have scored just once in the first period in
their past nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Larry Robinson erupted after a recent loss, questioning
his players' hearts for their refusal to play in front of the net
and pay the price with gutsy efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can tell them to go there, and we can show them what they
can do,'' Robinson said, ``but we're not allowed to jump on the ice
and grab them by the scruff of the neck and place them in front of
the net and say, `Hey, you've got to be here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the problem has nothing to do with personnel. It's
desire. His players aren't showing any, and he's fed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't produce, it's going to up at the point where
(General Manager) Dave (Taylor) is going to come to me and say,
`Hey, you know, either you get these guys going or we'll try to
find someone else' or I'm out of here. And I'll be damned if I'm
going to give up that early. . . . I'll be (expletive) if I'm going
to be the fall guy here.'' &QL; 
Save the ice
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's new edict to eliminate skate arounds before the second
and third periods to preserve the quality of the ice surface goes
into effect on Monday. If anyone besides the goalie and the five
starting skaters take a few spins around the rink to warm up, the
team will be given a two-minute bench minor.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes defenseman  &UR; Gerald Diduck rolled his eyes when asked
about the new rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, in this age of environmentalism, it's save the whale,
save the fox, save the deer,'' Diduck quipped. ``You might as well
save the ice, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need any stinking skate around anyway. Just drop the
puck and let's go.'' &QL; 
R-E-S-P-E-C-T
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Sharks Coach  &UR; Darryl Sutter apparently isn't giving the
Coyotes, the Dallas Stars or anyone else, for that matter, much
chance of challenging the Detroit Red Wings for the Stanley Cup
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until somebody takes the Stanley Cup away from the Detroit Red
Wings, there's nobody else,'' Sutter said. ``They'e the best team
in the league by 10 miles. I mean, is there any other team in the
league that can play four lines and have their starting goaltender
out for a period of time and it doesn't bother them at all?'' &QL; 
Jerry! Jerry! Jerry!
</P>
<P>
   When the Mighty Ducks were in Chicago last week, Selanne used a
day off to go see a taping of the ``Jerry Springer Show.'' He
managed to get front-row seats for himself and Anaheim rookies
 &UR; Mike Crowley, Antti
 &UR; Aalto and  &UR; Johan Davidsson.
</P>
<P>
   The show had a Thanksgiving theme, featuring families squabbling
about the holiday season. Three tables full of food were on the
stage, and it wasn't long before it turned into a food fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got hit in the leg with a slice of cake,'' said Aalto, a big
fan of the show. ``I try to watch it every night. After the show,
we got to meet him. I guess I'll go to the movie next.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teammates wished they had been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 12 guys said they wanted to go,'' Selanne said, ``but
I only had four tickets.'' &QL; 
The borrowers
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to many published reports, the Pittsburgh Penguins
haven't officially been awarded a $20 million loan from a French
bank to meet their upcoming payroll. A bankruptcy court judge won't
make the ruling until later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the loan,'' Penguins attorney  &UR; Robert G. Sable said.
``We'll run out of money in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins, reportedly worth between $75 million and $105
million, are $127 million in debt already. According to court
documents, they owe everyone from  &UR; Mario Lemieux to, get this,
$4,000 to the March of Dimes and $7.43 to a Georgia-based
long-distance phone company. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
