<HEADLINE>
SCHOENFELD: ALL WAITING FOR COYOTES TO FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ If it seems like all of Canada _ and the rest
of the NHL for that matter _ is waiting for the Coyotes to fall on
their face after such a hot start, it's probably because they are,
Coach Jim Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm sure that's what people out there are waiting for,''
Schoenfeld said before Saturday night's game against the Flames.
``That's just natural. When you're a new team and you're leading
the pack, people want to see if you're for real or not. All we can
do is maintain our winning edge and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach John Tortorella said the Coyotes should take
advantage of the perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a type of motivation you can use as a player, as
a coach, as an organization,'' he said. ``People still don't
believe in the Phoenix Coyotes and what they're trying to do as a
team. People have their opinions, but we know what we're trying to
accomplish. We're going to continue to strive and ... in June,
hoefully make people believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes captain keith Tkachuk said he could care less what
people are saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can say ... I don't care what they say,'' Tkachuk said.
``We deserve a little credit. I know it's early. We want to be
there at the end. That's when we want to stick it in everybody's
faces.'' &QL; 
GM meetings
</P>
<P>
   General managers from around the NHL will descend on the Valley
today for the start of two days of league meetings, which begin
Monday at the Phoenician Resort in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items on the agenda to be discussed include the
league's participation in the 2002 Winter Olympics at Salt Lake
City, the idea of adopting a shootout rule to end overtime ties,
and the financial burdens being felt by the six Canadian teams.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is expected to be resolved this week, however. The GMs
and the league's Board of Governors aren't expected to vote on any
sweeping changes until they meet again in February.
</P>
<P>
   As for the the Olympics, it is believed the NHL will once again
interrupt its season to allow its players to participate, but only
under the assurances that NBC televise the games in prime time. &QL; 
Slapshots
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's game, the Coyotes had eight players who were
a plus-10 or better in the plus-minus rankings. Pittsburgh and
Toronto were the next closest with three. Detroit has only two, as
does Edmonton and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The eight Phoenix players and their rankings: Tkachuk (+14),
Rick Tocchet, Juha Ylonen and Jyrki Lumme (each +11), Jeremy
Roenick, Dallas Drake, Oleg Tverdovsky and Keith Carney (each +10).
</P>
<P>
   Goalie coach Benoit Allaire joined the team in Calgary before
Saturday 's game after spending the past three days working with
the Coyotes' two young goalies in Springfield of the American
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might never let him leave again,'' joked Coach Jim
Schoenfeld, refer ring to Wednesday's 4-3 loss in Edmonton, which
Allaire didn't attend.
</P>
<P>
   During the Coyotes' 14-game unbeaten streak, the team went 42
days and nights without a loss. During their 17-game string of
allowing two goals or fewer, they went 53 days and nights between
giving up more than two.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Sean Gagnon, an eforcer who the Coyotes have playing
in Springfield this season, was given a four-game suspension for an
intent-to-injure misconduct during a game last week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
