<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WILLING TO SPEND TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers are preparing to lose some $18 million next
season, even if they manage to attract 3 million fans. Why? Because
the Rangers' new ownership is prepared to step up and play with the
big boys.
</P>
<P>
   Club President  &UR; Tom Schieffer, with the full backing of new
owner  &UR; Tom
 &UR; Hicks, plans to increase the club's payroll to somewhere near $75
million. He has decided to play with the heavyweights, no matter
the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market expects you to compete, and we think the price of
competing is is going to be in that range,'' Schieffer said. ``And
we do have a very good team without  &UR; Randy Johnson on it. We don't
want to tear it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Within one day of Johnson choosing to play for the Diamondbacks,
the Rangers started showing their commitment, signing first baseman
 &UR; Rafael
 &UR; Palmeiro and shortstop  &UR; Royce Clayton for a combined $63 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to do what it takes to get this club to the next
level,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro represents a significant upgrade over  &UR; Will Clark, who
signed with Baltimore on Saturday, in several areas.
</P>
<P>
   In five seasons with Baltimore, Palmeiro hit .292 with 182
homers, 553 RBIs and &UR; a .545 &UR; slugging percentage. In five seasons
with Texas, Clark hit .308 with 77 homers, 397 RBIs and a .485
slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Palmeiro is far more dependable. He missed six games in
five years with the Orioles. Clark missed 136 games, nearly a full
season, in his five years with Texas. &QL; 
Where's the game heading? &QL; 
If it seems like the money has gone wacko in baseball, well, maybe
it has. The game's highest-paid player (at least for the moment),
 &UR; Mo &UR; Vaughn, is being paid an average salary of $13.33 million. At
the beginning of the decade the game's five most expensive players
_  &UR; Robin
 &UR; Yount,  &UR; Kirby Puckett,  &UR; Roger Clemens,  &UR; Eddie Murray and  &UR; Don
Mattingly _ earned a combined $13.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yount was the game's highest-paid player in 1990, earning $3.2
million. Baseball's average salary has increased from $589,483 to
$1,377,196 (and that's without  &UR; Kevin Brown having signed).
</P>
<P>
   Only one club whose payroll was under $47 million managed to
have a winning record. That club? The Toronto Blue Jays. &QL; 
Road grays &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the Los Angeles Dodgers' uniform change may not be
as destructive as previously believed. The change in road uniforms
will actually be a throw back to the club's days in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' road gray uniforms will no longer read ``Dodgers''
across the chest but rather a scriped ``Los Angeles,'' much like
the days when the club's road uniforms read ``Brooklyn.'' In
addition, there will be a bit more blue stitching in the uniform. &QL; 
The hit list &QL; 
 &UR; Wonder if they still get their cut: Rafael Palmeiro's agents,  &UR; Bob
 &UR; Gilhooly and  &UR; Jim Bronner, has basically nothing to do in
negotiating the five-year $45 million contract the first baseman
reached with the Rangers last week. Palmeiro's financial adviser
hammered out the deal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback (to the very first free agent): Andy Messersmith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Daddy Warbucks nearly stuck the big one: It turns out
Diamondbacks managing general partner Jerry Colangelo did offer
Bernie Williams an eight-year deal worth $100 million. At least,
that's what the owners' player relations committee is saying.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Another feather in his tarnished cap: As early as last spring,
Florida's former owner,  &UR; Wayne Huizenga, was aware that the 2000
All-Star Game could be taken away from the Marlins. Not once did he
mention that news during negotiations to sell the club. &QL; 
Extra bases &QL; 
One of Atlanta's biggest shortcomings, its bench, has been upgraded
in a major way. The Braves' bench, as of today, looks like this:
 &UR; Otis &UR; Nixon,  &UR; Ozzie Guillen,  &UR; Gerald Williams,  &UR; Keith Lockhart and
 &UR; Eddie Perez. Only one more spot is open.
</P>
<P>
   The large and intimidating presence of  &UR; Dave Parker will no
longer be visible on the St. Louis Cardinals' bench. The former MVP
will not return as the Cardinals hitting coach. Expect Manager
 &UR; Tony La Russa to try to coax  &UR; Doug Rader out of retirement. &QL; 
The rumor mill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets are talking about bringing major league stolen
base king  &UR; Rickey Henderson to Queens to become their everyday left
fielder and leadoff hitter. Seattle has also shown an interest.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have received several inquiries about second baseman
 &UR; Eric Young, who will be paid $4.5 million each of the next three
years, practically a bargain these days. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
