<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5162 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BIG12-CASSTEVENS-     12-06 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG12-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULL OUT YOUR TRUSTY CALCULATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS - H'llo, you have reached the BCS 24-hour crisis
hotline. UCLA fans, press one. Kansas State fans, press two.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona fans, press any number.
</P>
<P>
   If the line is busy, please hold. A counselor will be with you
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second quarter, the TWA Dome announcer leaned into
the microphone and when he gave the score his deep voice sounded
like the voice of God delivering an answered prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Miami 49, UCLA 45.
</P>
<P>
   Lordy, you should have heard the cheers. Kansas State fans
hugged. They jumped up and down as if on pogo sticks. They shrieked
with joy. This town hasn't heard such noise since Mark McGwire hit
No. 70.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's late collapse which knocked Arizona out of the Rose Bowl
helped clarify a muddled title picture. There no longer were three
unbeaten teams. K-State would be returning to Tempe to play (fill
in the blank) in the Fiesta Bowl assuming the 11-0 Wildcats put
away underdog Texas A&AMP;M and the explosive 'Cats were in command,
leading 17-3. Purple-clad fans had cell phones pressed to their
ears, calling Valley hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is certain in college football this year _ not a
lead, or a BCS ranking.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M fought back, pushing K-State into overtime. Then Wildcat
faithful watched in horror as a young squire named Sirr Parker
caught a short pass _ oh no _ slipped a tackle, stiff-armed a
K-State defender _ stop him! _ and kept churning until he covered
32 yards and stretched his body across the goal line. Touchdown.
A&AMP;M, 36-33.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was over. K-State's undefeated season. It's 19-game
winning streak. Its national championship dream.
</P>
<P>
   As stunned Wildcat players wandered off the field, their fans
glum to their shoelaces, the college football world scratched its
head and asked, ````Now'' what?''
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back upsets created what what is akin to a national
crisis in which the president and vice president are unable to
serve. Who is next in line? The speaker-elect of the house? Who is
college football's Bob Livingston _ according to the Bowl
Championship Series?
</P>
<P>
   Florida State?
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, but we won't know for sure until the math whizzes
log on to the BCS computer and and begin crunching the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. Probably. Maybe. The BCS is a hopelessly complex
formula that weighs a Heinz variety of factors and assesses a
numerical rating to each of the nation's top teams.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to figure it out one afternoon and got a nosebleed.
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA, K-State and Tennessee had won Saturday the situation
would have been similar to three unbeaten horses crossing the
finish line at Churchill Downs simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   If the NCAA ran horse racing, it would compare the animals'
blood lines, schedules, opponents' schedules, margins of victory,
jockey and thoroughbred writers polls, the ``Daily Racing Form''
power rating and then announce that War Admiral and Gallant Fox
qualify for a run-off with the winner being named the Tostitos
Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the third horse, Yougottabekiddin, is eliminated, the
victim of a low sperm count index.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee went into the final week of the season ranked No. 1 in
the BCS with a 4.99 rating. UCLA was at 5.03. K-State 6.31. We
accept these numbers without question just as we accept as fact the
calculated distance between Earth and Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the numbers will change again. Florida State may climb
from fourth to second in the ratings, perhaps by a fraction of a
point. The scoring is like Olympic rhythmic gymastics.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sagarin, whose power rating is one of the criteria used by
the BCS, predicted a ``huge bombshell is going to hit this
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The MIT grad was right, although the bomb he spoke of wasn't the
one A&AMP;M dropped. Sagarin had done the math and announced that if
the Wildcats won they would move up from third to first in the BCS
rankings, for the first time, and qualify for the big game.
</P>
<P>
   But K-State never was a Fiesta Bowl team according to my pocket
calculator. The Wildcats' early season schedule was too easy. Bill
Snyder's team played Northeast Louisiana and Northern Illinois and
the Division I-AA Indiana State Sycamores. The Wildcats managed to
beat them, 201-14.
</P>
<P>
   K-State should have saved one of those touchdowns for the
overtime in the Big 12 championship game. But as they say around
the BCS, hindsight is 20.062/20.017. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
