<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5164 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-BICKLEY-AZR &LR;      12-06 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMATOSE BRUINS DON'T DESERVE SHOT AT FIESTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI - Even if they prevailed, even if their quarterback
provided another miracle and the winning streak continued to mask
the odor, any computer worth its gigabytes would've spit them out
like a cheap virus.
</P>
<P>
   When you reduce college football to decimal points, there is no
room for a team that gives up 689 yards to a second-tier outfit.
That surrenders a 38-21 lead with the Fiesta Bowl on the line. That
has two weeks to prepare and allows a running back named Edgerrin
to scamper for 299 yards.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA does not deserve to play for a national championship. Thank
the Bruins for ending the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't play good defense, you don't deserve to be a
national champion,'' UCLA Coach Bob Toledo said. ``You've got to
stop somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins couldn't cover or tackle or produce one defensive
stand. They couldn't provide one glimmer of competence, one reason
to believe they were worthy of the crown. In fact, UCLA's defense
accomplished only one thing on a stunning afternoon in the tropics:
</P>
<P>
   They stopped Arizona from going to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for Pasadena and Wisconsin's Ron Dayne, the
Bruins will now practice in the middle of the Los Angeles freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to beat Wisconsin,'' Bruins lineman Brad Melsby
promised.
</P>
<P>
   As Miami celebrated a truly wonderful victory, a game that
rekindled all the magic the Orange Bowl once held, the Bruins were
in ruins. Inside the loser's locker room, boxes of uneaten pizza
were stacked on tables. Heads were buried in hands. Numbness was
setting in.
</P>
<P>
   There is cruel irony in all of this. If not for the BCS, UCLA
never would have agreed to make up this game, a September match-up
canceled by hurricane. But to argue that Miami would've been more
vulnerable then is both futile and erroneous. The Hurricanes
already were locked into a bowl entering Saturday's skirmish, and
fresh off a 53-point loss to Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was David vs. Goliath,'' Miami's Derrick Hamm said. ``And
God came through for David again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, no slingshots necessary. There was no Goliath on this
field, and the Bruins knew it.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they knew they were stretching their destiny. They
had escaped once too often, their salvation tree plucked bare. And
when asked if he felt comfortable with a 17-point lead in the
second half, offensive lineman Andy Meyers was shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you watching the same game I was watching?'' he asked.
``The way our defense was playing, I wouldn't have been comfortable
if we were up 48.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly the stuff of champions.
</P>
<P>
   For too long, UCLA has been a one-trick pony, riding its
thrill-seeking quarterback on a 20-game odyssey. McNown was
brilliant as usual on Saturday, from the subtleties of his footwork
to passes that hit nearly every receiver in stride. He is as good
as it gets in college football, worthy of the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   McNown deserved a lot more than what he got, which was no
support and a face full of pepper spray as he left the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great shot at the national title,'' McNown said. ``We
did everything we could, especially offensively. It hurts deeply. I
hate to see the guys in a somber mood.''
</P>
<P>
   John Junker, executive director of the Fiesta Bowl, was in the
air when this all happened. He left the Orange Bowl with UCLA ahead
and surging. He landed in Atlanta with only two unbeaten teams
vying for the big prize.
</P>
<P>
   This is good for Valley hotel owners, who wouldn't have seen a
dime from UCLA's commuter fan base. This is good for the Fiesta
Bowl, which can claim a national champion without a third party
screaming to the heavens. But this is not necessarily good for
college football.
</P>
<P>
   Every year the BCS works is another year removed from a
much-needed playoff format.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be worse things for college football than being on
the front page of the sports section every day for the past two
weeks,'' Junker said.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, at least the Fiesta Bowl will be spared the paper
tigers from UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if they can only import McNown as designated quarterback.
For both sides. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
