<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-GIANTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSEL FACTOR PLAYS HAVOC WITH CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Against the Cardinals, they look like the 1985
Chicago Bears, the Pittsburgh Steelers of the 1970s, Vince
Lombardi's Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants, coached by former Cardinals offensive
coordinator Jim Fassel, can do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In three victories over the Cardinals the past two years, the
Giants have been unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   They've outscored the Cardinals, 80-30.
</P>
<P>
   They have gained 1,189 yards to the Cardinals' 828.
</P>
<P>
   They have run for 581 yards to the Cardinals' 138.
</P>
<P>
   They are plus-3 in turnover ratio.
</P>
<P>
   They have 21 sacks to the Cardinals' 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of hearing about it,'' Cardinals quarterback Jake
Plummer said. ``I've been here two years, and they've beaten us
pretty good every time I've played against them. It's something I
want to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   A loss to the Giants (4-8) today at Sun Devil Stadium would mean
the Cardinals (6-6) were swept by a team under .500, one that has
lost four of five games, two by a combined score of 68-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like it what has happened with the Giants the last
couple of years,'' Cardinals center Aaron Graham said. ``It's up to
us to respond and find a way to beat them. He (Fassel) has had our
number. I think we'll dig down deep and figure him out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are trying to make the playoffs for the first time
in a non-strike year since 1975. The Giants are trying to finish
respectably.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many stakes on the table,'' Cardinals defensive
end Simeon Rice said. ``We've got to get it done. We're trying to
get our game together for postseason play. (The Giants) are trying
to get things together for memorable moments.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants beat the Cardinals, 34-7, at Giants Stadium,
Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin and his staff caught a lot of flak from
fans for being ``outcoached'' by Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, who hired Fassel three years ago and has remained friends
with him, thinks the Giants' players deserve credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's overblown,'' Cardinals defensive coordinator
Dave McGinnis said of Fassel's influence. ``They've just
executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said players win games; it's a coach's job to get players
in the best position to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't played well against the Giants,'' Tobin said. ``We
haven't controlled the line of scrimmage. We haven't been able to
run the ball or stop the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players think that Fassel has an advantage in that he
is familiar with their talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has seen our players,'' Cardinals fullback Larry Centers
said. ``He has watched them in practice. He has a feel for what
certain players' weaknesses are.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cardinals quarterback Coach Geep Chryst points out that
Plummer, running backs Adrian Murrell and Mario Bates and guards
Chris Dishman and Lester Holmes weren't with the team when Fassel
was coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say Jim knows everything about this team, but we have a
lot of players Jim never was around,'' Chryst said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel doesn't think he has the Cardinals figured out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we played them, we played a very good game,''
Fassel said. ``We've been fortunate. We've played well against
them. I don't think there's anything (special).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't know any more how to read (the Cardinals) than you
guys (reporters) would. From my standpoint, this is like any game.
We work hard to prepare, to put the game plan together and then the
bottom line is go out and execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel isn't the only former Cardinal coach on the Giants staff.
Offensive coordinator Jim Skipper was Arizona's running backs coach
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Giants starting quarterback Kent Graham was with the Cardinals
the past two years. But Cardinals backup quarterback Dave Brown
came from the Giants in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team is more hung up about playing the Giants
because the Giants dominated in the past,'' Brown said. ``But to
the Giants, this is just another game. They play loose, and it
shows up. They go out and have fun and have won the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, I think this team gets so hyped up because we're
playing the Giants. Maybe it's paralysis by analysis, and we don't
play as well. We played our worst game of the year there this
season. So the Giants are a big hurdle for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' biggest problem in previous games is stopping New
York's rushing attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants ran for 239 yards at Sun Devil Stadium last season,
their most since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just knowing what they think about our defensive line is
enough motivation,'' strong safety Tommy Bennett said. ``The Giants
question our defensive line and whether we can play against the
run. I think our defensive line is going to play really well
(today).''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants will be going against a Cardinals defense that will
be minus three starters _ tackle Eric Swann (knee), middle
linebacker Ronald McKinnon (knee) and cornerback Tom Knight
(hamstring). It's the worst physical shape the defense has been in
all season.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players say they won't use injuries as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is essential for us, regardless of who is out there,
regardless of who is hurt,'' Rice said. ``If we fall (today), we
fall hard. You always want your destiny in your hands. In order for
it to be in our hands, we have to take it. We want to run the table
to make the playoffs. We don't want to make the playoffs by it just
falling in our laps.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer thinks the Cardinals have to play one of their most
physical games in order to finally beat the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to come and be the physical team and make them react
to us,'' Plummer said. ``We have to fight force with force, be the
stronger team, the faster team, the hardest-hitting team. We have
to show them we're not going back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't worry about what's happened in the past. We're about
the future now. We're worried about this one.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
