<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLASIDE-LADN </SLUG>
 
McNOWN COULDN'T DO IT ALL 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Punt, pass, run, block, catch.
</P>
<P>
   Cade McNown has done whatever has been asked of him in his four
seasons at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somebody should have asked him to play defense.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA quarterback had the best day of his career Saturday,
completing 26 of 35 passes for a school-record 513 yards, tying his
own record with five touchdown passes and running for the Bruins'
other touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   And, yet, it was also the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to two key fourth-quarter fumbles and a defense that
looked as if it would struggle to stop Poly High, McNown's
performance wasn't enough to prevent UCLA's national championship
hopes from evaporating in a 49-45 loss before 46,819 at the Orange
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   There were no tears or thrown helmets from McNown afterward. It
was hard, however, to mask the disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   McNown was polite, but feisty before a group of 20 reporters
outside the UCLA locker room. It was also clear that he wondered
why more of the Bruins weren't like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating,'' McNown said. ``I mean, we did everything
we could offensively. We made a lot of plays, we put up 45 points _
not off turnovers, but off driving the football and making plays. I
don't want to go out of a national championship race this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran up and down the field. We dictated the momentum on
offense. It wasn't even close. It was a joke. We rolled on 'em.
What more can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   McNown, who criticized his receivers after he passed poorly
against Arizona, was easier on Brad Melsby and Brian Poli-Dixon,
who lost fourth-quarter fumbles fighting for extra yardage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember to get down and really tuck the ball
away,'' said McNown. ``When you make moves, there's going to be a
backside trailer. (The fumbles) played a part in it, but we still
put up 45 points.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown had maintained all season that he only cared to win the
Heisman Trophy if it was a byproduct of the team's success. Indeed,
he played well mostly when the Bruins needed him and they happened
to need him all day Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played like a first-round draft choice,'' said offensive
coordinator Al Borges. ``It certainly wasn't his fault. I think he
threw one bad ball the whole day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He made plays just like he's made all year,'' guard Andy
Meyers said. ``He's a playmaker and a leader. He led us with pride
and with honor, but he finally lost a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown threw touchdown passes of 77 yards to Danny Farmer, 7 and
61 yards to Poli-Dixon and a 59-yard score to Melsby. The Bruins,
facing third-and-goal at the 1-yard-line midway through the fourth
period, put the ball in McNown's hands again.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the ball on an option play and beat strong safety Edward
Reed to the corner flag for a touchdown that put the Bruins ahead
45-35 with 5:40 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew unless we scored every time we got the ball, it was
still going to be tight,'' McNown said. ``Every time they got the
ball, just about every time they scored a touchdown. We knew if the
ball was in their hands, they were going to score.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown, who led the Bruins to fourth-quarter comebacks against
Oregon State and Stanford, had a chance to do it again after
Cheyane Caldwell returned the kickoff 24 yards to the UCLA 45 with
50 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-yard swing pass to DeShaun Foster got the ball to the Miami
43 with 42 seconds left. A hook-and-lateral play with Melsby and
Foster moved it to the Miami 37 with 24 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But McNown was forced to scramble for 3 yards, nearly had his
pass intercepted by linebacker Dan Morgan and then on the final
play, his Hail Mary pass into the end zone for backup quarterback
Drew Bennett was knocked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a pretty good chance,'' McNown said. ``We
almost got that last pass in the end zone. They got a lot of breaks
today and we suffered quite a bit. We didn't get so many.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami players, coaches and fans stormed the field as if they'd
won the national championship. McNown made his way through the maze
and said some Miami fans dumped pepper spray on him as he headed up
the tunnel to UCLA's locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to take this if you get real emotional,'' McNown
said. ``I don't get too high or too low. You have to stand back and
say we gave it a great shot but there's nothing we could do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
