<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-SOMERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULMER PULLS VOLS TOGETHER FOR WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
Tennessee 24, Mississippi State 14 
COACH Coach pulls Tennessee together for win 
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - There is nothing like an autumn Saturday in the South
to prove that not all of America has relaxed its grip on what is
important, like the proper way to cook greens, or how to address
your elders, or the importance of college football.
</P>
<P>
   Down here, some coaches still wear ties on the sidelines. State
troopers still escort coaches on and off the field. Fans aren't
embarrassed to ring cow bells or sing corny songs whenever the mood
hits, which is often. And players can actually tackle.
</P>
<P>
   So it's fitting that of the three undefeated teams that played
Saturday, only one, Tennessee, remained that way. The No. 1-ranked
Volunteers didn't do anything flashy but they were good enough to
beat Mississippi State, 24-14, in the SEC Championship game in the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Volunteers talked about not following in
the footsteps of UCLA or Kansas State, which were upset Saturday.
``Like (linebacker Al Wilson) said before the game, we're not
Kansas State, we're not UCLA,'' said receiver Peerless Price. ``We
control our destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers (12-0) are assured a spot in the Fiesta Bowl,
Jan. 4, and will find out their opponent today when results of the
Bowl Championship Series standings are announced.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a dream season for the Volunteers, who weren't
expected to do much after the loss of quarterback Peyton Manning,
the NFL's top draft choice. And when the Volunteers lost their best
running back, Jamal Lewis, to a knee injury in the fourth game,
their chances of playing for their first national title since 1951
seemed dismal.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers credit their coach, Phillip Fulmer, for holding
them together. He is an unlikely hero. Rumpled, overweight and with
a terminal lack of glibness, Fulmer doesn't look the part. But he
leads. Sure, not the way Mississippi State coach Jackie Sherrill
does. Sherrill, after all, once had a bull castrated to get his
Bulldogs ready to play Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And after Mississippi State upset Arkansas late this season,
Sherrill sat in his office chair, rubbing two Razorbacks' tusks
together in his hand. Got them in Texas a few years back, Sherrill
said, after shooting a Razorback from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer spins no such yarns. He's a regular guy, who, if he were
your neighbor, you wouldn't think twice about loaning him a power
tool.
</P>
<P>
   After last week's victory over Vanderbilt, Fulmer, his wife and
three daughters drove the three hours from Nashville to Knoxville.
They enjoyed the family time, stopping at a Cracker Barrel
restaurant along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer, ever the adventurer, had the meatloaf.
</P>
<P>
   Calmly, he has led this team week-by-week. Finally beating
Florida. Overcoming Lewis's injury. Nuturing quarterback Tee Martin
through growing pains. He never let the pressures of coaching at
Tennessee, where over 100,000 ``Rocky Top`` singing fans show up
for every home game, get to him.
</P>
<P>
   In his own way, Sherrill also did a remarkable job this season.
The Bulldogs have no stars, Sherrill is quick to point out, and he
claims not one of his defensive starters will ever be drafted.
</P>
<P>
   That's debatable. But what the Bulldogs, as well as the
Volunteers, will do is knock you into next week. Ball carriers who
cared to dance in Saturday's game paid a painful price.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the SEC office had banned missed tackles, along
with the cowbells that Mississippi State fans love to clang.
</P>
<P>
   That's why SEC football is better than the Pac-10, where defense
has gone the way of the Anasazi.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 this year might as well of been the Big Sky
Conference. Scores were astronomical. Offenses gorged themselves.
At least now we know what happened to track and field. The season
was moved to the fall.
</P>
<P>
   When the league's best team, UCLA, gives up 49 points to
unranked Miami, there are problems.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC title game was a stark contrast. Tennessee's defense
gave up nothing. Mississippi State scored on a 70-yard interception
return and an 83-yard punt return.
</P>
<P>
   The mark of the best teams is how they react when they're down.
When the Bulldogs went ahead, 14-10, in the fourth quarter, the
Vols were tough enough to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who struggled most of the night, found Price for a
41-yard touchdown. The defense forced a fumble and Martin tossed
another touchdown pass. In less than three minutes, the Volunteers
were ahead, 24-14, their trip to the Fiesta Bowl confirmed against
an as of yet faceless opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Only 35,000 or so their fans will follow. If you don't know the
words to ``Rocky Top,'' they won't be hard to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's like ``Boomer Sooner,'''' said John Junker,
Fiesta Bowl executive director. ``It just repeats itself. Although
I think there is a `Good ole` in there somewhere.''  &QL; 
Kent Somers can be reached at 602-444_8335 or at
kent.somers(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
