<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA STATE SITTING PRETTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Now it's up to the computers. But not the way everyone
figured. After weeks of mashing of the Bowl Championship Series
rankings of undefeated Kansas State, UCLA, and Tennessee, a new set
of problems developed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   How to differentiate between one-loss teams.
</P>
<P>
   With No. 3 UCLA and No. 2 Kansas State each losing Saturday, the
BCS rankings that will determine who plays in the Fiesta Bowl for
the national championship now must produce a winner between
one-loss teams such as Florida State and Ohio State, each of whom
thought they needed a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   What happened Saturday was as bizarre as it was dramatic. UCLA
began the day with a stunning 49-45 loss to Miami in the Orange
Bowl in a game that was not decided until the final play.
</P>
<P>
   That effectively knocked the Bruins out of the Fiesta Bowl and
into the Rose Bowl, where they are likely to play Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Big 12 championship game in St. Louis. Knowing
that UCLA had lost, all Kansas State had to do was beat Texas A&AMP;M
to get to the Fiesta. With a 27-12 lead in the fourth quarter, it
seemed the Wildcats were doing that.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aggies came back, forcing the game into overtime and
winning with a controversial touchdown in the second OT, 36-33.
</P>
<P>
   That loss could and probably will be devastating to the
Wildcats, who are likely to fall behind Ohio State and Florida
State in the BCS rankings and now could be headed to the Sugar
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State now appears to be in the Fiesta to face Tennessee,
which hung on to defeat Mississippi State, 24-14, in the SEC title
game Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The other BCS bowl matchups were also in doubt. Texas A&AMP;M is in
the BCS and most likely will get a Sugar bid, possibly vs. Ohio
State, while Syracuse was most likely in the Orange, possibly vs.
Florida. But most everything was on hold until Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 0105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5179 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-KANSAS-     12-06 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-KANSAS-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, SIRR, AGGIES STUN KANSAS STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Sirr Parker's headlong dive clipped the end-zone
pylon, touching off the deepest dogpile of maroon-clad football
players in the three-year history of the Big 12 conference.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's touchdown in the second overtime of yesterday's league
title game culminated a furious comeback that saw Texas A&AMP;M stun
Kansas State, 36-33, behind the 11th-hour magic of a backup
tailback and a backup quarterback who spent most of their senior
seasons in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker and Branndon Stewart were front and center during
crunch time in the Trans World Dome. They hooked up on the
game-tying touchdown and two-point conversion with 1:05 remaining
in regulation, as well as the game-winning, 32-yard strike in
overtime that allowed A&AMP;M (11-2) to win the Big 12 title and ended
the national championship dreams of Kansas State (11-1).
</P>
<P>
   With the triumph, the Aggies, ranked 10th in The Associated
Press poll, landed a berth in the Bowl Championship Series and will
play in either the Jan. 1 Sugar Bowl or the Jan. 2 Orange Bowl. A
likely scenario has A&AMP;M playing No. 5 Ohio State in the Sugar Bowl,
but the bowl pairings will not be finalized until today.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M players cared little about their postseason destination last
night as they mobbed Parker, who turned a short slant pattern into
a game-winning touchdown pass on a third-and-17 play that allowed
the Aggies to win as 14-point underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the best feelings in the world, until the guys
started yelling and taking away my oxygen,'' Parker said of the
postgame pile of happy, hugging humanity. ``This shows Aggies don't
ever give up fighting. When the clock says `zero,' we're still
fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, A&AMP;M never led yesterday's game until after the
fourth-quarter clock showed 0:00. A&AMP;M took a 30-27 lead on Russell
Bynum's 18-yard field goal in the first overtime, but watched
Kansas State kicker Martin Gramatica answer with a 22-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   Another Gramatica field goal opened the second overtime, but A&AMP;M
answered with the slant pattern heard 'round the BCS rankings.
Suddenly, a team that managed just 173 yards in last week's 26-24
loss to Texas had exploded for 452 yards (6.3 per play) and 25
first downs against the nation's No. 2 defense.
</P>
<P>
   A team that trailed, 27-12, at the start of the fourth quarter
had rallied behind Stewart, who threw for 235 yards, three
touchdowns and a pivotal two-point conversion in the fourth quarter
and overtime. Stewart, a Stephenville native who was replaced in
the starting lineup Oct. 3, threw for a season-high 324 yards as an
emergency replacement for the injured Randy McCown (broken
collarbone).
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M began its comeback with a 10-play, 78-yard touchdown drive
that ended with Stewart hitting Leroy Hodge for 13 yards to trim
the deficit to 27-19. With Kansas State attempting to run out the
clock, linebacker Warrick Holdman knocked the ball loose from
Wildcats quarterback Michael Bishop (442 yards total offense) with
2:26 remaining and Cornelius Anthony recovered at the Wildcats'
35-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Four plays later, Stewart hit Parker for a 9-yard scoring toss,
then followed with a two-point conversion pass to Parker to tie the
game, 27-27, and set up the duo's additional heroics in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be another Big 12 comeback to match
this one for a long time,'' Stewart said. ``All week, people were
saying, `The Aggies don't have the offense. The Aggies don't have
the passing game. The Aggies can't do this. The Aggies can't to
that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I got sick of hearing it. We're Big 12 champs.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they are. And, by beating a Kansas State team ranked No.
1 in the coaches' poll, A&AMP;M defeated a top-ranked opponent for the
first time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph was sweet, said A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum, but proved
even sweeter because of the prominent roles played by Stewart and
Parker (3 catches, 49 yards, 2 TDs).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fitting the two stars of this game are guys that have
been in the background most of the year but have had a lot to do
with this team's success,'' Slocum said. ``A lot of times, guys can
become disruptive if they don't play as much as they'd hoped,
especially in their senior year. But these guys have handled it
with class. I couldn't be more pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State players, on the other hand, could not have been
more disappointed. After the game, linebacker Jeff Kelly and
tailback Eric Hickson wept while sitting at the interview dais.
Kansas State coach Bill Snyder described it as the most painful
loss of his career, likening it to a death in the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous setback,'' said Snyder, whose team would
have played No. 1 Tennessee in the Jan. 4 Fiesta Bowl for the
national championship if the Wildcats, No. 3 in the BCS rankings,
had won. ``A&AMP;M played extremely well in all facets. They didn't
miss a beat with Branndon Stewart in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Stewart miss an open receiver when the game was decided
during the fourth quarter and overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for Branndon and for me,'' Parker said. ``They say
it's not how you start, but how you finish. And we finished
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong enough to give A&AMP;M its first Big 12 championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
