<HEADER>
A5181 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-MISS.-S     12-06 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-MISS.-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURPRISES HERE: TENNESSEE WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It might have capped a nasty little trifecta that
would have produced shrieks of horror from wherever the minions of
the Bowl Championship Series are holed up at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   But irony, it seems, can travel only so far in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Tennessee (12-0) managed to avoid the fate of its
fellow front-runners in the BCS standings yesterday _ striking
suddenly in the fourth quarter to defeat Mississippi State, 24-14,
in the Southeastern Conference title game in front of the
second-largest crowd (74,795) in the history of the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't worried about what happened to those other two,''
said Vols receiver Peerless Price, who caught the game-winning
touchdown pass. ``We said in the locker room beforehand, we're not
UCLA, and we're not Kansas State. We've got our own job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs (8-4) almost parlayed a gritty defense and two long
returns of a punt and an interception into the third upset of the
day. But in the end, the Vols scored twice within 28 seconds to win
the door prize.
</P>
<P>
   When Kevin Prentiss sailed 83 yards on a punt return for a 14-10
MSU lead with 8:43 remaining, the 'Dogs seemed to have fate on
their side.
</P>
<P>
   But the Vols, awakened, struck back quickly with a 75-yard drive
capped by a 41-yard scoring toss from Tee Martin to Price with 6:15
left.
</P>
<P>
   Living up to his name, Price caught the ball deep in the end
zone over backup cornerback Adesola Badon, just inserted into the
game in place of injured starter Kendall Roberson.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols then recovered a fumble at the MSU 26, and on the first
snap, Martin passed to a wide-open Cedrick Wilson in the end zone.
Finally, the 'Dogs were finished.
</P>
<P>
   The winning touchdown pass _ ``X-Takeoff'' _ was slightly
modified, Price said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the huddle,'' he said, ``Tee just said, `Peerless, I'm just
gonna throw it out there, and you've got to run out and get it. I'm
gonna throw early, because they're comin' in fast and hitting me,
so be ready.'''
</P>
<P>
   Vols coach Phillip Fullmer laughed about the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played a great defensive game against us, and we were
struggling,'' he said. ``Usually in that situation, our plan is to
just throw it out there somewhere around Peerless and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the sudden swing, Bulldogs coach Jackie Sherrill said, ``I
didn't really feel like we had the momentum \Rafter the punt
return\S because we weren't executing our offense. No question, it
was a tough defensive game for both teams _ and our defense
probably played as well as it can. But we couldn't execute the
third down on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come in here to spoil someone else's season. We came
here to win a championship, and we almost did.''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams sparred their way to within five seconds of a
scoreless first quarter, until an electrifying and confusing play
broke the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   From the Tennessee 18, Martin tried to go deep to Price, who was
shadowed by MSU's Robert Bean.
</P>
<P>
   As the ball descended, flags flew as the duo jostled for
possession. Bean slickly made the interception at the Bulldogs' 30
and turned back upfield as Price was both grounded and flagged for
interference.
</P>
<P>
   Bean eventually completed a meandering 70-yard scoring run as
the Vols gave halfhearted pursuit, some obviously thinking the play
had been blown dead.
</P>
<P>
   Another penalty at the goal line forced MSU's Brian Hazelwood to
kick a 35-yard extra point, but the 'Dogs were up, 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   The favor was returned in the second quarter when MSU
quarterback Wayne Madkin, pressured, lofted a weak pass that
Tennessee's Deon Grant picked off and returned 24 yards to the
'Dogs' 20. Travis Stephens dove over the stack to cap the short
drive, and the score was tied.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols then launched a drive from their 32 that reached the
MSU 7 before the Bulldogs pushed the attackers back to the 14. Jeff
Hall's 31-yard field goal gave UT a 10-7 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the third quarter, Tennessee's Al Wilson picked
off a Madkin pass and apparently took it 42 yards into the end
zone, but a penalty wiped out most of the return. Two plays later,
Travis Henry fumbled the ball back to the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols clung to the three-point lead until 8:43 remained in
the game _ when the 'Dogs suddenly struck again without snapping
the ball. Taking a punt at his 17, Prentiss moved quickly to the
sideline, turned upfield, and raced 83 yards untouched for a 14-10
MSU lead.
Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Former TCU coach Pat Sullivan was among the SEC Legends (one per
school) introduced at the start of the game. Richmond Flowers,
representing Tennessee, received a big cheer from Vols fans, but
they reserved their loudest ovation for onetime Ole Miss star
Archie Manning, father of Peyton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
