r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOWLS-PICTURE-TEX     12-06 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-PICTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA STATE MAY GET WISH AS TWO OUT OF THREE GO BAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UCLA's loss was TCU's gain. Kansas State's loss was Florida
State's gain. And Mississippi State's loss was Tennessee's and the
Bowl Championship Series' gain.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most exciting, upsetting and bowl-shifting days in
college football history ended yesterday with the national
championship picture drawn, erased and redrawn. The results might
have vaulted TCU into the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But TCU's out-of-the-blue bowl hopes were just part of a day of
incredible mood swings.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had the nation's longest winning streak at 20 games, but
couldn't hold a 17-point lead against Miami. Kansas State, which
inherited the longest winning streak (19 games), couldn't hold a
15-point lead against Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Tennessee needed 14 fourth-quarter points to rally past
Mississippi State in the Southeastern Conference championship game,
24-14. The victory assured the Volunteers a place in the national
championship game, the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's opponent will be determined today when the Bowl
Championship Series announces its final computer-generated
rankings. The remaining bowl pairings also will be announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State, No. 4 in last week's Bowl Championship Series
rankings, is expected to move up to No. 2 in both polls. If the
Seminoles have enough support in the BCS' computer programs, they
could wind up playing the Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can mess it up now, can they?'' Florida State coach
Bobby Bowden told The Associated Press after the Aggies' upset of
Kansas State. ``I mean nobody behind us can go ahead of us,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   That can be answered only by the computers. Three teams with one
loss _ UCLA, Kansas State and Ohio State _ all will hope that the
numbers add up in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   The day started with three undefeated teams _ Tennessee, UCLA
and Kansas State _ atop the BCS computer standings. UCLA's 49-45
shootout loss at UCLA and Kansas State's 36-33 double-overtime loss
to Texas A&AMP;M in the Big 12 Conference championship game probably
ended the championship hopes of the Bruins and the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Champions from the Big 12, Big Ten, Big East, Atlantic Coast,
Southeastern and Pacific-10 conferences are assured spots in the
four BCS bowls. The other two teams are at-large selections.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the probable matchups in the four BCS games: Fiesta _
Tennessee (SEC champ) vs. Florida State (ACC champ). Orange _ Texas
A&AMP;M (Big 12 champ) vs. Syracuse (Big East champ). Rose _ UCLA
(Pac-10 champ) vs. Wisconsin (Big Ten champ). Sugar _ Kansas State
(at large) vs. Ohio State (at large).
</P>
<P>
   BCS bowls pay out between $12 million to $14 million. Had UCLA
won, Arizona would have played in the Rose Bowl. That means the
Bruins' loss cost the Pac-10 a big BCS payday.
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas State and Ohio State earn at-large bids, the Big 12
and Big Ten will each earn double-their-pleasure paydays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
