<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-OKLAHOMASTAT     12-06 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-OKLAHOMASTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNOVERS KEY TO UCLA VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ They saw their football counterparts surrender
49 points to Miami, and vowed a UCLA team would not make the same
mistake twice Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball Bruins, drawing inspiration from the football
team's demise, decided that success comes only with reliable
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw them play and they didn't play much defense,'' Bruins
forward Travis Reed said of UCLA's football performance in its loss
to Miami. ``Through the season, they didn't play much defense and
it finally caught up with them. We decided that we've got to play
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, however devastating to the football team's national
championship aspirations, got through better than any lectures from
coach Steve Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th-ranked Bruins forced Oklahoma State into 25 turnovers
and defeated the 11th-ranked Cowboys 69-66 at the Wooden Classic
before an announced crowd of 14,237 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``To force an Eddie Sutton team into 25 turnovers is like
forcing a Vince Lombardi team into 12 turnovers,''' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a little farfetched, but the Oklahoma State coach
conceded it was the most turnovers one of his Cowboy teams has
surrendered in eight-plus seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a lot of them were forced,'' Sutton said. ``It
seemed like we were nervous. It wasn't a good game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's defense really became a factor down the stretch, as point
guard Baron Davis made two of the biggest plays of the game. With
UCLA ahead, 67-63, Cowboys guard Adrian Peterson drove to the
basket, but Davis stole the ball and went for a layup at the other
end.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys cut the lead back to three points (69-66) and had
one final chance to send the game into overtime. But Davis blocked
Joe Adkins' 3-point attempt with four seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a top team, you have to put people away defensively,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he should be UCLA's defensive coordinator next season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was his usual dominating presence despite playing in just
his second game after tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in his
left knee last March.
</P>
<P>
   He made his first start of the year, played a season-high 19
minutes, and had seven points and three steals, plus those two
influential defensive stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baron is probably farther along than I would have imagined,''
Lavin said. ``He's a very strong player mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis also deserved an assist for influencing the outcome of the
contest. He received an elbow from Oklahoma State point guard Doug
Gottleib at the end of the first half, which resulted in a
technical foul and Gottleib's ejection because he drew a technical
earlier in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Cowboys without their playmaker and leading
assist-man (9.4 per game) for the final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baron ran up to me like he was going to run into me,''
Gottleib said. ``I did elbow him, but he flopped over. With about
eight minutes left before the second half, the ref came in (to the
locker room) and said I was ejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis admitted he took a dive, but said the elbow he received
was real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I scored a layup and ran back. I didn't say anything to
(Gottleib),'' Davis said. ``He hit me in the stomach. I saw it
coming. I flopped a little bit but it hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (4-2) also got some nice efforts from forward Jerome
Moiso (13 points, seven rebounds) and guard Earl Watson (14 points,
six assists, five rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   Although the final margin was close, the Bruins had a 64-49 lead
with 7:28 left, and also enjoyed a 14-point advantage in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   But each time it appeared UCLA would rout the Cowboys, Oklahoma
State (4-2) got back into the game with 3-point shooting. Half of
Oklahoma State's field goals (12) were 3-pointers. The Cowboys shot
45 percent from beyond the 3-point arc, but made just 36 percent of
their two-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Just another example of the Bruins' tight defense.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said UCLA had no problems remembering to improve its
defense, with the visual aid they received watching television
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you see it, it's easier to remember,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 0114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
