<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5187 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     12-06 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELY ON HEART, NOT THE ODDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The computers were powerless yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Tears flowed. Hearts plummeted and soared.
</P>
<P>
   For the Kansas State Wildcats, one step away from the game of
their lifetimes, it proved to be a night that they would never
forget.
</P>
<P>
   In the horror of their 36-33 double-overtime defeat, the
heretofore unbeaten, unblemished Wildcats could offer no
explanation for what had just happened.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great hearts,'' Slocum said. ``This A&AMP;M team has character.
This team has great heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Overtime can be the cruelest word in college football. When
yesterday's second overtime was over, the Aggies rushed to swarm
the hero of the day, the all-but-once-forgotten Sirr Parker. They
hugged strangers. They hugged each other.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Dat Nguyen's eyes welled with tears as he said:
``This is one of the most special teams that I've ever been around.
We never give up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter of this Big 12 Championship Game, a mighty
roar had gone up in the Trans World Dome when it was announced that
Miami had upset UCLA. The largely purple throng of 60,798 didn't
need the convoluted Bowl Championship Series computers to tell them
what the upset meant.
</P>
<P>
   Finish off the Aggies, and the opportunity to play for No. 1
would be theirs. The Wildcats led, 17-3, when the UCLA score was
announced. From that minute on, the clock never seemed to move fast
enough for K-State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of opportunities,'' Wildcats linebacker Travis
Ochs said. ``But we just couldn't put them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, we held them all day. But we bent and
finally broke. When it got down near the end of the game, it seemed
we couldn't stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Overtime had been a new and chilling experience. In hindsight,
maybe the computers had been on to something. En route to 11-0, the
Wildcats had been downgraded for an allegedly undemanding schedule.
</P>
<P>
   When the Aggies did rise to challenge them in the fourth quarter
yesterday, the Wildcats appeared lost to respond _ especially their
acclaimed defense.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M, on the other hand, kept coming. Ignoring the pregame
predictions. Burying, for a day, the loss to Texas. And oblivious
to the widening shadow that Kansas State was playing under.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic was it that the forgotten quarterback found the
forgotten running back for the touchdown that would decide this
day?
</P>
<P>
   ``People were saying, `The Aggies don't have the offense. The
Aggies don't have the passing game. The Aggies don't have this. The
Aggies don't have that,''' said Branndon Stewart, whose days as an
A&AMP;M quarterback-hero were supposed to be behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of hearing about it. We're Big 12 champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love opportunities to prove people wrong. People say,
`Stewart can't do this. Stewart can't do that.' I love proving them
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Fate had placed Stewart, a senior from Stephenville, in this
game of games. After Randy McCown broke his collarbone, Slocum
called on Stewart, the better passer.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State was ahead by 15 points with 12 minutes left in
regulation. From that point on, Stewart faced seven third-down
situations _ he converted six, gaining 81 yards and scoring two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a story,'' Slocum said of Stewart's day.
</P>
<P>
   Around him on the field, Aggie players still hugged and danced.
At one point, Slocum himself joined a big group that was bouncing
up and down, chanting, ``Gimme some sugar! Whoop! Whoop!''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies, indeed, should expect a phone call from the Sugar
Bowl today.
</P>
<P>
   For Kansas State, the consolation prize didn't seem to matter.
</P>
<P>
   The scene in the formal interview room, with Snyder and four of
his players at the microphones, made even hardened media members
squirm.
</P>
<P>
   Swallowing back tears, Snyder said: ``I have so much pride in
these players. This may be, in their young lives, the most
difficult thing they have had to handle. The pain that comes from
this is because such an emotional investment was made by all these
young people.''
</P>
<P>
   To the coach's left, two players hung their heads and openly
sobbed.
</P>
<P>
   The dream was dashed. No slights that the bowl-system computers
had ever spit out could compare with this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told some of the young guys after the game to remember what
this feels like,'' said ebullient A&AMP;M tight end Dan Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   But no reminders were necessary, of course.
</P>
<P>
   They'll remember. Both sides will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
