<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG-12-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOCUM'S DECISION PAYS OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ In a game filled with monumental decisions, Texas
A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum's biggest came during the first of two
overtimes in the 36-33 victory over Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   With the first possession after the Wildcats won the coin flip
and chose to play defense, A&AMP;M neared the goal line when Branndon
Stewart connected with tight end Dan Spiller for 18 yards to the
Wildcats' 7.
</P>
<P>
   Three plunges by Dante Hall left the Aggies facing
fourth-and-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sorely tempted to try and get the thing in,'' Slocum
said. ``But I knew if we did miss it, they had a great kicker
\RMartin Gramatica\S and would just line up and kick it. I decided
we had to take the three and take the chance we could hold them to
three.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum's decision was correct. Kansas State ended up with the
same decision on fourth-and-goal from the 1 and made the same
choice, sending Gramatica in to tie the game at 30-30 and set up
the final dramatics.
No change from 'Canes
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State coach Bill Snyder and his players said news of
Miami's 49-45 victory over UCLA that could have thrust the Wildcats
into the national championship game did not cause them to play any
differently.
</P>
<P>
   News spread from a fan behind the Wildcats' bench who was
watching on a portable television shortly after quarteback Michael
Bishop threw a 66-yard touchdown pass to Darnell McDonald for a
17-3 Kansas State lead. Moments later, the Trans World Dome
scoreboard flashed the final and Wilcats fans cheered wildly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they announced the score, it didn't have an effect on the
game,'' offensive guard Jeremy Martin said. ``If anything, it gave
us a boost. But we knew we had to come out and take care of
business. We just didn't get it done.''
Loss means much pain
</P>
<P>
   Snyder and his players were tearful during postgame interviews,
talking of national championship dreams likely gone by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pain that comes from this comes from emotional
investment,'' Snyder said. ``The greater the investment, the
greater the pain.''
No repeats for Nguyen
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M linebacker and Lombardi Award finalist Dat Nguyen said
that when the game went into overtime, memories of last week's
failed last stand in the 26-24 loss to Texas flashed through his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in overtime,'' Nguyen recalled, ``I said to the
other guys, `Don't let this one slip away.' We let the game against
Texas slip away, but we did not let it happen again.''
Back to San Antonio?
</P>
<P>
   The Trans World Dome crowd of 60,798 was more than 5,000 shy of
a sellout _ marking the second time the game has failed to sell out
the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's match between A&AMP;M and Nebraska filled the Alamodome
to a capacity crowd of 64,824. That likely means the Big 12 will
vote to comply with an athletic directors' recommendation that the
game return to San Antonio next year.
A $50,000 catch
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Barnes Hoffman, a divorced mother of three who works at
a supermarket in Georgetown, left the Big 12 championship game with
a check that should buy a lot of groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman could have won $1 million in the ``Pepper Punt Payoff''
promotion had she caught three punts. She caught only one, but that
was worth $50,000 and more than enough salve to soothe the numerous
bruises tatooing her arms from a month of catching punts from her
boyfriend _ who was a backup punter on his high school team.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman won her shot at becoming a millionaire by filling out a
form for the Dr Pepper sweepstakes contest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
