<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-PENGUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GET BY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pat Burns had watched his club struggle through 65
minutes Tuesday night, the result a tie with Vancouver. Saturday
night, in a nip-and-tuck 2-1 thriller over the Pittsburgh Penguins,
the Bruins coach again watched his club, after taking a 2-0
first-period lead, hang on for dear life.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins sport an impressive seven-game unbeaten streak
(5-0-2), but the fact is, they haven't played all that well at
times. The problem isn't Boston's effort. It's partly the schedule,
which calls for the Bruins to play just three games in 13 days.
After a matinee against Montreal the day after Thanksgiving, the
Bruins had three days off until the Vancouver game. They had three
more days off until Saturday night's game, and now have four days
off before facing the Hurricanes in Carolina Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Burns believes that was a big factor in his club's trouble
containing the Penguins, who poured 34 shots on Byron Dafoe. The
goalie turned in a remarkable performance, making 17 saves in the
middle period alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saved us there,'' said Burns. ``We weren't very sharp. This
is going to sound funny, but we played like we practiced all week,
with no competition. That's exactly the way we played. A lot of
idle time. I could see when we were attacking with the puck, it was
like we were doing it in practice. Nobody's going to hit you,
nobody's going to whack you, you think it's going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much comes easy, Burns added, against the Penguins. ``They
can probably throw the most talent down below the blue lines,
around the net, than anybody in the league,'' he said. ``But we
found a way to win, and that's the most important thing. When your
goaltender is sharp, you're going to win hockey games. We could
have easily lost the game, very easily. But we hung on, and that's
what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   In their last 12 games, the Bruins are 7-1-4. They went into
Saturday night with a tall order, facing the second-highest-scoring
team in the Eastern Conference and the league's top point-getter,
Jaromir Jagr. Boston countered with the best combined special teams
_ the third-best power play and second-best penalty-killing
percentage _ as well as the second-best goalie tandem in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   When all was said and done, Boston won on the strength of two
first-period goals and outstanding goaltending by Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:48, the Bruins found the net first, as Shawn Bates scored
his first goal of the season. Bates, centering Steve Heinze and
Anson Carter, was in the lineup for the first time since Nov. 19,
when he played against Florida. (He had been scratched for four
games after that and had missed Tuesday's game because of the flu.)
He made his presence known, figuring in both of the Bruins' scores.
Later in the game, however, Bates was used sparingly, because Burns
felt Joe Thornton had more experience.
</P>
<P>
   On the first goal, Dmitri Khristich, positioned behind the net
to the right of goalie Tom Barrasso, dished the puck through the
crease and it bounced off Barrasso's stick. Bates charged into the
crease after the puck, and it caromed off his right skate and into
the cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just going hard to the net,'' said Bates. ``I'll take
them any way they come.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston made it 2-0 at 17:58 on a nice individual effort by
Heinze. After Bates took a hit at center ice to advance the puck
forward, Heinze took it in on a two-on-one break. He blasted a shot
from the left circle that Barrasso stopped. But Heinze picked up
the rebound and chipped it past the netminder for his eighth goal.
Dafoe earned the second assist on the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heinzie gave the puck up to me,'' said Bates. ``I saw the
defense-man coming down, and Heinzie was yelling for the puck, so I
just tried to sideswipe the guy and just lead him and fortunately
it got through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins began unleashing their barrage in the middle
period, outshooting the home team by a whopping 18-6 and pulling
within a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was peppered by Pittsburgh and came up big, save after
save. The only one he didn't stop was Jagr's shot from the slot
that cut the lead in half at 10:55.
</P>
<P>
   From there, as they have so often this year, the Bruins
weathered the storm and walked away gratefully with the win, after
Dafoe made 10 saves in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Thursday, the schedule heats up and the Bruins will
play seven games in 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been tough mentally to get up,'' said Burns, referring
to the layoffs. ``We feel like we're in good physical condition,
which we are because we practiced all week. We're rested; the
injuries aren't there. All of sudden you get into games and you're
flat. That's the tough part.''
</P>
<P>
   When the team gets into the heat of the schedule later in the
month, Burns said he'll likely have the opposite reaction to the
one he has now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' he said, ``I'll say we played too much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
