<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE STANDS UP TO NONSTOP ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Skill is in short supply in today's NHL. Once were the
days when we talked about the Flying Frenchmen of the '50s and
'60s, the great Euro-Oilers of the '80s. Even the Broad Street
Bullies had a few diamonds embedded in their knuckles, as did our
darlings, the Big, Bad Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   For decades the game was full of skate and shoot, great
up-and-down action that kept the crowd engaged, with no need for
high-tech jumboboards or blaring rock music to whip everyone into a
frenzy (the NBA's gift to hockey _ and look where the NBA is this
morning).
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Penguins of '98-99 likely won't win the Stanley
Cup, but they are one of the few teams in the Original 27 that can
do a little something with the puck. They are more than just
Jaromir Jagr, and there are some teams that can't cobble together
the talent of 20 guys to equal his abundance of riches.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins also attack with the likes of Martin Straka and
Alexei Kovalev, Robert Lang and Alexei Morozov. German Titov, once
Dmitri Kvartalnov's running buddy in Russia, also is no slouch in
the attacking zone. All that talent was on display for 60 minutes
Saturday night at the FleetCenter, and it all added up to a 2-1
loss to the Bruins, principally because Boston's greatest skill
level, once again, was embodied in the stick and blocker of
netminder Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a lot of huge saves,'' said Hal Gill, who did what is
becoming his customary job of bailing up the dangerous Jagr, though
Jagr did strike for Pittsburgh's only goal. ``He kept us in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once beyond the first period, which found the Penguins slow to
warm up their legs, the Bruins spent the better part of 40 minutes
in uptempo, firewagon retreat. There were times when Jagr set up
behind Dafoe's net, the puck seemingly tethered to his long stick,
with not one of Boston's five skaters daring to go after him.
Respect in this game is often measured in inches. When Jagr
controls the puck, the standard is stretched to feet, sometimes
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jagr was behind the net, I don't know how many minutes
tonight,'' said Dafoe, who turned away 33 of 34 shots _ 10 of those
saves at the combined expense of Kovalev (6) and Jagr (4). ``That
second period was a little hairy, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins rolled up an 18-6 shot lead in the second, by far
the hardest Dafoe had to work all eve-ning. He blocked a steaming
Kovalev slapper in the early minutes, cut down a difficult,
long-range Jeff Serowik wrister at 6:53. Just before Jagr popped in
the only Pittsburgh goal at 10:55, even Bobby Dollas forced Dafoe
to come up with a sparkling stop. Before the period ended, Jagr
would have another excellent opportunity, nearly connecting for a
shorthanded strike when he turned Darren Van Impe into a
6-foot-1-inch pretzel deep in Boston territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jagr makes every player around him pretty scary,'' said Dafoe.
``And they've got the kind of team that does a lot of passing.
Kovalev (recently acquired from the Rangers in the Peter Nedved
swap) is a strong addition. That's not a dump-and-chase team.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what made Dafoe's eighth win of the year all
the more impressive, and the play of the Penguins so distinct, so
distinguishable. At least 20 teams in the league, including the
Bruins, attack with the puck as if they are connected to the
push-and-pull rods of a hockey board game. If they can break
through the morass of their opponent's neutral zone trap, they'll
do their best to funnel the puck to the middle and hope for an
honest whack or two between the circles. Boston's lone exception to
this, of course, is the Sergei Samsonov-Dmitri Khristich-Jason
Allison combination. But that line faded into anonymity against the
mighty Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably throw the most talented players at you, down
low, around the net, as any team in the league,'' reflected Bruins
head coach Pat Burns. ``They can scare you. You're looking at the
big guy (Jagr) all the time, the way he runs around, but you forget
about Kovalev ... you forget about Titov ... you forget about
Straka ... There are some pretty good hockey players there, and
they can get you into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But only Jagr's wrister would beat Dafoe. The Bruins' surehanded
goalie dropped his goals-against average to a miniscule 1.72 and
boosted his save percentage to a dazzling .940. He is the hottest
hand this town has seen since Pete Peeters was rolling to the
Vezina 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Skill comes in many packages, many styles. Sometimes it is
embodied in the ferocious speed and agility of a powerful forward
like Jagr. Other times it can be found in the rather stationary
posture of a goalie, his lightning reflexes always at the ready.
Saturday night, Dafoe's more subtle science proved the greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he's got a job to do,'' said Boston captain Ray Bourque,
a wry smile crossing his face. ``He came up great, again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 0120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
