<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5194 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-SIDER-T     12-06 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART RESURRECTS AGGIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ After Vickie Stewart finally braved the delirious
celebration of Texas A&AMP;M players and coaches to embrace her son
Branndon in the immediate afterglow of the Aggies' overtime victory
against Kansas State, she reflected on a phone call Branndon made
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that day, Branndon Stewart had learned that he would
start the Big 12 championship game after it was discovered that
Randy McCown had suffered a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Branndon is so low-key,'' Vickie Stewart said. ``He just said
he was going to start on Saturday and that it was all in the Lord's
hands. After all he has been through, he deserves this. I'm so
proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some may point to divine guidance of the passes Stewart threw
late in the 36-33 victory against the Wildcats. But there was no
question that the ball _ and in a sense the game _ was firmly in
the hands of the oft-scorned senior who yesterday may have had his
finest moment of a star-crossed collegiate career in which he twice
lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played with a great deal of character,'' Kansas State coach
Bill Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember ever being this excited after a football
game,'' Stewart said. ``Even after the \RClass 4A\S state
championship \Rat Stephenville in 1993\S. A lot of times in
college, you don't have the same camaraderie you do in high school.
But everyone kept fighting today. And to see the gratification on
everybody's face and to know we fought through it all was really
satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate enough to win this game. And I think we
played better as the game went on.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that Stewart played his finest during crunch
time, when he helped the Aggies rally from a 27-12 deficit with 40
seconds remaining in the third quarter. He completed 11 of 20
passes for 235 yards, three touchdowns and a game-tying two-point
conversion during the fourth quarter and the two overtime periods.
</P>
<P>
   For the game, Stewart was 15-of-31 with one interception _ on a
tipped ball _ for 324 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about Branndon,'' said Sirr Parker, who
scored the game-winning touchdown after taking a perfectly timed
pass from Stewart on a slant pattern. ``He is such a strong person.
We weren't surprised by his performance today at all. We've won a
lot of big games with him before.''
</P>
<P>
   None bigger than this one, conceded Stewart, who is now 20-10 as
a starter at A&AMP;M. And though Stewart may have been low-key during
his conversation with his mother last week, he was hiding a heart
that was beating strong again at the thought of the sudden
resurrection of a career he thought was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been so excited about playing a football game,''
Stewart said. ``The whole week, I couldn't wait until Saturday. I
really didn't feel like I'd be able to compete again because Randy
was doing such a good job. To be able to go out there and compete
again was so great, especially in a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   His rebirth once appeared short-lived. Stewart hyperextended his
right knee on the Aggies' third offensive series. But after a few
anxious moments, he warmed up again as Kansas State drove to a 10-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard it pop and thought, `Oh no.' Then it popped again and
it was all right,'' he said. ``And in a game like this, you forget
about things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be many things about this game Stewart will chose to
remember.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
