u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-FREEAGENTS-HNS &LR;      12-06 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FREEAGENTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Free-agent signings widen gap between haves, have-nots
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
It doesn't take a Harvard education to understand baseball
economics these days. If you have enough of the green stuff, a
ticket to the postseason can practically be bought. Otherwise, make
alternate plans for October.
</P>
<P>
   In a winter of free spending on the free-agent market, there has
been a widening disparity among baseball's haves and have-nots. And
some of baseball's top officials already have concluded that as
many as 18 of the 30 teams can already be counted out of contention
for the eight playoff spots next season, just because they can't
generate enough revenue to field competitive teams.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the World Series, deals involving big money
have seemed an every-day occurrence, and it doesn't appear that an
end is near any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   The bill so far has exceeded $850 million for more than 40 free
agents and potential free agents. Mike Piazza alone accounted for a
record $91 million, seven-year contract with the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an attempt to sort out the winners and losers in this
season's free-agent market:
</P>
<P>
   Winners &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1. Arizona: The Diamondbucks have been the most interesting
player during this winter's spending spree. What do you expect from
a club that plays at Bank One Ballpark?
</P>
<P>
   During the past month, they have been busier than an automated
teller machine, spending close to $100 million to upgrade their
pitching staff. The signings of Randy Johnson for $52.4 million,
Todd Stottlemyre for $32 million and Armando Reynoso for $5.5
million to go along with Andy Benes and either Brian Anderson or
Omar Daal gives the Diamondbacks one of the best rotations in
baseball this side of Atlanta. Suddenly it isn't quiet in the
desert, as a championship within four years is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exhilarating opening season for us. But we got our
brains beat out too many times. We took a lot of losses,'' said
owner Jerry Colangelo, whose club finished with the third-worst
record in baseball at 65-97. ``I wondered what kind of honeymoon
with the fans we were going to have. I looked at the lay of the
land and decided that we had to go sooner rather than later make
more of an attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Some baseball insiders believe Arizona is becoming nothing more
than a National League West version of the Florida Marlins, who
loaded up on high-priced free agents two years ago, won a World
Series title, then dismantled much of the roster in a series of
trades. The Diamondbacks' payroll will rise from $32.8 million in
1998 to the $53 million range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing what everybody is trying to do _ compete,''
Colangelo said. ``Why is it not OK for us to do something, and it's
OK for the Yankees, or anybody else for that matter?''
</P>
<P>
   2. Atlanta: The rap sheet on the Braves the past several seasons
has been that they don't have enough hitting to complement the
majors' best starting rotation. That should change next season as
they look to remedy a string of postseason disappointments that
have resulted in only one World Series title despite seven straight
divisional crowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves traded pitcher Denny Neagle to Cincinnati in a
five-player deal that brought All-Star second baseman Bret Boone
and then signed power-hitting outfielder Brian Jordan to a $40
million contract. Those moves give Atlanta a projected lineup of
six players who had at least 24 homers and 90 RBIs in 1998. The
Braves also brought back free agent Otis Nixon, giving them a true
leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``New linen, new china, new crystal,'' said Braves GM John
Schuerholz.
</P>
<P>
   3. New York Yankees: Even when they aren't playing on the field,
the Yankees keep winning. Think 125 wins sounds impressive? At this
rate, they may never lose a game. The World Series champions will
return intact after re-signing free agents Bernie Williams, the
American League's batting champion, and third baseman Scott
Brosius, Most Valuable Player in the Yankees' World Series sweep of
San Diego. They also picked up the renegotiated option of 20-game
winner David Cone.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible New York isn't through this offseason as owner
George Steinbrenner attempts to woo five-time Cy Young Award winner
Roger Clemens to the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   4. Anaheim: The Mouse has spending power. Thanks to Disney's
commitment _ not to mention thick wallet _ the Angels signed
slugger Mo Vaughn to an $80 million, six-year contract, giving him
the highest annual salary in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim lost out in the Randy Johnson sweepstakes, but so did
division rival Texas, so the race in the AL West should remain
competitive next season. With the distracted Vaughn out of Boston,
expect him to carry his weight in his new West Coast surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   5. Cleveland: A No. 1-caliber pitcher still remains a big
priority for the Indians, but offense and defense rank a close
second and third. They took care of the latter two areas with the
$32 million signing of free-agent second baseman Roberto Alomar,
thus putting an end to the ongoing shuffle at second that has
featured 16 different players since 1996. The addition reunites
Roberto with older brother Sandy, the Tribe's starting catcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians did upgrade their bullpen with the acquisition of
Ricardo Rincon from Pittsburgh and might be a sleeper in the race
to land Clemens. If Clemens goes elsewhere, GM John Hart is
comfortable with his club's chances in the weak AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves have three or four No. 1 starters and haven't made
it to the World Series in either of the last two years. We've been
to the World Series in two of the last four years,'' Hart said.
``There are a lot of ways to put together a championship club.''
</P>
<P>
   Losers
</P>
<P>
   1. Boston general manager Dan Duquette: Isn't this the same guy
who said Roger Clemens was in the twilight of his career? Since the
Red Sox parted ways with the popular Clemens, the Rocket has won
two straight Cy Young Awards and shows no signs of stopping any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with Duquette unwilling to go beyond a five-year deal
with Vaughn, the power-hitting first baseman has packed his bags
for sunny California. But hey, they caused a stir by giving a
four-year, $26 million deal to Jose Offerman _ whose 22 career
homers are 18 fewer than Vaughn hit this past season _ and agreeing
to multi-year deals with Troy O'Leary, Reggie Jefferson and Jeff
Frye.
</P>
<P>
   2. Chicago White Sox: The White Sox have a gaping hole in their
lineup after the departures of outfielder Albert Belle and third
baseman Robin Ventura, who combined for 70 homers and 243 RBIs last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Belle, who signed with Baltimore, had 49 homers and 152 RBIs in
1998 and became a free agent because a clause in his $55 million,
five-year contract allowed him to if the White Sox did not keep him
among baseball's three highest-paid players. Meanwhile, Ventura
turned down the White Sox's final offer and signed with the New
York Mets for $32 million over four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the situation the last two years, October rolls
around, and you're out there working on your golf game. That just
didn't sit well with me,'' Belle said. ``It was a situation where I
weighed all my options, and I felt Baltimore was my best option.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox, pushing a youth movement, finished 80-82 last
season after a terrible start. They were 35-51 in the first half
and 45-31 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   3. San Diego: For now, we'll classify the defending NL champion
Padres as losers, but that can change if they are able to re-sign
pitcher Kevin Brown, which becomes less and less of a possibility
as each day passes.
</P>
<P>
   The first to go was former NL Most Valuable Player Ken Caminiti,
who got his wish and signed a free-agent deal with the Astros.
Outfielder Steve Finley appears headed to Arizona, while the
Colorado Rockies are considered the front-runners to land Brown.
</P>
<P>
   4. The $48 Million Payroll-and-Below Club: The biggest losers in
an industry gone mad for the almighty dollar are the teams on a
budget.
</P>
<P>
   How wide is the gap? Only one team with a 1998 payroll above $48
million had a losing record _ Baltimore, whose player salaries
amounted to a major league-high $74 million. Conversely, only three
teams spending less than $48 million _ San Francisco ($47.9), St.
Louis ($47.6) and Toronto ($37.3) _ managed winning records.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't good news for clubs like the Montreal Expos and
Florida Marlins. Piazza, Williams and Belle will make more than the
Expos paid their entire team last season ($8.3 million).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible,'' Expos president Claude Brochu said. ``You
have to keep in mind the Expos have by far the lowest payroll and
by far the lowest revenues, so we are just between a rock and a
hard place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
