<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBALOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NBA players may issue deadline
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ In his continuing war with the National Basketball
Players' Association, NBA commissioner David Stern has often
alluded to his biggest weapon, the so-called ``drop-dead'' date.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the point of no return is called, the date on which
the season will be canceled because there would be not sufficient
time to get in enough games to make up a competitive season.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the inability to get a new collective bargaining
agreement with the players' union, Stern has refused to actually
set a drop-dead date.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the players, tiring of the 160-day lockout, may just tell
the NBA to drop dead this week.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dutt, a member of the agents' advisory committee to the
players' union, said he will urge union executive director Billy
Hunter to set a drop-dead date in an effort to pressure the owners
into more serious bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to the conclusion that maybe we need a drop-dead
date to get things done,'' said Dutt, an agent who represents
Antonio McDyess, Shawn Kemp, Nick Van Exel and Avery Johnson, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the committee) will take the next opportunity to urge
Billy to come out and announce a drop-dead date. Instead of
operating under the owners' terms (in negotiations) all the time, I
think the union should say, `We're giving you (the owners) an
ultimatum, and here it is.' Then you set the date.''
</P>
<P>
   What would that date be? Dutt said the committee hasn't really
discussed an absolute date yet, but he thinks it shouldn't be too
difficult to arrive at one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to go back to what people are discussing as to
when you could really have a season,'' Dutt said. ``Most agree that
it's right around Christmas. You say, `OK, it's going to be Dec. 21
or 23.' That gives everyone a couple of weeks to get something
done. But at least there's something at the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's bargaining session in New York, which consisted of
almost 11 hours of face-to-face meetings, was the first in almost
two weeks. No new talks are on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference after Thursday's session, Stern was
asked about the possibility of mediation to end the stalemate, but
included talk of killing the season in his response.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was suggested that we set a deadline and cancel the season
if we don't agree by the deadline,'' Stern said. ``That's something
I find sufficiently abhorrent. An artificial deadline for the
season is useless. In our view, the season will expire of its own
weight whenever that time is.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I'm planning to do to push that ahead to an
artificial limitation. But I now recognize the possibility, if not
the likelihood, that the season will expire.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are tiring of the constant lags in discussions,
where they often go days or even weeks between sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to do the deal, let's do it right now,'' said
Utah's Karl Malone, who attended Thursday's meeting. ``If not,
cancel it. Stop teasing the fans. Stop stringing people along. I'm
willing to sit out the whole year to get what's fair. They can take
the season away, that's commissioner Stern's call.''
</P>
<P>
   Not if the agents' advisory committee has its way.
</P>
<P>
   The committee actually talked with Hunter about setting a
drop-dead date before last Thursday's negotiating session. Hunter
decided to hold back on setting any date, but mentioned in the
post-meeting news conference that it may be time to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue of time,'' Hunter said. ``I think they (the
owners) are just not quite ready to make a deal. They're hoping to
take us up to the 12th hour, in hope that when we're confronted by
some kind of end time, we'll be inclined to enter an agreement that
we're not inclined to do now.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of fact, we've suggested that if that's how the
scenario evolves, and each of us are going to have guns to our
heads, maybe we should set a date now for cancellation. Then we can
negotiate under that pressure in hopes of getting the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The major obstacle to getting a deal remains the timing rules
change, which would force teams that sign another team's free agent
to forfeit the right to go over the salary cap to re-sign their own
Larry Bird exception free agents. Teams have been able to go over
the cap to re-sign their own free agents, the reason the Bulls were
able to pay Michael Jordan $33 million last year despite a salary
cap of $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   The owners tried to ease the shock of the timing rules change by
offering to phase it in over a period of time, but the players have
made it known that they will not accept any changes that impact
Bird free agency. The owners, who would like to close as many cap
loopholes and exceptions as possible, are holding firm on their
demand for the timing rules change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're within striking distance, but there are pretty
significant issues that separate us right now,'' Hunter said.
``Unless they soften their stances on those issues, we're not going
to have a season.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutt agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't get a deal in two weeks, then you're not going to
have a deal in a month,'' he said. ``If you have a (drop-dead)
date, it's going to stop this, `We'll meet once a week for the next
six months,' that's been going on. Once you get to that drop-dead
date, I think the owners can't afford to lose the season. Right
now, they're dictating to us everything that's going on. Why
operate on their terms all the time?
</P>
<P>
   I feel that as much as it hurts, I would rather lose the season
than agree to what they (the owners) have on the table.
Absolutely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
