<HEADLINE>
NBA MAY LOSE SEASON, BUT TOO FEW REALLY CARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ With the lockout in its sixth month, 230 games
canceled, $400 million in salaries lost and the drop-dead date
approaching faster than the Y2K meltdown, the NBA is staring
nervously at the guillotine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it's gotten to this point, but you're wearing
blinders if you don't think the season is in big jeopardy,''
Mavericks guard Erick Strickland said at last night's charity
exhibition game staged at Loos Field House. ``Not that we want to,
but I think we're all making plans to beout of work a year.''
</P>
<P>
   And on that cheerful point, on to the really bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody cares.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, 4,000 fans paid between $20-$100 to watch Cedric Ceballos
score, Robert Horry dunk and a late-arriving Shaquille O'Neal sign
autographs and suck on a lollipop in a goofy maroon football
jersey, but it has become clear that the NBA is missed about as
much as Pong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame them because I'm sure it doesn't make sense to
them,'' Mavericks guard Steve Nash said. ``I just don't want them
to blame us. We'd be playing if it was our choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans aren't debating the lockout at the water cooler, and
they're not particularly lamenting the loss with their remote
controls. ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' says ratings are up this year
despite the lack of nightly 15-minute NBA highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The NBA has bred entertainment fans, not necessarily
basketball fans. And those fans, occupied by football through
January, were already turned off last year with players' off-court
transgressions and the ugly on-court style of play.
</P>
<P>
   Add this lengthy, nonsensical lockout of players already making
salaries comparable to the GNP of Bangladesh, and now it's NBA:
Nothing But Apathy.
</P>
<P>
   A charity game in Miami drew only 2,200 on Friday and one in
Houston attracted 6,000 last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss the players, but not really the games,'' said Joe
Caton, who drove his two children to last night's game from North
Richland Hills. ``They're like movie stars, and this was a good
chance to see them. But if you want to really see good basketball,
you can watch college or even high school.''
</P>
<P>
   While players and owners continue to haggle over the ``problem''
of dividing $2 billion, fans fight the out-of-sight, out-of-mind
dilemma for a league with a future about as bleak as the holy
matrimony of Dennis Rodman and Carmen Electra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the owners, these guys are just playground players,''
said Bonnie Hyatt of Dallas, who nonetheless shelled out $40 for
her and her son to watch last night's game. ``It's not like they
don't make enough money already. They're all greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, hard-core hoop fanatics experiencing NBA
withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame because we all miss them,'' said 28-year-old fan
Jerome Hawkins of Oak Cliff. ``This is the only game we may see all
season, so we had to be here. I think everybody's sick about this,
and I don't even understand what's going on?''
</P>
<P>
   While commissioner David Stern spreads holiday doom-and-gloom by
saying ``it's more unlikely than likely that we will have a
season,'' players and fans are learning to deal with their limited
options.
</P>
<P>
   There's talk of a Dec. 19 game in Atlantic City featuring
members of all four Dream Teams and similar exhibitions in the
coming weeks in Canada and Atlanta. Between cameos, players are at
least finding productive ways to spend their spare time.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Williams is turning into Bison Dele, Chris Webber is
weaseling out of jail again, Kenny Anderson is figuring out a way
to pay the insurance on his nine cars and Latrell Sprewell is
sitting quietly at his home in Milwaukee, under 90-day house arrest
with an ankle monitor for a reckless driving conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's exhibition was fan-friendly with players signing
autographs, children allowed to participate in pregame layup lines
and the absence of those pesky traveling violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't care we wouldn't be here,'' said O'Neal, who
arrived for the supposed 7:30 tip-off at exactly 7:45 and didn't
play because organizers couldn't find shorts big enough. ``We do
care, we want to play and we want the fans to know that. Games like
this help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
