<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI LEAVES BRUINS IN RUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ They came off the field hearing chants of ``Rose Bowl,
Rose Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   In any other season, those would be words of comfort and joy for
the UCLA Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   But not Saturday. Saturday those words shouted by a jubilant
Orange Bowl crowd were taunts.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, UCLA is going to the Rose Bowl, but more importantly and
devastatingly, the Bruins are not going to play in the Fiesta Bowl
Jan. 4 for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   That became painfully and stunningly official following Miami's
remarkable 49-45 come-from-behind victory over the No. 3 Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Bruins (10-1) lose for the first time this
season, they lost for the first time in 21 games, ending the
longest winning streak in Division 1-A.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of upsets, as Kansas State lost to Texas A&AMP;M,
36-33, in Saturday's Big 12 championship game. No. 1 Tennessee beat
Mississippi State in Saturday night's SEC title game, and will be a
Fiesta Bowl participant, but which team it will face is the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Few people gave Miami (8-3) much of a chance to beat the Bruins.
The Hurricanes were banged up and embarrassed following last week's
66-13 pounding by Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Even Miami coach Butch Davis wondered about the health and
motivation of his club following the worst loss by a Miami team
since 1944.
</P>
<P>
   But people wondered about the Bruin defense, ranked a horrible
92d (of 112 Div. 1-A schools). Was it one that could win a national
championship?
</P>
<P>
   For 10 games, the Bruins and their supporters said yes. Sure the
Bruins had survived scares against Stanford and Oregon State, but
they had managed to win.
</P>
<P>
   But the Miami game raised some red flags. First of all, it was a
makeup game, orginally scheduled to be played in September, but
postponed because of the potential threat of Hurricane Georges,
which swept through the South Florida area that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins pondered playing the game at all, eventually agreeing
to reschedule it in December, two weeks after their regular season
was over, but knowing, with the vagaries of the BCS formula of
computer rankings and strength of schedule, they might need it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the point is moot. UCLA lost, done in by the heat and
humidity of a south Florida day, overcome by a Miami team that
conjured up the ghosts of great Miami teams of the past for the
Orange Bowl crowd of 46,819 by staging one of the most remarkable
comebacks in the long and storied history of the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Edgerrin James set a tone for the day by breaking
loose on a 45-yard run that gave the Hurricanes a quick 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   For James, it was the start of a historic afternoon as he rushed
for a career- and school-record 299 yards in 39 carries, scoring
three touchdowns, including the winner from 1 yard out with 50
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The game unfolded like a regular-season-ending game in the
Orange Bowl 14 years ago when Boston College's Doug Flutie became
an instant college football legend by throwing a Hail Mary pass
that gave BC a 47-45 win over Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Miami scored, with James running behind an offensive line that
was dominating the UCLA defense.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, behind the brilliance of quarterback Cade McNown (25 of
36, 513 yards, 5 TD passes, 1 TD running) countered with its own
offensive weapons and skills. At the half Miami held a 21-17 lead,
which was hardly secure. And when the Hurricanes went three-and-out
on the first series of the third quarter and UCLA came back and
scored three quick touchdowns to take a 38-21 lead, the Bruins
looked OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a doubt in my mind what we were going to do,''
said Miami quarterback Scott Covington. ``We just went right at
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had nothing to lose. They had everything to lose. We left
everything we had on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly and steadily the Hurricanes came back, cutting the lead
to 38-35 on a 71-yard pass from Covington to Santana Moss with
12:34 left in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, said McNown, who took the Bruins 83 yards, in which
he ran for a 1-yard touchdown that made it 45-35. The Bruins turned
the ball over, and suddenly the momentum, like the wind, shifted
towards Miami. A 29-yard pass from Covington to Mondriel Fulcher
made it 45-42 with 6:08 left.
</P>
<P>
   Again, UCLA drove, but a fumble by Brad Melsby at the Miami 26
killed another chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes, behind James's running and Covington's spot
passes, moved into the end zone with 50 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   McNown attempted a Hail Mary into the end zone from the Miami 29
on the last play, but it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed for them, for the seniors,'' said UCLA coach
Bob Toledo. ``Now, we're going to represent the Pac-10 in the Rose
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   But the words were spoken without a trace of joy or pride. That
would come later. Now there was only disappointment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
