<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROBERTSON-COMMENTARY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Resilient Aggies play role of purple people beaters
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ For those wearing the color purple, and there were
throngs of them, it seemed an epiphanous one-two punch.
</P>
<P>
   Only moments after Michael Bishop, that most celebrated of
Aggies rejects, rifled a 66-yard touchdown pass off his back foot
Saturday, word spread through the Trans World Dome that Miami, a
team coming off a 53-point loss, had ruined UCLA's unbeaten season.
</P>
<P>
   A throaty rumble swiftly turned into a sustained roar once the
formal announcement was made. After 105 seasons of intercollegiate
football participation, a huge majority of them served as fodder
for football factories with far grander aspirations than theirs,
Kansas State could dare think of a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The hated Bowl Championship Series wasn't going to be allowed to
cruelly smite them after all. Manhattan, Kansas, was six quarters
from becoming the center of the amateur football universe. Bill
Snyder's 'Cats suddenly had both a 17-3 lead on Texas A&AMP;M and a
clear path to the Big Game, the Fiesta Bowl, in Tempe on January 4.
</P>
<P>
   The ill-conceived, badly flawed, oft-criticized BCS scheme had
been vindicated, albeit in spite of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Out of chaos there would be order.
</P>
<P>
   Uh ... no, Sirr!
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, this long day's gridiron journey into night
concluded with things more muddled and messier than ever. It ended
with UCLA and Kansas State in utter despair, having been rudely
detoured from the promised desertland of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It also ended with the Texas Aggies and their fans making
hullabaloo and ca-necking with their significant others, locked in
joyous embraces following the 36-33 double-overtime shocker they
will someday tell their grand-Aggies about, a victory that ranks as
the school's most notable in more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Or, heck, maybe ever.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, it became the Aggies' most lucrative. Sirr
Parker's deciding touchdown catch-and-run off a third-and-17 will
result in an $11.5 million windfall to the Big 12 Conference, of
which Texas A&AMP;M is now the improbable 1998 champion and only
guaranteed representative in the four-bowl BCS pecking order. They
have Sugar Bowl written all over them.
</P>
<P>
   That's $10 million more than the Alamo Bowl, where A&AMP;M appeared
destined before Saturday's cataclysmic turnaround, pays out. If the
Aggies were ecstatic beyond belief, their conference brethren with
whom they must share should be no less so, assuming K-State can
still land a second BCS spot for the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it's not likely. The Orange Bowl, where the only at-large
berth exists, would have to rebuff 9-2 Florida in order to take the
Wildcats. Instead, they may fall all the way to the Alamo in the
Aggies' stead.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA can at least find solace in an extra ``home'' date at the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, who is, by nature, stubborn, gruff and irrascible, was
actually reduced to tears by the shattering reversal, admitting:
``It's very evident we are tremendously disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sick feeling,'' added K-State quarterback Bishop, whose
lost fumble late in regulation gave the Aggies their opportunity to
force overtime. ``I feel terrible about the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Aggies couldn't believe their good fortune.
Gracious, how quickly the ol' worm can turn.
</P>
<P>
   Sirr Parker, overshadowed by A&AMP;M's younger backs all season,
finally earned the knighthood his name implies. Fellow afterthought
Branndon Stewart finally earned his halo. R.C. Slocum, under some
fire despite a 10-2 record going in, finally earned respect as a
coach who could find an answer for a superior opponent.
</P>
<P>
   As devastating as last week's last-second loss to Texas was _
never mind subsequently losing his starting quarterback suddenly,
three days before kickoff _ Slocum kept the Aggies composed and
confident in the face of daunting odds. After all, K-State had won
19 games in a row, among them a 48-7 rout of the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   R.C.? Stands for Real Calm, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love an opportunity to prove people wrong,'' Stewart said,
referring to prognostications that the Aggies stood a snowball's
chance in the face of the Snyder juggernaut. In reality, Stewart
proved people right. Remember, when he transferred from Tennessee,
he was supposed to be the guy to carry the Aggies to a higher
place.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he only lost the starting job _ a couple times. He
might not have played a down against Kansas State if Randy McCown
hadn't been diagnosed with a broken collarbone Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, generally at his best when pressed into duty on short
notice, took a five-sack licking but passed for 324 yards and three
touchdowns, the last of which Parker pretty much got all on his
own.
</P>
<P>
   He stiff-armed cocky K-State safety Lamar Chapman at the seven,
then somehow managed to get a tiny piece of the pylon at the goal
line, thus capping the comeback from the 27-12 deficit that A&AMP;M
found itself confronting when the fourth quarter began.
</P>
<P>
   From Sirr, to Aggies everywhere, with love.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
