r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-06 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TASK TOO TOUGH TO TACKLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The UCLA football team let a national championship slip
through its fingers Saturday. In the biggest Bruins football game
in 31 years, the defensive backs tackled as though they were
chasing lacquered sunbathers.
</P>
<P>
   The linebackers looked like they were trying to hail a passing
cab along Ocean Drive. The secondary's pass coverage was skimpier
than any bathing garment being paraded around South Beach. And two
receivers joined a notorious south Florida fraternity when they
were mugged in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many wins the third-ranked Bruins string together,
they're never going to be considered more than a novelty east of
the Rockies until they can win a game that the very provincial East
Coast sporting establishment doesn't have to stay up past midnight
to watch on television.
</P>
<P>
   Five times in this decade UCLA has crossed into the Eastern time
zone seeking victories and validation. Every time they've lost
three hours, they've gone on to lose the game.
</P>
<P>
   The really horrible thing about the Bruins' 49-45 demoralizing
loss to Miami was that the Fiesta Bowl was beckoning the Bruins
like a tropical breeze right up until the Hurricanes' final gust.
UCLA hadn't played a perfect game by any stretch of the imagination
and yet the Bruins held a 17-point lead (38-21) with 16 minutes to
play.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody was going to knock UCLA out of the national
championship game, it appeared it was going to be the Bowl
Championship Series computers. Instead, the Bruins, playing in the
Eastern time zone for the first time since embarking on their
nation-leading 20-game winning streak, did nothing to squash the
generally accepted belief on this coast that their defense is a
rumor.
</P>
<P>
   Or as one New York-based sportscaster mused before the upset got
under way at the Orange Bowl, ``Can a team that is ranked 55th in
the nation in scoring defense play for a national championship?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer: apparently not. A bona fide national championship
contender does not give up 689 yards in total offense, 231 yards of
it in the fourth quarter alone. A defense determined to silence its
critics doesn't allow Miami to complete four first downs in as many
plays on its second-to-last scoring drive or to convert a
third-and-6 at its own 46 on its game-winning drive.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this was not the first time the Bruins' defense had
teetered and tottered. Last month it let Washington run wild on it
and the month before that Stanford had passed prodigiously on it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had to make do without one of their two senior
starters on defense when linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo re-injured
his left knee on the first play from scrimmage. He would grace the
playing field for just one down more but that's hardly an excuse
for the fact UCLA made Miami running back Edgerrin James look as
armed and dangerous and elusive as Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   James is good enough to have notched back-to-back 1,000-yard
seasons but he shouldn't have been able to burn the Bruins for a
Big East-record 299 yards on 39 carries. The only thing that slowed
him was his own lung capacity.
</P>
<P>
   In their first 10 games the Bruins always had managed to turn
their open palm of a defense into a tight fist when nothing less
than a knockout would do. They would let runners beat them to the
outside all day, then step up and make the big play to save the
game (remember their stand on Oregon's overtime drive?).
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday Anderson and Co. fell flat. Hey, you didn't need to
be learned in the language of logarithms to recognize the law of
averages was bound to catch up with them. We just assumed it would
take a little while longer, at least another game or two.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Bruins did, too. Perhaps they had been pulling magic
out of their helmets for so long they assumed the stardust would
never run out. Maybe that's why, when Ayanbadejo stared hard at his
teammates' faces before they took the field for one final defensive
stand, he saw... nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when I (encourage them) I get a response,'' he said,
``but I just got a blank look.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was left to senior Cade McNown to scramble and try to
make something out of nothing like he does so well. He drove UCLA
26 yards in the final 50 seconds before his 29-yard pass in the end
zone with no time left eluded backup quarterback Drew Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   McNown was second to McNone in his final regular-season game as
a collegian, passing for 513 yards and five touchdowns and carrying
the football for a sixth score. The Bruins' offense would have
bailed out the defense yet again if Brian Poli-Dixon and Brad
Melsby hadn't turned over the football in the final, frantic 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon was stripped at the Miami 13 and the Hurricanes drove
87 yards on their ensuing possession to draw to within 10 points.
Then, with less than two minutes left, Melsby caught a pass at the
Miami 26 and lost the ball after it appeared he already was down.
It was ruled a fumble, the Hurricanes took over and marched 74
yards in 2 minutes, 34 seconds to send UCLA crying into the night.
Quite literally.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' tears sprang from their grief over losing a shot at
the national title and from the pepper spray that was squirted into
their faces by some obnoxious Miami fan (on this day that was a
redundancy). As if the game hadn't been humbling enough, the Bruins
were stopped in their paths on their way to the locker room by fans
who had streamed down from the bleachers so they could stand there
and make choking gestures and ones far more obscene than that.
</P>
<P>
   One heckler kept screaming ``Rose Bowl'' in a tone that aimed to
turn the grandfather of all postseason games into the mother of all
insults.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins should take it as an affront, that they came all this
way just to ice the right to play on their own field on Jan. 1.
Those who are satisfied with playing in the Rose Bowl will find out
soon enough how hard it is to get to where they stood Saturday
morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
