</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATSON IS FULCRUM FOR YOUNG BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Coach Steve Lavin was asked Saturday evening
what he knows about his UCLA basketball team now, six games into
the 30 games season, that he didn't know before.
</P>
<P>
   He responded with the longest silence you might ever get from
Steve Lavin. Four, five, six seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good question,'' he finally said, warming up to an
answer that covered ``intensity'' and ``selflessness'' and
``progress'' but nothing more specific.
</P>
<P>
   Let me try to help.
</P>
<P>
   What Lavin and Bruins fans know now that they didn't know then
is that the team is going to revolve around sophomore point guard
Earl Watson, and that's a good thing. I said revolve around, not
rise and fall with.
</P>
<P>
   Given the youth of the 18th ranked Bruins _ who started two
freshmen and three sophomores in their 69-66 victory over 11th
ranked Oklahoma State in the Wooden Classic at the Pond _ a
playground metaphor is in order here.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is going to be a teeter-totter _ up one game (or one
minute) and down the next. Watson is going to be the fulcrum, the
base on which it rotates.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Bruins so far.
</P>
<P>
   In six games, they've used five different starting lineups
including Saturday's, in which guard Baron Davis took the place of
forward Matt Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   In six games, they've had eight different players in the
starting lineup, four freshmen and four sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   In six games, they've been led in scoring by four different
players and in rebounding by five.
</P>
<P>
   Add the fact they've already worn three different uniforms, and
you get the idea the only certainty about these Bruins is the
uncertainty about these Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may never know what our starting lineup is going to be,''
Lavin admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Let alone their lineup from moment to moment. Lavin substituted
so frantically Saturday, meaning to take advantage of a shallower
Oklahoma State team, the Bruins on the bench might as well have
left their warm-ups off.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of this whirlwind stood Earl Watson, the only
Bruin to start every game, playing 37 of the 40 minutes this time,
leading the team with 14 points and six assists and a reassuringly
steady hand.
</P>
<P>
   Watson won't be the player who puts the Bruins over the top this
season, if over the top is where they're headed. That could be Dan
Gadzuric or Jerome Moiso, the big freshmen who have such big
potential, or Davis, the sophomore guard who is weeks away from 100
percent in his comeback from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But take away Watson and see what will happen. Nothing good.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it was during Watson's last, short break Saturday
that a 15-point UCLA lead became a seven point UCLA lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the 40-minute man. Coach Lavin calls him our Cal Ripken
Jr.,'' forward Travis Reed said of Watson, a six-footer from Kansas
City who was the only Bruin to play in all 33 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our leader by example, the first to practice and the last
to leave. He's our general on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in the first couple of games this season, he was
generally out of control, seemingly trying too hard to make up for
Davis' absence. Watson committed 10 turnovers (with two assists) in
a win over San Francisco and seven turnovers (with four assists) in
the loss to No.5 Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   But in the encouraging loss to No.4 Kentucky and the wins over
Delaware State and Oklahoma State, the turnovers came down to one,
four and three and the assists went up to five, six and six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to learn to play with my (new) teammates and be a
leader,'' Watson said of his erratic start. ``It comes naturally to
me. But I'm only a sophomore, I'm not a senior.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to all the freshmen, it's easy to forget Watson isn't
exactly a grizzled veteran.
</P>
<P>
   He's modest enough to give credit to Davis for drawing defenders
and giving Watson more chances to score. And he sets a personal
goal that sounds modest _ ``I've got to be consistent'' _ but is
vital to the team.
</P>
<P>
   He's got to keep his head while everyone around him is trying to
figure this college game out.
</P>
<P>
   It's a team of unknown quantities, but after the past three
games, Lavin should know Watson can do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
