<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-REDWINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FALL TO RED WINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ It was pretty much what one would have expected, the
championship team finding a way to win, the downtrodden team
finding a way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had their moments Saturday night, rallying from a
three-goal deficit against the two-time Stanley Cup champion
Detroit Red Wings. In the end, though, a third-period goal by
Detroit winger Tomas Holmstrom was the difference as the Kings lost
4-3 before a sellout crowd of 16,005 at the Forum that included a
very vocal minority of Wings fans.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the 11th in the last 12 games for the Kings
(6-17-3).
</P>
<P>
   The first period was the latest chapter in the Kings' ongoing
saga of suffering, the perpetually dormant power play compounding
its ineptitude by allowing a shorthanded goal to Sergei Fedorov
followed by even-strength goals 25 seconds apart by Steve Yzerman
and Brendan Shanahan. By the end of the first 20 minutes, the Kings
trailed, 3-0, and had failed to score in the first period for the
10th time in the last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   There was little reason to expect a second-period turnaround,
but 5:53 into the second, the Kings cut the deficit to 3-1 with a
goal from Yanic Perreault. For Perreault, who scored 28 goals last
season, it was his first goal since Oct.18, a span of 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings weren't finished, and by the end of the second period,
the score was tied 3-3, their scoring outburst equaling their
offensive production for the previous four games combined.
</P>
<P>
   At 16:18, Luc Robitaille cut the deficit to one with his
team-high 12th goal, a goal that ended the Kings' 0-for-18 drought
on the power play. The Kings scored when a Detroit lapse _ and a
beautiful behind-the-back pass from Jozef Stumpel _ resulted in a
2-on-0 for Robitaille and Glen Murray.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings tied the score with 49 seconds left in the period and
referee Blaine Angus signaled a delayed penalty on Wings defenseman
Uwe Krupp. Sean O'Donnell scored the goal, his first of the season,
from the slot off a Stumpel centering feed.
</P>
<P>
   It would be for naught. Less than three minutes into the final
period, defenseman Doug Bodger and Detroit's Kris Draper tangled
for a puck to the right of goalie Stephane Fiset. Draper landed on
top of Bodger, and the puck ended up along the left boards, chased
by Steve Duchesne and Detroit's Doug Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown arrived first, centering the puck to Holmstrom who was all
alone in front of the net, a defensive lapse Fiset _ who made 41
saves _ was defenseless to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pulling Fiset for an extra skater in the last minute,
the Kings could not get the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: In response to a reporter's question, general manager
Dave Taylor said a coaching change is not being contemplated and
has not been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident in Larry as a coach,'' Taylor said. ``We offered
Larry an extension in training camp. He really hasn't responded to
it. We're worried about trying to get the team turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is in the final year of his contract. ESPN this week
reported that there are doubts whether Robinson, in his fourth year
as the Kings' coach, wants to return.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said, ``There's always doubt, not of whether I want to
return, but there's doubt of whether they want you back. Life is
full of doubts. Life is full of surprises. I'm the type of person
who lives day to day, not year to year.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson added that he would not feel comfortable signing an
extension while the Kings are so deeply mired in a slump....
Captain Rob Blake, sidelined five weeks with a broken foot, is
scheduled to undergo an MRI on Monday, and if results are negative,
he said he is hoping to start skating Tuesday and to play as soon
as Saturday at home against Vancouver. Winger Russ Courtnall,
however, is still on crutches, probably a month from returning from
his broken ankle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
