<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS' DIATRIBE ENOUGH TO UPSET OKLAHOMA STATE'S GOTTLIEB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The feud between UCLA point guard Baron Davis
and Oklahoma State's Doug Gottlieb was raised to public levels
during the Bruins' 69-66 victory over Oklahoma State at the Wooden
Classic on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb was ejected from the game after receiving his second
technical foul for throwing an elbow at Davis as the first half
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The elbow, Gottlieb admitted afterward, was wrong but only
highlighted the verbal war between the point guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baron was running his mouth,'' Gottlieb said. ``He wanted to
talk trash the whole game. I don't blame him but I don't take my
hat off to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for him as a player but it's a shame
he needs to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis denied saying anything to Gottlieb during the game, but
admitted he was upset by comments that were relayed to him from
Gottlieb's father, Bob, a former coach at Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was saying Doug was better than me and Earl (Watson),''
Davis said. ``He said Doug was going to destroy me.''
</P>
<P>
   For Doug Gottlieb, the ejection ruined his homecoming at the
Pond. He went to high school at Tustin and had his family at the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst feeling in the whole world,'' he said. ``I
didn't think I deserved the (technical). Baron had been talking to
me the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Home away from home: UCLA forward Travis Reed had fond memories
of the Pond, where he played for A.B. Miller High School against
Long Beach Poly in the Southern Section Division I-AA championship
game two years ago and scored 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   He responded with one of his better games Saturday, with 12
points and five rebounds against Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Pond. The Pond is like a second home,'' Reed said.
``I wish we played all our games here. I'd be automatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect in Wooden: UCLA is 4-0 in the Wooden Classic, with three
victories against teams (Kentucky, New Mexico, Oklahoma State) that
were ranked higher than the Bruins. The only lower-ranked team to
play the Bruins was Maryland.
</P>
</TEXT>
