<SLUG> BC-BOX-LOPEZ-PAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAGE GOES TO MAT TO BEAT LOPEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY _ Jose Luis Lopez is a bull, and bulls die hard in
the ring. But they die all the same.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night at the Atlantic City Convention Center, Lopez
died harder than most, twice knocking down World Boxing Association
welterweight champion James Page before losing a 12-round decision.
</P>
<P>
   Page actually hit the canvas six times, but four were slips on
the wet canvas and a fifth should have been but referee Tony Perez
called it a knockdown in the ninth round. To her credit, judge
Debra Barnes ignored the conventional requirement that a knockdown
result in a 10-8 round, but the other two judges did not. In the
end it didn't matter, because Page won a unanimous decision, with
Barnes giving him a 116-111 nod, while Guillermo Perez had it
115-112 and judge Cesar Ramos scored it 115-111. The Globe had Page
a 115-113 winner.
</P>
<P>
   Page started fast, his superior hand speed allowing him to beat
Lopez to the punch with a long jab and a right hand behind it.
Those punches repeatedly landed on the bridge of Lopez's nose.
</P>
<P>
   But in the third round, Lopez (42-4-2) showed what has made him
one of the most dangerous welterweights in the world when he landed
a counter right to the face of an off-balance Page and floored him.
When Page (23-3) got up, he was still in trouble, and Lopez
continued to pound him until the champion staggered back to his
corner in a fog at the bell.
</P>
<P>
   Still in trouble when the fourth round opened, Page kept
blinking as if peering into a foggy night, but by the end of the
round he was rallying and Lopez was again on the defensive. Lopez
stayed there until the fifth round, when he again hurt Page with a
straight right when the champion pulled out of a close exchange
with his right hand down while moving backward.
</P>
<P>
   Those mistakes were nearly fatal because Lopez leaped on them
and stunned Page with another right and the champion went limp. But
Lopez was unable to finish his work before the round ended.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the fight followed that pattern, with the champion
controlling long stretches with his jab and speed and some stinging
right hands that would have sent many a man out on his shield.
</P>
<P>
   But Lopez never buckled, despite taking severe abuse as his head
was repeatedly rocked straight back. But it was as if Page had
spent 12 rounds punching in vain for all the lasting damage it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt how strong he was when I hit him,'' Page said. ``I
thought he would at least bobble, but he never budged. I was trying
to stay focused and keep my jab going. He's a great fighter, but I
won the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   From time to time Lopez would stagger Page with powerful rights,
bloodying the champ's lip late in the fight and appearing twice to
have him out on his feet. After those brief explosions, Lopez would
mysteriously follow Page around, getting peppered in the process as
the champion build up his lead.
</P>
<P>
   At those times, the champion seemed to have Lopez baffled, and
in the end those long dry spells cost Lopez his second shot at the
WBA title because while he won his rounds in spectacular fashion he
lost more of them in silent fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good fight. Page deserved to win,'' Lopez said.
``Tonight I was just a bit off.''
</P>
<P>
   So was former two-time junior bantamweight champion Johnny Tapia
(45-0-2), but he managed to win a majority decision to take the WBA
bantamweight championship away from Nana Konadu (39-4-1). Judge
Uriel Aguilera scored it 116-111 and John Poturaj had it 115-112,
while judge Franco Priami saw it as a 114-114 draw.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 rounds the fighters mostly looked fiercely at one
another, although Konadu did cut Tapia's right eye in the third
round. Tapia won the last two rounds with some furious flurries
which, had they come earlier and more often, might have made things
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the evening, Richard Hall won the ``interim'' WBA
light heavyweight title that Roy Jones Jr. successfully defended
three weeks ago at Foxwoods.
</P>
<P>
   Hall (23-1, 22 KOs) stopped Anthony Bigeni (19-5) at 1:49 of the
third round, a decision made by referee Rudy Battle one second
after Bigeni landed one of the few punches he put on target in the
fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
