<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FALL TO RED WINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A rarely-evident atmosphere enveloped the
Los Angeles Kings' locker room after the second period Saturday
night, exactly what one would expect from a struggling team that
had overcome a three-goal deficit to draw even with the two-time
defending champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was life,'' winger Glen Murray said later. ``Finally.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the game, the atmosphere was back to its deathly norm,
after Tomas Holmstrom's goal early in the third period lifted the
Detroit Red Wings to a 4-3 victory before a sellout crowd of 16,005
at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Holmstrom scored when left alone in front of the net by Kings
defenseman Steve Duchesne, who had chased the puck to the boards
even though his partner, Doug Bodger, was tangled on the ice with
Detroit's Kris Draper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cardinal sin for a defenseman,'' coach Larry Robinson
said of Duchesne's play. ``Some mistakes are from wanting to do too
much. Others, you learn as a pee-wee growing up. When your partner
is in trouble, as a defenseman, you stay in front of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus did the Kings (6-17-3) lose for the 11th time in their last
12 games, though it wasn't as easy for Detroit (14-9-1) as it first
appeared it would be.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings grabbed a 3-0 lead after one period, the Kings'
defensive miscues contributing to goals by Sergei Fedorov
(shorthanded), Steve Yzerman and Brendan Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, however, rallied to tie in the second period, scoring
as many goals in a 13:18 span as they'd scored in their previous
four games combined. Yanic Perreault's first goal since Oct.18, Luc
Robitaille's power-play goal (snapping an 0-for-18 drought with the
man advantage) and Sean O'Donnell's first goal of the season
brought the Kings even.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' Robinson said of the atmosphere after the
second period. ``It was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   But not for long, thanks to Holmstrom, who scored after a
centering pass from Doug Brown, who had beaten the ill-positioned
Duchesne to the puck. The Kings didn't come close to tying the
score in the game's final minutes, and were left to stew over their
latest mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys in here have to face the fact that we're losing
and if they don't bring more to the table, things are going to
change,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   A coaching change, however, does not appear to be imminent, even
though the Kings have the fewest points of any of the NHL's 27
teams. In response to a reporter's question, general manager Dave
Taylor said a change is not being contemplated and has not been
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident in Larry as a coach,'' Taylor said. ``We offered
Larry an extension in training camp. He really hasn't responded to
it. We're worried about trying to get the team turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a finalist for coach of the year honors last season,
is in the final year of his contract. ESPN this week reported that
there are doubts whether Robinson, in his fourth year as the Kings'
coach, wants to return.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said, ``There's always doubt, not of whether I want to
return, but there's doubt of whether they want you back. Life is
full of doubts. Life is full of surprises. I'm the type of person
who lives day to day, not year to year.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson added that he would not feel comfortable signing an
extension while the Kings are so deeply mired in a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Kings notes: Captain Rob Blake, sidelined five weeks with a
broken foot, is scheduled to undergo an MRI on Monday. If results
are negative, Blake said he is hoping to start skating Tuesday and
to play as soon as Saturday at home against Vancouver. Winger Russ
Courtnall, however, is still on crutches, probably a month from
returning from his broken ankle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
