<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-SUN-BOWL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSETS ASSIST TCU'S HOPES FOR SUN BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE AND JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TCU's chances of playing in the Dec. 31 Sun Bowl were boosted by
UCLA's loss at Miami, Fla., and Texas A&AMP;M's upset of Kansas State
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this point, it's in our best interest to have a
Texas team,'' said John Folmer, chairman of the Sun Bowl selection
committee. ``And there are a lot of TCU people here, as we found
out from all the letters and faxes.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly qualified that seeming endorsement of TCU, saying
``nothing is sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs' chief competition for a trip to El Paso
appears to be Central Florida. However, Central Florida, which
appeared to lose a spot in one of the two Hawaii bowls with UCLA's
loss, might have regained that berth thanks to A&AMP;M's victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Bowl has a contract to match teams from the Pac-10 and
Big Ten conferences. Here's how yesterday's results effected TCU:
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's loss opened a spot in the Bowl Championship Series for
Ohio State. The Big Ten Conference has only five bowl-eligible
teams but can't fill all them, opening a berth in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's loss sends the Bruins to the Rose Bowl and moves the
Pac-10's five bowl teams down a notch. That means that the Oahu
Bowl, which also has an agreement with the Pac-10, gets a Pac-10
team, probably Southern Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M's victory means the Aggies get a spot in a BCS bowl,
probably the Orange. Kansas State is likely to get an at-large BCS
bid, probably in the Sugar. The Big 12 has seven bowl-eligible
teams and five other bowl spots.
</P>
<P>
   That means Colorado, instead of filling an at-large berth in the
Aloha Bowl, moves into one of the Big 12's bowl spots, probably the
Insight.com. That leaves an opening in the Aloha that could go to
Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to think,'' TCU coach Dennis Franchione
said. ``I thought we were supposed to be cheering for UCLA; now I
don't know. We're just excited to be in this position and hope that
holds true.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Bowl's 11-person selection committee plans to meet at 9
a.m today to select a team to play against a Pacific-10 Conference
team, most likely Oregon, which is 8-3 and ranked 21st in The
Associated Press media poll. The committee's choice is expected to
be announced later today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had someone say: `I guess this means that Central Florida is
the favorite.' Not at all,'' Folmer said. ``Just because they're
9-2 doesn't mean they are the favorite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 1309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
