</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANGERS-MATEO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LIKELY TO OFFER MATEO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Center fielder Ruben Mateo, the No. 1
prospect in the Rangers' minor-league system, likely will be the
centerpiece in any Texas trade proposal for Toronto right-hander
Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said yesterday that the
inclusion of catcher Ivan Rodriguez or left fielder Rusty Greer in
any trade proposal is ``very unlikely,'' leaving Mateo as the
likely core to any offer. Nevertheless, Melvin foresees the Rangers
being able to make a competitive offer for the five-time Cy Young
Award recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, a 20-year-old outfielder from the Dominican Republic, hit
.309 with 18 home runs and 75 runs batted in and stole 18 bases in
107 games this year for Double-A Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we didn't trade Ruben Mateo last summer, and we
won't,'' Rangers owner Tom Hicks said Tuesday after the Rangers
announced their acquisition of first baseman Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, though, made that statement before Clemens demanded to be
traded. Clemens, who resides in the Houston suburb of Katy,
informed the Blue Jays on Wednesday of his desire to be traded to
an organization closer to his home or to a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers inquired about acquiring Clemens before the July
trade deadline, but nothing materialized. Melvin and Blue Jays
general manager Gord Ash then discussed a trade that would have
sent Clemens to the Rangers in exchange for Greer, Mateo and
left-hander Darren Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is without a doubt the best Double-A player I saw this
year,'' said one American League scout who saw Mateo play numerous
times this past season. ``He's a five-tool player. He's going to
hit for average, and he's going to hit for power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can run. He can throw. He's got great range. He can play
shallow and go get the ball. He can cut the ball off in the gap and
make the throw. He's just an exciting guy to watch.''
Orioles sign Clark
First baseman Will Clark signed a two-year, $11 million contract
with Baltimore yesterday, meaning the Rangers will receive two
draft selections as compensation for losing the free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, as it stands now, will receive the Orioles'
third-round selection and a sandwich pick between the first and
second rounds for losing Clark. The Chicago White Sox and Seattle
Mariners, as it stands now, will receive the Orioles' first- and
second-round selections, respectively, for losing left fielder
Albert Belle and right-hander Mike Timlin to Baltimore through free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 34, could earn as much as $12.8 million with the Orioles
through incentives. He received a $1 million signing bonus with
base salaries of $4.5 and $5.5 million the next two seasons. He
also will earn bonuses of $200,000 for 115 and 120 games played and
$250,000 for 130 and 140 games played each of the next two seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
