<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5271 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-BOOKIE-TEX     12-06 2539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-BOOKIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLEGAL SPORTS BETTING THRIVES AS BOOKIES HAVE LITTLE FEAR OF LAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``B.H.'' is a lot like you and me.
</P>
<P>
   Lives in a tranquil Tarrant County neighborhood. Has an adoring
wife of 18 years, a 17-year-old son, a '91 Ford truck and passions
for sports and cold, hard, cash. He smokes too much, swears like a
sailor, is uncomfortable in ties, gives what he can to charity and
relishes his time on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   But look closer _ where few are offered a view _ and B.H. is
nothing like you and me.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of us were casually watching the Minnesota
Vikings-Green Bay Packers ``Monday Night Football'' game on Oct. 5,
he propped up his feet, popped open a cold one and illegally made
$17,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some people live ``for'' sports; others live ``on'' sports. You
betcha, B.H. is a big-time bookie, an independent member of a
thriving local underworld fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not claiming to be a saint by any means,'' he said
recently in the kitchen of his sneakily modest house. ``But I'm
making an honest living. Like it or not, I'm a public servant.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials disagree, but say they are handcuffed
by financial and manpower limitations to curtail neighborhood
high-stakes bookies who often take in as much as $50,000 a weekend
in bets on sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's safe to say it's pretty prevalent around our
area,'' said Steve Vega, Fort Worth Police Department vice division
officer, who nonetheless indicated his department had not made a
gambling arrest in the past year. ``We really don't have the
resources to make a commitment to shutting it down.''
</P>
<P>
   From $5 bets at the corner bar, to $500 wagers on Cowboys games,
to the point shaving scandal that has invaded the football and
basketball programs at Northwestern University, sports gambling _
legal and illegal _ has ballooned into a $100 billion industry that
authorities find difficult to harass, much less to harness.
</P>
<P>
   Final score: Bookies $$$, Arrests 0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plain and simple, it's just very hard to stop,'' said Ray Rike
of the Tarrant County District Attorney's office. ``We know it
exists _ there are bets made at every level on practically every
corner _ but we can't afford to go out and set up sting operations
to catch every bookie.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does B.H. seem to need gadgets to attract customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see me advertising, do you?'' B.H. said. ``People
come to me because they want to, not because I beg or entice them.
The Texas Lottery doesn't give a damn if it's a family down to its
last $20, they'll take it and not even know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a businessman, but I've also got a heart. I won't let
people destroy themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't stop people from placing bets with bookies such as
B.H. In a recent study, the Texas Council on Problem and Compulsive
Gambling (TCPCG) estimated that 45 percent of Texans gambled on an
activity other than the lottery last year, and 34 percent placed a
sports bet with a friend or a bookie.
</P>
<P>
   Says B.H., ``If you don't bet, chances are you know a friend of
a friend who does.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't smirk. Your repair man, fast-food delivery boy, or even
your judge could be gambling on sports right under your naive nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howdy, Joe Bob. I'll take some milk, bread, a bag of those
pork rinds, and give me TCU plus the points for $25.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the Fort Worth-Dallas area on weekends, tens of thousands
of bettors phone-in illegal wagers ranging from $25 to $10,000 in
an attempt to predict the final score of football games. The
Cowboys, for example, are favored today over New Orleans by 6 1/2
points, referred to as the ``point spread.'' If the underdog Saints
win the game outright or lose by fewer than 6 1/2 points, those
betting on them will win and those betting on Dallas will lose.
</P>
<P>
   Bets also are commonly made on the total points scored in the
game, known as the over-under, and on multiple-game packages,
called ``parlays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most estimates say $100 billion is bet legally and illegally
on sports each year,'' said John Avello, director of Bally's Sports
Book in Las Vegas. who ranks football ahead of basketball and then
baseball in volume. ``That's a pretty healthy industry.''
</P>
<P>
   With a backdrop of phones ringing in makeshift offices, payoffs
exchanged in restaurant parking lots and losers anguishing through
sleepless nights, a close-up look at the ever-growing industry of
illegal sports gambling from bookie, to bettor, and beyond: WHO'S
BOOKING? For every 40-ish B.H., who has owned what he calls a
``store'' for 23 years, there are thousands of fly-by-night,
20-something bookies who disappear owing a couple hundred bucks
here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any other profession, reputation is everything,''
said ``Goldie,'' a bookmaker in south Dallas who claims to stash as
much as $200,000 cash under his fish aquarium and to have 75
regular players, including a Tarrant County Junior College freshman
and a high-level executive at a major area business. ``There are
bookies who are in it to get rich quick, to steal your money.
Believe me, we hate them as much as anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   B.H. said he has been a professional gambler since his
grandfather taught him to pitch pennies at age 7. Watching the
Dallas-Fort Worth Spurs, a minor-league baseball team, at Turnpike
Stadium as a teen-ager in the late 1960s, he stumbled upon a gold
mine. After witnessing a pass-the-hat ``Guess Tonight's
Attendance'' game flourish, B.H. decided to take it a step further.
</P>
<P>
   After trolling each section and soliciting around 200 guesses at
$1 each, B.H. later found the patron with the closest guess and
awarded the winner's pot _ of $100.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the money, it was the right to stand up and brag
about how smart they were,'' said B.H., who pocketed the other $100
without a single inquiry. ``That's called running the numbers. The
mob did it. Today, the lotteries do it. You may be thrilled to win
$40 million, but what if they took in $50 million?''
</P>
<P>
   Like the lottery, B.H. assumes a position that practically
guarantees a profit. That position includes collecting a ``vig or
``juice,'' a 10 percent fee on losing bets that keeps bookies in
business and most bettors in the red.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lifeblood,'' says B.H. ``It's not that you can't beat me,''
B.H. said, grinning. ``It's that you can't beat the odds.
Eventually, they'll catch up to you. The only guys who have a
chance are the ones who only play big on one or two games here and
there. But they eventually lose, too.''
</P>
<P>
   B.H. knows the ups and downs of gambling _ he said he once won
an acre of land near Lake Whitney in a poker game, another time
sank a 10-foot par putt worth $64,000, lost $57,000 on Super Bowl
XXVI and routinely takes $5 bets on horse races from his
76-year-old mother. Despite the success, he isn't pushing his son
to enter the family business. He points more toward his two
siblings, who hold more socially acceptable jobs as a machinist and
an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ashamed at all of what he does,'' said B.H.'s son, who
plans to attend college to become a math teacher. ``If my friends
say this or that, I just tell them how ignorant they are. He's
making a good life for me, better than the one he had.''
</P>
<P>
   B.H. said he owns only one credit card, for hotel reservations
only, carries a wad of $100s the size of the Taco Bell Chihuahua,
takes expensive weekend trips to Las Vegas, recently donated money
to help build a local high school baseball field, and last wore a
suit to a family funeral in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good-hearted, old-fashioned dinosaurs,'' said his wife,
pouring B.H. a beer-and-tomato-juice concoction as his ``store''
employees are swarmed with a combined $10,000 action on the
Syracuse-Boston College football game and Game 2 of the National
League Championship Series. ``He's got the gift of knowing numbers,
and having a big heart.'' WHO'S BETTING? Cultivating consistent
clientele is never a problem for B.H., who says he turns away as
many as 10 prospective players a month to keep his number around
130. Nowadays, it's word-of-mouth that lead bettors his way.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, it was more sleight of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Needing to build a base of customers, B.H. hatched a simple
scheme in which he mailed 10,000 local letters to names he acquired
from the Las Vegas Business and Tourist Department. In half the
letters he predicted the Cowboys to cover the point spread. In the
other half, he predicted Washington would cover. Down to 5,000 the
next week, he again used the ploy on the next Cowboys game. Two
weeks later, B.H.'s system rewarded him with 1,250 bettors to whom
he had given _ free of charge _ three consecutive weeks of
point-spread winners on Cowboys games.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he built a ``bettor'' mousetrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could've charged them $500 a month for my picks at that
point,'' he laughs, ``but it was only something like $75. Bettors
are gullible people, always looking for a shortcut. They don't
realize it's luck, pure and simple luck.''
</P>
<P>
   That same naivete led bettors to follow B.H.'s East Coast tout
phone service during the 1991 NCAA basketball tournament. And who
could blame them? After all, the $10-a-call recorded messages
picked winners 86 percent of the time during the month-long event.
</P>
<P>
   So what if he let his dog, ``Tippy,'' do the selecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hold up two pieces of paper with the two teams and he'd
bark at one,'' B.H. said. ``Damnedest thing I've ever seen. People
call those experts like crazy, but I can tell you from experience
that they're having smoke blown up their \Rbehinds\S. It's the
biggest waste of money on earth. If those guys really went 9-1
every weekend, why would they need some piddly telephone
business?''
</P>
<P>
   Added Goldie, ``We're here to sell a product, the opportunity to
make money. It's speculation, just like the stock market. It's very
appealing. Has been for centuries. Those who study and work hard
are better than others, but the next expert to come along will be
the first. If the coaches themselves aren't sure what's going to
happen, how can some slick-talking guy in an expensive suit be
sure?''
</P>
<P>
   So who are these bettors, flooding 1-900 numbers to hear
prognosticator Johnny DeMarco yell ``I am on fiiiire!'' even though
no such person even exists? Making nightly calls to wager their
hard-earned money on a bounce of the ball here or an blown coin
flip there? And using places like local sports bars and night clubs
as weekly drop-off points for envelopes containing as much as
$12,000 in cash?
</P>
<P>
   According to Gamblers Anonymous and the Texas Council on Problem
and Compulsive Gambling (TCPCG), they are predominantly young white
males from above-average income households.
</P>
<P>
   For local bookies B.H. and Goldie, Fort Worth/Dallas is a
betting hotbed because of what they call ``homers,'' fans who bet
on the Cowboys with their hearts instead of their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the \Rpoint spread\S in Vegas and then here,'' said
B.H., who tries to manipulate the line to persuade the same amount
of money to be bet on both teams so he can profit from the 10
percent juice regardless of the outcome. ``It'll always be 1 to 2
1/2 points more expensive on Dallas. I'm a Cowboys fan, but when
they don't cover on Sunday, I usually have a happy Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Those with a severe gambling problem usually have a less happy
Monday. According to the TCPCG, approximately 500,000 Texans are
spinning out of control chasing the elusive sure thing. ``Bob'' is
among them.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as social activity in his UT-Arlington
fraternity grew into a $1,000-a-day habit that cost him his job,
his family and, almost, his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won $5,000 one week, then eight days later had to steal from
my wife's family to pay off my debt. When I won I felt invincible.
But the lows were so much more drastic. I quit caring about things
like sleeping or eating. It's just like a powerful drug. You get
addicted to the rush.''
WHO'S BOTHERING? While neither Goldie nor B.H. admits to ever
physically harassing slow payers or no-payers _ ``There's a judge
who owes me so much he just finally put me in his will,'' jokes
B.H. _ both have their tricks to avoiding legal trouble.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Goldie said he has changed his phone numbers twice a
month, answered his phone ``Whataburger'' or ``Taco Bell'' and kept
records on rice paper, easily dissolved when flushed down a toilet.
To avoid Internal Revenue Service red-flagging, B.H. said he owns
several tax-paying businesses like an air-conditioner repair shop
and a delivery service. Nosy neighbors, he said, are kept quiet
with a surprise supply of firewood at their doorstep or an
impromptu painting of their house.
</P>
<P>
   While the FBI and IRS do have units assigned to monitor
organized crime and gambling in Fort Worth-Dallas, bookies have,
for the most part, avoided the long arm of local law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very rare that we prosecute a sports gambling
case,'' said Robert Hester, chief of the Tarrant County District
Attorney's intake division. ``The police just don't bring us
anything. In fact, I don't remember any in the last several
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Vega indicated the crackdowns were tougher and the arrests more
frequent in Dallas. He says each of the dozen Fort Worth gambling
arrests made in the past 12 months were for cockfighting and video
slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``To really catch bookies you have to get a foothold in their
network, and that takes time and money,'' Vega said. ``They run in
their own circles and are basically tight-lipped. It seemed like we
were spinning our wheels, spending $2,000 and a couple months' work
to get a guy on two years' probation.''
</P>
<P>
   B.H. only smiles when asked about his annual income and laughs.
He said his self-employed salary is ``unpredictable'' and his store
is ``profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   He does brag about having carte blanche in some of Fort Worth's
finest restaurants and on some of its best golf courses, where he
routinely +accessorizes his 14-club bag with a gun, ``just in
case.'' During a recent round, he said he paused from a birdie putt
long enough to introduce his foursome to a fellow bookie permitted
to play barefoot because of ``friendly connections'' with the club
pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sleep great at night,'' B.H. said. ``I don't owe anyone a
dollar I can't pay right here on the spot, and I got most
everything I need. As for the victims, show them to me. I consider
my players as business associates, and I've even become friends
with some of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bookies knowingly break the law, but say they prefer to remain
illegal eagles. Unlike proponents for prostitution or marijuana,
they aren't pushing to make their product legal, in part because
they would be forced to pay taxes on their income.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one reason it can't be legalized, but it's a good
one,'' B.H. said. ``If it were, we could never really trust the
athletes not to bet against themselves. It would ruin sports, and
sports is what it's really all about. Nobody knows what going to
happen in games, but the temptation is to thinking you do.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you run out of luck and money, at least you can take
that advice to the bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
