<HEADER>
A5273 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-HELP-TEX     12-06 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-HELP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE A PROBLEM? THERE IS HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gamblers Anonymous is an organization designed to help
compulsive gamblers stop gambling. There are two locations and
three meetings in the Fort Worth-Dallas area _ two at 7 p.m. in
Dallas on Tuesday and Thursday night _ and one in North Richland
Hills on Thursday nights at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Gamanon is an organization for people who are affected by
gambling but don't gamble, the GA equivalent of Alcohol Anonymous'
Alanon. The Gamanon usually includes spouses, parents, children and
friends. The meetings are at the same time, places and nights as
the Gamblers Anonymous meetings, but in a different room. There is
also a mixed meeting involving both groups in Dallas on Saturday
mornings at 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Membership at the meetings, which include from seven to 20
members, requires only a desire to quit gambling. ``People just
want to take two aspirins and be cured by morning, but it isn't
quite that easy,'' says Herb E. of the Dallas branch. GA has 20
questions that it asks new members. Compulsive gamblers usually
answer ``yes'' to at least seven.
</P>
<P>
   1. Do you lose time from work due to gambling?
</P>
<P>
   2. Does gambling make your home life unhappy?
</P>
<P>
   3. Does gambling affect your reputation?
</P>
<P>
   4. Do you ever feel remorse after gambling?
</P>
<P>
   5. Do you ever gamble to get money with which to pay debts or to
otherwise solve financial difficulties?
</P>
<P>
   6. Does gambling cause a decrease in your ambition or
efficiency?
</P>
<P>
   7. After losing, do you feel you must return as soon as possible
to win back your losses?
</P>
<P>
   8. After a win, do you have a strong urge to return and win
more?
</P>
<P>
   9. Do you often gamble until your last dollar is gone?
</P>
<P>
   10. Do you ever borrow to finance your gambling?
</P>
<P>
   11. Do you ever sell anything to finance gambling?
</P>
<P>
   12. Are you reluctant to use ``gambling money'' for normal
expenditures?
</P>
<P>
   13. Does gambling make you careless about the welfare of your
family?
</P>
<P>
   14. Do you ever gamble longer than you planned?
</P>
<P>
   15. Do you ever gamble to escape worry or trouble?
</P>
<P>
   16. Do you ever commit, or consider committing, an illegal act
to finance your gambling?
</P>
<P>
   17. Does gambling cause you to have difficulty sleeping?
</P>
<P>
   18. Do arguments, disappointments, or frustrations create within
you an urge to gamble?
</P>
<P>
   19. Do you have an urge to celebrate good fortune by a few hours
of gambling?
</P>
<P>
   20. Do you ever consider self-destruction as a result of your
gambling?
</P>
<P>
   If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, call the
Texas Council on Problem and Compulsive Gambling at (800) 742-0443
or (972) 889-2331.
</P>
<P>
   For additional information about support groups, you may write
to: Gamblers Anonymous, World Service Office, P.O. Box 17173, Los
Angeles, CA 90017. Family members and friends of the compulsive
gambler should write to the Gamanon International Service Office,
P.O. Box 157, Whitestone, NY 11357.
</P>
</TEXT>
