</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-TERMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERMS OF ENDANGERMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
A look at some of the most commonly used terms and phrases by
bookies and bettors:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bookie: Person who accepts multiple bets from multiple people on
sporting events. Also called ``Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Store: Office _ sometimes home garages or even rented warehouses
_ in which bookies set up phones and operations.
</P>
<P>
   Player: Person who makes bets with bookies on sporting events.
Depending on outcome, he will either pay or be paid by bookie.
</P>
<P>
   Line: Number selected by bookie to entice half his players to
bet on one team and half on the other. Also called ``Point
spread,'' or ``Number,'' it is the key to establishing each game as
a money-making proposition for bookies.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite: Team that the betting public thinks will win the game.
The bookie makes his line based on public perception. For example,
the Cowboys were an 8-point favorite against the Giants on Nov. 8.
Since they won by 10, 16-6, those betting on Dallas won and those
on New York lost.
</P>
<P>
   Underdog: Team that the betting public thinks will lose the
game. Backers of these teams can ``win'' if losing by a total less
than the point spread. For example, Stanford lost to UCLA, 28-24.
However, since Stanford was an 18-point underdog and only lost by
four, the Stanford backers were winners in betting terms.
</P>
<P>
   Credit: Given to bettors at start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Settle: Discreet, cash-only transactions from either
bookie-to-player or vice-versa. Most of these occur in public
places.
</P>
<P>
   Action: Used by bookie or player to describe volume of betting
on a certain game. For example, a typical Cowboys game draws
approximately $15,000 worth of action to some stores.
</P>
<P>
   Juice: The 10-percent tax by the bookies on all losing wagers.
Most bookies charge bettors $11 for every $10 they risk. For
example, a player winning a $50 bet would win $50, but a loser
would lose $55. Also called ``Vigorish'' or ``Vig,'' it might not
seem like much. But if a bookie can take $10,000 action on one team
and also $10,000 on the other, he's guaranteed to make $1,000 in
juice no matter the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Totals: A bet on how many points will be scored in a game.
Bookies establish the number and players bet either over or under
the total.
</P>
<P>
   Parlay: Multiple-game bet in which the player tried to correctly
predict two or more games to increase his odds. For example, a
player winning a three-game parlay gets paid 6-to-1 ($300 on a $50
bet) for getting all three games right. He must get all three games
right, but there is no juice on parlays.
</P>
<P>
   Push: Used to describe tie bets. For example, if the Cowboys
were favored over the Giants by 8 and had won, 24-16, it would have
been a push. No money exchanges hands on pushes.
</P>
<P>
   Limit: Pre-determined amount established between bookie and
player on a particular game.
</P>
<P>
   Homer: Player who typically bets on one team regardless of the
point spread. Dallas is known as a hotbed of homers because of the
rabid loyalty to the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Solid: Player who has established a good reputation with his
bookie for paying his balance on time.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit: Player who is attempting to not pay his amount due the
bookie. They often attempt to avoid the bookies by changing their
phone numbers or even addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Expert: Person who claims to be able to correctly predict
outcomes of sporting events, especially football games. Also called
``Touts,'' they charge for giving out information on a recorded
message.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 1313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
