r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-RECOVERY-TEX     12-06 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-RECOVERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU BET YOUR LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The writer is a 48-year-old compulsive gambler in recovery,
who has worked in the communications field since he was 18. He
gambled from the time he was 20 until he was 40, stopping Dec. 8,
1990. Because he's a member of Gamblers Anonymous, his name cannot
be used.''
</P>
<P>
   There are mornings I wake up and think about making a bet.
</P>
<P>
   They're usually days when there's a big game _ a Super Bowl or
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   And then I think about a few other things.
</P>
<P>
   I think about how much money I lost, making bets on ``sure
things.''
</P>
<P>
   I think about eight years ago, when I turned 40, and had no
savings, no possessions that were truly mine.
</P>
<P>
   I think about the look of terror and defeat on my wife's face
when she discovered by accident that ``we'' were more than four
years' salary in debt.
</P>
<P>
   I think about two friends who committed suicide, and several
others who could have died if fate hadn't intervened.
</P>
<P>
   I think about my father turning his back on me and sadly saying
eight years ago, ``I love you, but I've never respected you.''
</P>
<P>
   And I go another day without making that bet.
</P>
<P>
   I lied, broke laws and nearly drove my wife into a nervous
breakdown. I've hurt those who are close to me, financially and
emotionally. I've been awake at 5 a.m., my heart thumping, because
I knew I couldn't pay the bookie or the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, the bookie was always more important. Because not
paying him meant I couldn't continue to bet.
</P>
<P>
   And that was unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   I'd wake up in the morning after losing several thousand dollars
the night before and swear to myself I'd never do it again. Then,
that afternoon, I'd make 20 or 30 more bets, knowing that I'd be on
the road to getting even.
</P>
<P>
   After the first couple of years, I wanted to stop, or at least
frequently told myself I wanted to. But I was unable to. Denial was
one reason, although there were other factors.
</P>
<P>
   If I were an alcoholic or a drug addict, my addiction would have
become obvious to the people close to me because of physical
reasons, if nothing else. But a compulsive gambler rarely shows any
physical effects, other than a lack of sleep or shortness of
temper.
</P>
<P>
   As with most addictions, however, accessibility and availability
creates the potential for problems. As I got older I had more
spending money.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 15 years, I went on a progressive downhill slide.
In my early 20s, I was making two or three bets a week, usually for
about $25 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   When we were living in San Francisco and the earthquake hit in
1989, the first thing I worried about was my wife. Second _ and it
was only minutes later _ I worried about the major bet I had on the
World Series, wondering if the games would be played. I didn't care
about the people who had suffered. My bet was my concern.
Truthfully, if the earthquake had happened a year later, my wife
would ``not'' have been my first concern.
</P>
<P>
   Then, about two years later, I got caught.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, in December 1990, I was betting every game on the
board. At that point, the bets ranged from $5 to thousands of
dollars. The action was what mattered, not the cost.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I went on vacation, and when we returned, she found
the bills I was usually able to hide. She started to call the
police, thinking that somebody had stolen our credit cards. When I
confessed, she broke down.
</P>
<P>
   She told me that she was probably going to divorce me and
possibly turn me into the police. She said she would ``definitely''
do that if I didn't start going to Gamblers Anonymous meetings. She
was determined to save herself, but wanted me to save myself as
well.
</P>
<P>
   With those threats hanging over my head, I attended my first
meeting. I was tired of the gambling, weary of the lying, depressed
by the losses. So for me, an alternative was welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, eight years later, it's a different life. The bills are
paid, the emotional fences are mended, we even bought a house a
year ago. I attend meetings at least once a week, which sometimes
is difficult since there are just three meetings in the entire Fort
Worth-Dallas area.
</P>
<P>
   I still think about making a bet from time to time, but the
consequences aren't something I want to deal with _ at least not at
this point in my life.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing, is I now have piece of mind. The phone
rings and I don't scramble to answer it. The mail comes and I don't
run out the door to get it before my wife can. I sleep well _ and
so does the rest of my family.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy, but I've never gone back, not even for a $1
lottery ticket or a Pepsi on a baseball game. But I could. I could
tomorrow, and I know that if I do, normal life will end for me, and
the nightmare will begin again. And will probably get worse.
</P>
<P>
   My father died five years ago Christmas Eve. Shortly before his
death, he said to me, ``I love you. And now, I respect you.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope I never betray that trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
