<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS DOESN'T GUARANTEE SUCCESS, MAY RESTRICT FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Clemens is 36, and he has pitched in one World Series
during his 15-year career.
</P>
<P>
   He's definitely a No. 1 pitcher in any rotation. But he will not
offer guaranteed success to the team that acquires him and anyone
that does will have to give up talent that's both equal and _
understand this carefully _ much younger.
</P>
<P>
   That has to be realized by the people who are mindlessly
screaming to go get Clemens, once again believing he will be the
Rangers' ``final piece of the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring Clemens might get the Rangers to the World Series.
However there's a greater possibility it could turn the Rangers
into a mirror image of the Baltimore Orioles: a team with a
free-spending owner, great ballpark, a bloated payroll and a
hodge-podge of great talent, good enough to contend but not good
enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave them in the vicious never-ending cycle they've
been in since 1986, when manager Bobby Valentine interrupted a
major rebuilding program by winning 87 games and deluded the
franchise into thinking they were getting close.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers are going to trade Ivan Rodriguez, they ought to
trade him to a team that can give them two or three great young
pitching prospects in return. Then you go out and sign Terry
Steinbach and have done two things: kept yourself competitive and
still made the future look a whole lot brighter.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, in seven years this team could be loaded with
All-Star outfielders Ruben Mateo and Mike Zywica, second baseman
Kelly Dransfeldt and catcher Cesar King ... and still be looking
for starting pitching. RANDOM OBSERVATIONS The continued escalation
of salaries is final proof the devastating 1994 players strike that
forced cancellation of the World Series and ripped apart the
public's trust accomplished absolutely nothing. Zero. The rich
still get richer and the poor have absolutely no chance. And the
poor substantially outnumber the rich.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox owner Jerry Reinsdorf admitted two years ago that
signing Albert Belle to a $55 million contract would spell death to
the small-market clubs. Little did he know that he would be signing
his own club's death warrant. Welcome to the poor side of town,
Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   Three keys to the Rangers having strong leadership in 1999:
Rusty Greer emerging out of Will Clark's shadow, Mark McLemore
being healthy and happy again, and Rafael Palmeiro building the
bridge that brings Ivan Rodriguez and Juan Gonzalez back to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro was docked $4 million per year for not being perceived
as a leader. That's the difference in pay between him and Mo
Vaughn, who's considered the consummate leader. Responded Palmeiro,
``I'm a quiet leader. When it's time to take charge, I lead by
example.'' Cal Ripken Jr. is the only player in the Baltimore
Orioles lineup who was originally drafted by the club. Designated
hitters Chris Hoiles and Willie Greene, catcher Charles Johnson and
outfielder Brady Anderson were acquired in trades and outfielders
Albert Belle and B.J. Surhoff, shortstop Mike Bordick, second
baseman Delino DeShields and first baseman Will Clark were added as
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will move on Clemens mainly out of fear that the
Indians will get him and have that long-needed No. 1 starter.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown is taking his sweet time on deciding where he'll
play next year. Agent Scott Boras is most likely waiting until the
winter meetings next weekend in Nashville, Tenn., when he has all
general managers assembled in one spot and can drive up the price.
Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash will probably take the same
approach with Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks owner Jerry Colangelo hired some of the best
front-office talent around, including Sandy Johnson, Roland Hemond
and Mel Didier. But he has now has apparently decided to take the
Wayne Huizenga route to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have quietly done a nice job of improving an 88-74 team
from last year. But this may be manager Bobby Valentine's last
chance. If he doesn't get into the playoffs after the money being
spent by the Mets owners, he could have a hard time keeping his
job. The pressure from the New York media is getting intense.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Johnson did not hit well last year, but he's still a
superb defensive catcher with some offensive potential. The Dodgers
are making a huge mistake if they think they're better off with
Todd Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Johnson, he won four consecutive Gold Gloves in the
National League. Being traded to Baltimore puts him in direct
competition with Rodriguez, who has won the last seven catching
awards in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Hall of Fame ballot includes not one but three
ex-Rangers pitchers on for the first time: Nolan Ryan, Charlie
Leibrandt and Frank Tanana. Bert Blyleven is on for a second time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
