<HEADLINE>
PLUS-MINUS DOESN'T ALWAYS ADD UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plus-minus might be the most confusing statistic in the NHL.
Some players even call it inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   And, in truth, simply saying the Flyers' Eric Lindros is the
best player in the NHL because of his plus-18 rating through
Thursday's games is as wrong as saying the Tampa Bay Lightning's
Karl Dykhuis is the worst because of his minus-17 rating.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with plus-minus. When extremes are brought in
and then spread across the spectrum of the NHL, the statistic can
be misleading. But if studied properly, plus-minus can shed a good
deal of light onto the efforts of a player in the framework of his
team.
</P>
<P>
   The basic premise of plus-minus is to measure a player's value
by counting the times he is on the ice for a goal in a ``fair''
situation. For example, in all even-strength situations, goals for
and goals against are counted _ telling whether you are a positive
player or a negative player.
</P>
<P>
   If you're on the power play and score a goal, the goal doesn't
count toward your plus. If you're killing a penalty and an opponent
scores a goal, the goal doesn't count against your minus. It's not
fair to be rewarded when you have the man advantage, the NHL
reasons, or punished when you're a man down. However, if you score
a goal short-handed, you receive a plus and the opposing power play
players receive a minus. Again, it's fair to believe that with the
man advantage, a team shouldn't be scored upon.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the best way to study plus-minus is within a team.
For example, Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk is a plus-8, while
fellow defenseman Sergei Zubov and Darryl Sydor are minus-2 apiece.
Mike Modano is a plus-10, while Joe Nieuwendyk is a minus-3.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams have similar trends. In Anahiem, Stu Grimson is a
plus-3, while fellow tough guy Jim McKenzie is a minus-10. Both
have relatively the same job, so the comparison is easy.
</P>
<P>
   Or take, for example, the Blackhawks' Chris Chelios. On a team
that is literally all minuses, including a minus-9 for leading
scorer Tony Amonte, Chelios is a plus-4. He has to be doing
something right.
</P>
<P>
   Or look at the Flyers. Lindros is plus-18. John LeClair is
plus-16 and most of the team is on the positive side of the ledger.
But center Chris Gratton is a minus-7 and the Flyers are trying to
trade him. That's where the statistic can be really telling.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to the one player who probably deserves more
accolades than any other for plus-minus and yet isn't anywhere
among the league leaders. His Tampa Bay Lightning has six players
in double-digit minuses, including the aforementioned Dykhuis at
minus-17, and yet he has somehow posted a plus-2 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Take a bow Daymond Langkow, now that's an accomplishment. SLAP
SHOTS
KING RED WINGS Whatever problems the Detroit Red Wings have had
this season, Stars fans who hate the Wings shouldn't think the
two-time defending champs are going away easily. They recently went
on a 4-1 run with rookie goalie Norm Maracle leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until somebody takes the Stanley Cup away from the Red Wings,
there's nobody close,'' Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said. ``They're
the best team in the league by 10 miles. I mean, is there any team
in the league that can play four lines and have their starting
goalie out for a period of time and it doesn't bother them at
all?'' He's new at this Tampa Bay Lightning owner Art Williams, who
bought the team from a Japanese coglomerate last season, alreay is
disillusioned with the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Williams called his players ``pansies,'' last week and said, ``I
refuse to sit there and cater to a bunch of overpriced
cry-babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams added: ``This season has been a brutal lesson for me. I
was told we were a few players away from a competitive team, so I
willingly spent even more money than we had budgeted.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who told him that _ GM Phil Esposito _ has since been
fired.
NEW BLOOD
</P>
<P>
   Last week was the one-year anniversary of Canada getting shut
out in the quest for an Olympic hockey medal, and Team Canada GM
Bob Clarke made it clear he's not coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose like we did, I don't think I should get another
crack at it,'' the Flyers GM said. ``Someone else should come in as
a manager.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading candidate to be that someone else is Stars GM Bob
Gainey, who was Clarke's assistant.
TIGHT POCKETS The Penguins, who currently are trying to work out of
bankruptcy court, made their Nov. 30 payroll only because of the
infusion of $2.5 million in cash from trading Petr Nedved to the
Rangers. Now, they're seeking a $20 million loan from a French bank
to make the Dec. 15 payroll.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, the cash value of superstar Jaromir Jagr has to
become a very serious discussion, if NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman
would allow such a trade.
THE BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Conference: John Vanbiesbrouck, who has a 2.03 goals
against average, is receiving credit as the man who could finally
help solve the Flyers' goaltending problems. But a quick look at
the stats reveals coach Roger Nielson might be the real hero. The
Flyers are yielding a league-least 20.3 shots per game under
Nielson's defense-first system. The Stars, who led the NHL last
season, are second in that category at 22.9 shots per game. ...
Sabres winger Rob Ray is the latest NHL player on a long list to
get a suspension, taking a four-game hiatus after slew-footing
Panthers winger Alex Hicks. Slew-footing is intentionally knocking
the legs out from underneath an opposing player, forcing him to
fall, often times on his head. ... The Caps continue to struggle as
Adam Oates and Peter Bondra are in and out of the lineup with
nagging groin injuries. ... The Lightning have talked about
waiving, trading or demoting former Stars winger Benoit Hogue. ...
The Rangers are trying to begin discussions with defenseman Bryan
Leetch on a contract extension. Leetch, who is making up for last
season's horrendous start by scoring 19 points in 24 games, could
become the highest paid defenseman in the league, surpassing Rob
Blake's $5.5 million per season. ... Wayne Gretzky's greatest
nemesis ever is _ Tommy Salo? That's right, the Islanders young
goalie had not yielded a goal to Gretzky in nine games, the longest
The Great One had been shut out by a goalie. But Gretzky ended that
streak last week, scoring in a 3-2 Rangers' win on Wednesday. ...
Former Stars defenseman Kevin Hatcher is supposedly next on the
trading block for the Penguins, who need to unload all the salary
they can. The older brother of Stars captain Derian Hatcher, Kevin
is actually having a decent season with 16 points and a plus-9
rating. The Kings and Mighty Ducks are said to be interested. ...
The Bruins get no slack at all from their fans. After a 1-1 tie in
Boston on Tuesday, the Fleet Center crowd booed their homeboys, who
dropped all the way to 6-1-4 in an 11-game span with the tie. ...
Just one more reason why the Maple Leafs are surprising everyone _
No. 2 center Igor Korolev has six goals among 20 points and is a
plus 10.
</P>
<P>
   Western Conference: If there was any debate that the Kings' Rob
Blake was the most valuable defenseman in the NHL last season, it's
been put to rest now that Blake is out with a broken right foot and
isn't expected back until the end of the month. The Kings have gone
1-9 in their past 10 games, and in seven of those games scored one
or fewer goals, leading one to believe that their injured goalies
are not the problem. ... After posting a league-best 11-game
point-scoring streak, Mighty Ducks winger Paul Kariya was held
without a point in three consecutive games. ... The Coyotes saw
their 14-game unbeaten streak end in a 4-3 loss to Edmonton, but
made the Oilers work for it. Oilers goalie Mikhail Shtalenkov had
45 saves in the win. ... The Coyotes also fell short of tying an
NHL record. They had allowed two goals or fewer in 18 consecutive
games before giving up four. The record for consecutive games of
two goals or fewer is 19 set by the Montreal Canadiens in 1958-59.
... Blues goalie Grant Fuhr is back on the ice practicing after
injuring his groin Nov. 7. His return date is up in the air, but
he's ahead of the original prognosis of six weeks. Fuhr was 3-1-2
with a 2.06 GAA and a .915 save percentage when he was injured. ...
Sharks winger Owen Nolan has scored two goals in his past 35
regular season games. ... Sharks goalie Steve Shields is getting no
help. Shields has a 2.00 GAA and a .924 save percentage, but is
just 1-2-2.
THE WEEK AHEAD
Tuesday: Flyers at Devils _ Two favorites to battle for East crown
give fans a juicy preview. Thursday: Devils at Flyers _ With a
little bad blood going after one meeting two days earlier, this one
could be even juicier. Saturday: Red Wings at Hurricanes _
Hurricanes owner Peter Karmanos still loves to beat Red Wings owner
Mike Ilitch at anything. Plus, this is about the only team that can
fill the Greensboro Coliseum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
