<HEADER>
A5284 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN07-COX     12-06 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A book policymakers can't ignore
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Emory University welcomed William Bowen to Atlanta
last week. Bowen, former president of Princeton University, is
co-author of the book, ``The Shape of the River,'' which documents
through meticulous research the positive impact of affirmative
action on college admissions. The book shows that numbers of black
students admitted to highly selective schools would be sliced in
half even today if race were not allowed to be used as one of many
factors in admission policies.
</P>
<P>
   Emory President William Chace said the book confirms what he's
always believed: that race-conscious college admissions have worked
to the good of America by producing black professionals and
community leaders and encouraged the growth of a healthy black
middle class. Emory, many of whose graduates were interviewed for
the study, was a private school pioneer _ suing successfully 36
years ago to overturn state legislation barring private schools
from receiving tax exemptions if it admitted blacks. Now the
school, blessed with Coca-Cola benefactors, has a higher percentage
of African-American students and faculty than any among the top 25
with which Emory ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there were no lawmakers at Bowen's lecture. I
wished privately that he had been invited to speak at the upcoming
orientation for state legislators at the University of Georgia.
They could do with some real facts to shoot down the myths spouted
year after year on the floor on the General Assembly:
</P>
<P>
   _ Affirmative action harms blacks by denigrating their ability
to compete.
</P>
<P>
   _ Affirmative action equals quotas (outlawed by the U.S. Supreme
Court years ago _ and not supported by Bowen or his co-author,
former Harvard President Derek Bok).
</P>
<P>
   _ Affirmative action is no longer needed and should be replaced
by economic disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   All of those arguments are dismissed with scholarly data that
can be dissected in a million ways and still hold. African-American
male graduates of Ivy League schools, with identical skills,
experience and positions, still make an average of $8,000 less per
year than white counterparts. The differential is, of course,
greater for less well-educated and less skilled.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue that caught my attention in the book and in
Bowen's talk is the examination of the meaning of ``merit,''
probably because I've heard so many politicians repeat the tired
line that all students should be judged on merit, as if that had
never happened. It's the standard rhetoric for Georgia Rep. Earl
Ehrhart who proposes a bill every year to abolish what few
affirmative action programs remain in Georgia schools and agencies.
His bill would do away with the minimal program at the University
of Georgia, which includes race as one of 16 criteria for 10
percent of incoming freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Surely merit was never meant to be limited to test scores,
though. It includes drive, achievement, determination, character, a
hundred other factors. Certainly African-American students (whose
scores met the minimum requirement for admission) were accepted
over some whites whose scores were higher. But so were some white
students with lower scores than whites who were rejected. There's
no way around subjectivity in competitive admissions decisions, and
there shouldn't be. Merit assessment is forward looking, predictive
of college and post-college performance. Admissions policies
consider how students individually and collectively will enhance
the educational experience and the institution.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowen-Bok book should be required reading for policymakers.
But I can say with certainty it won't be. Those who oppose
affirmative action, be they Californians or Georgians, aren't open
to real data. The excuse under the Georgia Gold Dome will be, it's
just a bunch of Yankee eggheads trying to lord it over us again.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
