</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Opposites attract when politicians label
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore recently touted his political philosophy,
which he called ``practical idealism.'' He is road-testing this
phrase for the 2000 presidential election when he might have to put
it up against the ``compassionate conservatism'' of Texas Gov.
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a choice between practical idealism and compassionate
conservatism, an idealistically cynical voter could be clearly
flummoxed.
</P>
<P>
   This is not anything new. The tradition of politicians straining
language and credulity to advance logically opposed ideas is long
and distinguished.
</P>
<P>
   In Roman times, the Emperor Augustus wasn't a strongman, boss,
mack daddy or maximum head of human resources. He liked to describe
himself modestly as ``primus inter pares,'' first among equals.
</P>
<P>
   Whiners may have quietly asked how someone can be both first and
equal. In practice, this was decided easily enough. The equal who
ran the Roman army could be as equal as he wanted to be. Still, as
political fictions go, this one proved soothing and still sounds
just fine after 2,000 years of use.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, currently second among equals at the White House, says his
phrase is meant to convey a philosophy that ``applies the values of
the past to the amazing opportunities of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the best of opposites. Like a telescope fitted with a
rearview mirror, it certainly would be versatile, but your eyes get
blurry imagining how it would work.
</P>
<P>
   Such an instrument could prove a hard sell against compassionate
conservatism, which means Republicans will no longer take pleasure
in what they have to do to folks so taxes can be low, people who
live wrong can be punished and profits maximized.
</P>
<P>
   A hard choice for voters here. Particularly voters who are
restlessly complacent, cautiously optimistic or raging moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Opposites are attractive in other labels as well.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is a practical idealist because he is a New Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   This means he's a member of the world's oldest continuously
operating political party, but in a new way. Being new means he's
not like '70s Democrats but more like the Democrats we remembered
before the last generation of Democrats. Not an Old Democrat, but
more like an Old, Old Democrat _ which now is new. Or was new until
it started to get old.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, is a Big-Tent Republican. This should not be
confused with the clowns of Big-Top Republicanism but it still
evokes images of elephants in a circus.
</P>
<P>
   Compassionate conservatives want a big tent but small
government. Grouchy, old-fashioned conservatives want a small tent
with the right kind of people, no tent taxes and the right to pitch
it in a wetland if they feel like it. And smoke as they do so.
</P>
<P>
   Many Small-Tent Republicans are young fogies, conservative
revolutionaries and new traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be gullibly skeptical about these claims. But I
believe Bush can be compassionate and Gore both new and improved.
I'll trust but verify, as former President Reagan promised to do
when he was being tough but fair.
</P>
<P>
   I do this because I have taken to heart the words of former
Florida Gov. Bob Martinez when he promised, in his legislative
dealings, to be ``firm but flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   This phrase sowed confusion among a literal-minded capital press
corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean, like Gumby?'' asked one reporter, vainly trying to
recall any other exemplar of firm flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter was not trying to be helpful. He was being
playfully hostile. But he was on to something. Gumby is
demonstrably both flexible and firm _ you can bend any toy Gumby to
prove it. And he might be animal, mineral or vegetable. Who can
say? Surely, this is an apt but ambiguous political symbol for our
age.
</P>
<P>
   Whether anyone will have the foresight and copyright to run with
this remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I look forward to the next election with
fearful anticipation. Any battle between practical idealism and
compassionate conservatism could prove seriously amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
