<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digesting the idea of a spagetti junction in Lufkin
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ The big news in my little hometown is that the
interstate highway system has finally found its way here, some 40
or 50 years after cementing together most everywhere else in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Folks in favor of the interstate say it's for the common good of
the common man. Of course, folks in favor of the Mobil-Exxon merger
are likely to say much the same.
</P>
<P>
   Lufkin's not exactly isolated, off here in the Pineywoods of
Deep East Texas. Granted, the nearest existing interstates are 100
miles in most any direction. Never mind that the airlines won't fly
here.
</P>
<P>
   If you're coming to Lufkin from afar, best bet is to fly to
Houston or Shreveport and then rent a car for the two-hour drive.
It's not that convenient for everybody. But in the past it's helped
to deter big-city corporate-baggers from giving us more attention
than we would appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   We've got highways, sure enough. Paved, too. Not counting the
pot holes, of course. I doubt if anybody could count the pot holes,
especially on U.S. 59 between here and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   That highway has a certain Third World charm. You'd almost think
you were in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, U.S. 59 is on its way to Mexico. Thanks to NAFTA,
the traffic is something akin to wall-to-wall diesel trucks backed
up most all the way to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the purpose of the proposed interstate, dubbed I-69, a
major trade route for the NAFTA traffic that's taking our business
south.
</P>
<P>
   Lufkin's leaders have been all for it. Otherwise, the world
might pass us by, without so much as honking.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the preferred route will swing east of the city,
cutting a swath through farms, ranches and rural settlements. What
used to be out in the country is now going to be under an
underpass.
</P>
<P>
   I'm waiting for our first cloverleaf intersection to open up for
local traffic. That'll be something to see, especially in a town
where most drivers have yet to master the principle of four-way
stop signs.
</P>
<P>
   But I've seen it all before, to lesser degrees.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a young boy, the highway traffic came straight
through downtown on First Street. Back then, there was a service
station on every other corner.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays there's only one left along that same route.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of Timberland Drive, the four-lane bypass that
opened in 1950. The cafes and service stations followed in swift
pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Funny story that most everybody has forgotten, how Timberland
Drive got its name.
</P>
<P>
   Several names of prominent leaders had been put forth for the
honor. So it was that the powers that be decided to let the people
choose, in the form of an election, as to who among the prominent
was the most favored. The choice of Timberland Drive was added to
the ballot as an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what won by a wide majority. Timberland Drive, by any
other name, was None Of The Above Drive.
</P>
<P>
   A loop followed in the 1960s and '70s, and business stretched
itself accordingly. I expect much the same when the interstate
arrives.
</P>
<P>
   I have every hope of living to see that day, assuming that
between now and then I don't get run over at one of our four-way
stops.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
