A5287 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASKET-HOLD-DEATH07-C     12-06 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASKET-HOLD-DEATH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mental health officials try to get a hold on `basket' restraint
misuse
 &HT;    By William Cooper Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Unless national standards for training
and the use of physical restraint are developed, state and national
experts believe more people like 17-year-old Laura Hanson will die.
</P>
<P>
   Police are still investigating Hanson's death, which was ruled a
homicide by asphyxia. She died at on Nov. 19 after two employees
put her in the controversial ``basket hold,'' a restraint that has
lead to the deaths of mental health patients across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Child Welfare League of America, the nation's oldest child
advocacy organization, is pushing for national standards regarding
the use of restraint, said Lloyd Bullard, director of residential
care for the Washington-based nonprofit agency. Bullard said the
group wants federal legislation that will require training and
mandatory reporting of restraint deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to influence the legislation if we can,'' Bullard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Low pay and poor training are contributing factors to the
restraint deaths, he said. Typically, the workers who are in direct
contact with the patients and have to administer the restraint are
paid anywhere from $15,000 to $17,000, Bullard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find that some of these direct-care workers are competing
with the fast-food workers when it comes to salaries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the staff members who restrained Hanson have not
been released, nor has their training, experience and salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bullard believes the lack of national standards for the use of
restraint has left mental health officials to police themselves.
Without federal regulation, the oversight varies from state to
state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He and other advocates want a system that tracks restraint
deaths and specific training measures for mental health employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to ban restraint use. We can't allow clients to
endanger themselves or others,'' Bullard said. ``I think the real
focus has to be on national standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drawback has been a lack of money. If the federal
government creates standards, there also should be money offered to
centers for staff training.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, states such as Florida look to experts such as Dr.
John Ward, the clinical director at the Florida Mental Health
Institute at the University of South Florida in Tampa. Ward and his
colleagues crafted a form of restraint called T.E.A.M. _ Techniques
for Effective Aggression Management.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was developed a decade ago in response to a boy who
died while being restrained at a state juvenile detention center
near Tampa, Ward said. The T.E.A.M. approach calls for the patient
to be restrained by more than one person, and places emphasis on
monitoring the patient's ability to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person can talk, then they're breathing,'' Ward said.
``You leave room for the chest to expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward estimates some 60,000 mental health professionals have been
trained nationally in the T.E.A.M. approach.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, the Department of Children and Families regulates
mental health centers and approves the types of restraint they can
use, Ward said. In the T.E.A.M. approach, staff members must
undergo 18 to 20 hours of training before they're eligible to
assist in the use of restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers in the T.E.A.M. concept need another 18 to 20 hours of
training, along with teaching the technique while being observed by
panel of peers.
</P>
<P>
   The South County Mental Health Center in Delray Beach uses the
T.E.A.M. concept, said Jeffrey Lefton, an administrator at the
facility. The South County center has a special unit for youngsters
who need immediate stabilization because they've gone into a mental
health crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson was restrained by employees after she got into a fight
with her 15-year-old roommate. After refusing to calm down, two
employees placed her in the basket hold for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Those workers are on paid administrative leave until the
investigation is finished. The state and the National Alliance for
the Mentally Ill of Palm Beach County are reviewing if the
employees were properly trained in the use of restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from DCF's alcohol, drug abuse and mental health
division visited the center last week.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Suresh Rajpara, the center's medical director, said the
staff members have been trained in crisis prevention techniques,
but he would not elaborate on the training procedures or the amount
of training received by the employees involved in Hanson's death.
</P>
<P>
   The basket hold is a technique commonly used in mental health
centers, Bullard said. The hold becomes deadly when the patient is
placed face-down, pressure is placed on the backs and the patient's
arms are criss-crossed over the chest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the police nor the center have revealed Hanson's
position when she died.
</P>
<P>
   Any time someone dies while being restrained it affects the
entire mental health industry, said Linda Steiger, president of the
Crisis Prevention Institute in Wisconsin. The backlash can lead to
fear among the parents of patients to a chilling-affect among staff
members who must work with the clients.
</P>
<P>
   CPI, which is one of the nation's leaders in crisis management,
teaches nonviolent techniques as well as physical restraint. The
primary goal of the program is to certify employees to return to
their jobs and teach other staff members, Steiger said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees are taught to use as many methods as possible to bring
calm to a situation without having to use restraint. However, when
restraint is necessary, the events usually happen quickly, Steiger
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why using restraint must be the choice of last resort,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your adrenalin is pumping,'' Steiger said. ``You really don't
know what's going to happen next.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
