<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRIKES07-COX     12-06 1713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIKES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two-strikes laws often lack intended impact
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Half-brothers Maurice Bentley and Anton Tukes were
convicted of raping their sisters. Under the mandatory state
sentencing law, they should have gotten 10-year prison sentences.
Instead, they got one year and have been free since February.
</P>
<P>
   And the man accused of the October slaying of five people,
including three downtown Hilton hotel guests, should have been in
jail, about one-third of his way through a 10-year term for
aggravated sodomy. Instead, he was on 10 years' probation. Faced
with a weak case because the victim didn't want to testify against
Timothy Carl Dawson, the state had to offer a probation term in
exhange for a plea, said former Fulton County Assisstant District
Attorney Charles Smegal.
</P>
<P>
   Since the state sentencing law took effect in 1995 in response
to public pressure to get tougher on crime, there have been at
least 130 cases _ about one in 20 _ in which violent felons have
escaped the mandatory minimum sentence for convictions under the
so-called ``two strikes'' law, said Deputy State Attorney General
Mary Beth Westmoreland.
</P>
<P>
   The lesser sentences go against Gov. Zell Miller's 1994 pledge
to make Georgia's sentencing laws the nation's toughest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply cannot understand why any judge, who is sworn to
uphold the law, won't follow it when it's plainly written in black
and white,'' said Miller. ``I continue to be alarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   And the lawyer who researched all the nation's two-strikes and
three-strikes laws found weaknesses in virtually every state,
including Georgia _ one of only two that actually enforced the law,
even on a limited basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of the law seems to be irrelevant,'' said Walter
Dickey, special counsel to the nonprofit Campaign for an Effective
Crime Policy, which funded the research.
</P>
<P>
   But even as some prosecutors and judges are not enforcing the
mandatory minimum sentences for the crimes listed in the Georgia
Sentencing Reform Act, some policy-makers are talking about
limiting judges' discretion even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we need to get this one that we have on the
books now straight first,'' said Attorney General Thurbert Baker,
who, as a legislator, sponsored the two strikes law for Governor
Miller. ``I just wish people would follow the law.''
</P>
<P>
   What the law says
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 act says anyone convicted of armed robbery, kidnapping,
aggravated child molestation, aggravated sodomy, rape or aggravated
sexual battery must spend at least 10 years in prison and cannot be
paroled. A second conviction for any of those six felonies or for
murder _ known collectively as the seven deadly sins _ demands life
without parole.
</P>
<P>
   The language of the statute is precise: There must be prison
time, and probation is forbidden if any of those crimes were
committed after Jan. 1, 1995. The inmate cannot be pardoned or
paroled and the sentence cannot be commuted.
</P>
<P>
   But it often doesn't happen that way.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 16-year-old Johnathan Davis, who admitted to sexual
assault for fondling a 13-year-old girl, should have gotten a
10-year sentence. Instead, he received two years and will be free
late next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the president of the District Attorneys Association of
Georgia can explain why the law isn't being followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a prosecutor, I would hope _ particularly when it comes to
this type of legislation that makes us the toughest in the nation
on violent criminals _ that all prosecutors and judges would follow
the law,'' said Coweta Judicial Circuit District Attorney Pete
Skandalakis, the association president. ``It's surprising to me
that the mandatory-minimum sentences for the `seven deadly sins'
...are not being enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker says there is no excuse for giving a prison sentence that
does not at least meet the minimum that the law requires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that law was written, if they are charged with one of
those seven deadly sins, they must be sentenced to 10 years to
serve in prison for the first strike and life without parole for
the second,'' Baker said. ``There is no discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   But he admits that there is no way to force judges to follow
comply with the statute, though ``you would expect and hope that
the judges would follow the law. I'm sort of surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,375 inmates have been convicted of one of the seven
deadly sins since the law took effect in 1995. But judges did not
follow sentencing requirements in 130 cases. When the state
attorney general's office pointed out the illegal sentences, local
judges revised 10 of them. Yet, 70 of that 130 are still serving a
term less than the required life without parole for a second
offense. And another 50 _ like Tukes, Bentley and Davis _ have been
sentenced to fewer than 10 years for their first conviction. Seven
of those 50 so-called first-strikers are already out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they have no way of knowing how many violent
felons on probation should be in prison under the ``two strikes
law.'' Their computer records only show the date the sentence was
returned, not when the crime was committed. The law is based on the
date of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections spokesman Scott Stallings said ``it would be
reasonable to assume that there is a small number of offenders who
received probation instead of the mandatory prison sentence called
for in the seven deadly sins legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   A response to pressure
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing problem became apparent soon after the law took
effect. In September 1996, Miller sternly wrote prosecutors and
judges, reminding them of the highly publicized and popular law.
Some sentences were corrected, either by resentencing the defendant
under the guidelines or downgrading the charges so the law did not
apply.
</P>
<P>
   Lowndes County District Attorney David Miller said prosecutors
and judges have no choice but to comply with the mandatory-minimums
that are now law, but he worried that more structured sentences
could present a problem. He expects the state's prosecutors to make
a make a joint statement later this month protesting more
mandatory-minimums
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us less discretion to deal with these folks,'' Miller
said. ``A lot of people would feel better about the criminal
justice system if there was more truth in setencing. The numbers
(of years sentenced and actual years served) should be closer. The
Georgia sentencing laws have been changed in such a hodgepodge way,
maybe it's just time to go back and look at the entire sentencing
schedule and redo it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some prosecutors, judges and criminal justice experts have
suggested that the range of prison time available might be reduced
so that the actual time served would more closely resemble the
court sentence. For example, a judge can sentence a burglar to one
year in prison or as much as 20 years in prison. Prosecutor Miller
says the range of 1 to 20 years in some case and five to 30 years
for other crimes may be too much and should be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   That might improve the public perception that criminals serve
only a portion of their sentences even though the time might be
more than what is doled out in other states for the same crime,
said Rep. Denny Dobbs (D-Covington), who has been working on a
sentencing reform proposal since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolism vs. substance
</P>
<P>
   ``Our criminal justice policy should not be based on symbolism,
but on substance,'' Northeastern Judicial Circuit Judge John
Giradeau told the Dobbs at a meeting this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs, chair of the House committee that oversees the state
prison system, plans to offer a report with substative
recommendations for reform to the General Assembly before his term
ends in January and he leaves the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is tired of all the publicity they have seen about
violent criminals being released on parole or getting probation,''
Dobbs said. ``The two-strikes law was a response to public pressure
to do something about violent offenders and habitual offenders.''
</P>
<P>
   In all the cases of illegal sentences, the punishment was part
of a negotiated plea. Prosecutors say it was the best alternative,
given that a jury most likely would have acquitted the defendant
because the case was weak. Judges _ like the one who gave Tukes and
Bentley invalid sentences _ said they ordered an invalid prison
sentence because the prosecutor recommended it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One size fits all laws'' are a problem, said Eastern Judicial
Circuit Superior Court Judge John E. Morse Jr., who sentenced
Bentley and Tukes to two years for rape instead of 10 in the
Savannah case. ``Mandatory-minimums can be helpful, and they can be
quite a hindrance. With them in place, you don't have discretion,
which tends to take the pressure off. But at the same time, when
discretion is needed, you don't have it. It's a double-edged sword.
''
</P>
<P>
   Invalid sentences not always clear
</P>
<P>
   When sentencing standards are not followed, the Department of
Corrections is supposed to refuse to pick up the inmates from the
county jails. But Westmoreland of the AG's office said the invalid
sentences are not always obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs said he has heard in his House hearings that prosecutors
and judges oppose structured sentencing, especially any system like
those in other states that reduce or eliminate prison time for the
less serious crimes. Perhaps, Dobbs said, more mandatory-minimum
sentences is not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judges want to be judges. They want to weigh the merits of
a particular offense and assign punishment to a particular
criminal,'' Dobbs said.
</P>
<P>
   And some prosecutors agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence that my colleagues and judges will come up
with more appropriate decisions than a hard and fast rule,'' said
John Pridgen, the district attorney for Cordeale Judicial Circuit
in South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that leaving some discretion, with the possiblity that
the felon will serve only a portion of a sentence, might be better
than giving them shorter sentences with no parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather see them do three years on a 10-year sentence
than18 months on an 18-month sentence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
