<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TX-LAWMAKER-PENSION07     12-06 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-LAWMAKER-PENSION07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas lawmakers reap plentiful reward for their work _ after
they retire
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ During his first eight years in office, Texas
paid state Rep. Charles Finnell $400 a month to make laws. For the
next 21 years, the state paid him a princely $600 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Finnell's constituents fired him.
</P>
<P>
   Come January, Texas will set him up with a retirement package
worth about $5,700 a month, or more than $68,500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Life in the below-minimum-wage Texas Legislature is not all that
lucrative. But ahhhh, the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving with no sour grapes whatsoever toward the
legislative process,'' said Finnell, who plans to meet with state
officials this week to craft his retirement package.
</P>
<P>
   Texas pays longtime lawmakers more to stop making laws than they
were paid to make laws. The lucrative retirement plan was created
by lawmakers in 1975, and next year it will be very, very good to
an unusually high number of longtime legislators who are leaving
office.
</P>
<P>
   The newly retired, as well as those already on the plan, also
will benefit from an increase approved this year by the Employees
Retirement System board.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is lucrative because lawmakers made it that way. In
1975 (Finnell likes to point out that he was not in the Legislature
that year), lawmakers voted to tie their retirement checks to state
district judges' salaries, which are set by the Legislature.
Lawmakers contribute 8 percent of their token-payment paychecks
(now $7,200 a year) into the retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-legislators who served at least eight years _ those who
retired voluntarily and those retired by the voters _ qualify for
the pension plan at age 60. Lawmakers who hang on for 12 years
qualify at age 50.
</P>
<P>
   For each year of service, they get credit for 2.25 percent of
state district judges' salary _ currently $101,700 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sept. 1, the multiplier was 2 percent. The increase
amounts to a 12.5 percent raise for retirees. A retired lawmaker
who was getting $50,000 before Sept. 1, for example, now gets an
additional $6,250 a year. The Employees Retirement System, not the
Legislature, enacted the increase. The Retirement System increased
the multiplier to match an increase the Legislature approved last
year for the state employees retirement plan _ which is not keyed
to the high-dollar judicial salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Finnell, ousted last month in a 257-vote loss (out of 29,451
cast) to Republican Rick Hardcastle of Vernon, thinks the system he
is about to cash in on is a bad one. He believes lawmakers'
pensions should be keyed to teachers' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many legislative pensioners, Finnell says he is going
home to his family's oil field business. Many ex-lawmakers hang
around Austin and become lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   And, for many of them, the legislative retirement money offers a
nice side income. That really grates on the government do-gooder
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary numbers from an upcoming report by Texans for Public
Justice show that 56 ex-lawmakers who lobbied during the 1997
legislative session pulled in more than $1.4 million in state
pension checks.
</P>
<P>
   That's an average of about $25,430. And that's above the state's
per capita income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because too many ex-legislators can't resist the premiums they
command as influence peddlers, the Texas Legislature suffers a
split personality,'' said Craig McDonald of Texans for Public
Justice. ``Formally, it is the body that sets the laws of the land.
Informally, it's the state's premier finishing school for
lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Rep. Hugo Berlanga of Corpus Christi is among the recent
graduates of the finishing school. He resigned his House seat last
May after 21 years and joined the lobby corps.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on top of the money he earns lobbying, Berlanga, who hit
the magic 50 in August, is entitled to a retirement package worth
about $48,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   It's nuts, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a system where legislators in Texas were compensated
adequately for their work we probably wouldn't have a retirement
system that is totally upside down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers' salaries aren't the only component in their
compensation package. Legislators also receive a per diem, now $95
a day during a legislative session. That could go up this week,
just in time for the 76th Legislature, which convenes Jan. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Ethics Commission, at a meeting scheduled for Friday,
is expected to approve a staff proposal to increase the per diem to
$119, the new maximum allowed by the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   The system is screaming for scrutiny, says Tom Smith, Texas
director of Public Citizen, a government watchdog group that has
been barking for years about the state's low-pay Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to lawmaking, you get what you pay for, according
to Smith. You're better off paying them now _ the form of something
resembling a living wage _ than paying them later, he said, adding
that the current system encourages all manner of inappropriate
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives good members _ good members who should stay in the
Legislature _ the wrong incentive,'' Smith said. ``Sometimes they
retire because they can't afford not to. And it keeps bad ones in
because the retirement package is so sweet. You have members who
are bored with it, who don't want to be there, who will continue
for four or six years beyond the time they ought to be there just
so they can get the retirement package.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite consensus that the system is out of whack _ too skimpy
on salary, too generous on retirement benefits _ the public's lack
of interest in a pay hike probably guarantees it will persist.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pushing for a pay raise, a concept rejected with
some regularity by voters, Smith is backing a concept that has even
less of a chance of passing. No pensions for
lawmakers-turned-lobbyists, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only have we trained them how to be great lobbyists at
state expense, but then we continue to give them an allowance after
they are gone and support them while they are raking in hundreds of
thousands of dollars from private interests for going back and
lobbying their old buddies,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald of Texans for Public Justice, has a simpler proposal:
Ban lobbying-for-pay by ex-elected officials. That would be a ban
that could hit close to home for several lawmakers leaving office
this year. A handful of longtime House members are about to make
the transition from low-priced lawmaker to high-dollar retiree.
Some will also be lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the top 10 House members on the longevity list will not
be back. Finnell was defeated. L.P. ``Pete'' Patterson,
D-Brookston, mounted an unsuccessful bid for state agriculture
commissioner. Berlanga and Al Price, D-Beaumont, resigned. Dan
Kubiak, D-Rockdale, died while seeking re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Other senior members not coming back _ as least not as
legislators _ include 18-year veteran Jim Horn, R-Denton, and
16-year veterans Mark Stiles, D-Beaumont, and Allen Hightower,
D-Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   All, save the late Kubiak, are eligible to begin collecting
retirement money. Stiles just made it, turning 50 on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Also heading into legislative retirement is Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock, whose state employment stretches back to his 1957 election
to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, who as the state's No. 2 elected official gets the same
$600 a month that lawmakers receive, has selected a retirement plan
package that provides $58,597 a year, according to his office.
</P>
<P>
   For Bullock and other veteran legislative players, legislative
compensation has long been a tricky issue. The Legislature meets in
regular session every other year for only 140 days. A 1989 effort
to boost the salary to about $22,000 a year went down in flames at
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   So legislators still rely on the retirement plan to, eventually,
augment their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Session after session,'' said Public Citizen's Smith, ``we
find special retirement packages buried in bills at the end of the
session.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Rep. Buzz Robnett, R-Lubbock, won late-night approval
for an amendment that lowered from 55 to 50 the age at which an
ex-lawmaker with eight years on the job can becomes eligible for
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Robnett, now a lobbyist, retired after the session, at age 51.
</P>
<P>
   After taking some public heat for engineering the self-serving
change, Robnett declared, ``I'm at peace with myself because
legislators go through a lot and deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
