<SLUG> BC-WEB-VIAGRA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Health officials make over-the-Web Viagra prescriptions
punishable
 &HT;    By Seth Mnookin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Concerned about the danger of Web sites that
offer Viagra prescriptions without any face-to-face doctor-patient
contact, the state's Board of Medicine said that doctors who
prescribe the drug online could face criminal prosecution or board
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have at least a basic history and physical and an
impotence workup,'' said Dr. Abraham Woods, a Lake Mary urologist
and member of the board. ``This is clearly not an issue you want to
treat lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The area of Internet prescriptions is so new that the board had
never before discussed setting rules for the issue, but the board
made it clear that they frown upon online Viagra prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem, board members said, is that doctors who
prescribe over the Internet know very little about the patient.
Woods said some patients may be impotent as a result of diabetes or
elevated testosterone levels, and therefore Viagra would not be
appropriate. Also, taking Viagra in conjunction with heart medicine
can be extremely dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need follow-up and care, he said. ``You can't just put a
person on medication and leave them out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Prescribing medication without a license is illegal. However,
the board said Friday it is unclear whether a doctor practicing
outside the state needs to have a Florida license to prescribe
medication to a Florida patient.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to set some guidelines, board members said that
regardless of where a doctor practices, he must follow industry
standards when prescribing Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly is the standard of care at least for the initial
prescription that a physical is needed,'' said Dr. Gary Winchester,
a Tallahassee-based board member.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who fail to follow these standards face board
discipline, including suspension and revocation of license.
</P>
<P>
   A board task force will meet Friday to discuss telemedicine, and
the board directed them to specifically examine Internet
prescriptions at that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
