<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reporting minor crimes skews data outcome
 &HT;    By Shannon Joyce
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Grand Junction Police Chief Gary Konzak
raised some eyebrows when he said last week that Grand Junction has
one of the highest crime rates in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Federal crime statistics prove him right.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Junction in 1996 had the third-highest crime rate in
Colorado among cities with more than 10,000 people, according to
the FBI's statistical abstract, Crime in the United States. In
1996, the latest year with available figures, Grand Junction had
100 crimes per 1,000 people. Commerce City, a Denver suburb with
18,500 people, had 105, and Montrose had 104.
</P>
<P>
   To tabulate the total number of crimes committed in a given
area, the FBI compiles the total number of crimes classified as
murder, manslaughter, forcible rape, robbery, aggravated assault,
burglary, larceny and theft and motor vehicle theft.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Junction police Lt. Robert Knight said the way the police
department reports the crimes may give the city a bad rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage people to report all crimes, from petty theft to
murder,'' Knight said. ``The down side of that is it makes the
crime statistics look a little bit ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight said larger cities such as Denver often don't report
smaller thefts like shoplifting a pack of cigarettes, whereas a
smaller police force like Grand Junction includes such a theft in
its crime statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Cobley, a training instructor for the FBI in Denver,
said it's a problem that occurs in all areas of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Cobley and Knight said much of Grand Junction's drug arrests
come because of its location on Interstate 70, a major
cross-country highway. Grand Junction's role as the commercial hub
for the Western Slope adds to the movement of people in and out of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said the city aggressively targets suspected drug
runners, raising the number of arruri and Trinity County, Calif.,
as Y2K friendly.
</P>
<P>
   A Y2K-friendly area is described as being some distance from a
major metropolitan area, having milder winters and moderate summers
and ``safe'' from major known hazards, such as earthquakes and
nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Other pages focus on what a family needs to be prepared should a
computer catastrophe hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Noah's Ark Homesite, for instance, offers everything from
how to organize a 72-hour survival kit to details about long-term
storage and water purification.
</P>
<P>
   The storage of food and water is not new in Western culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has for at least
50 years encouraged church members to keep a supply of food and
water on hand to take care of the family for at least a year in
case of emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has not taken a position relative to the year 2000
but has always suggested to members to provide at least one year's
supply of food and water,'' said Grand Junction LDS West Stake
President Jerry Chadwick. ``Not for a catastrophe but for
emergencies that may come along, if you lose a job. But if the
computers refuse to function after awhile, a year's supply of food
and water would be welcome. ... Members would certainly share with
the neighbors around us if that need should arise.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
