<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Water stocking picks up as year 2000 draws nearer
 &HT;    By C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Someone walked into Deep Rock Crystal
Drop Water in Grand Junction recently, plopped down a couple
hundred dollars and left with enough packaged water to last a year.
</P>
<P>
   Company secretary Carolyn Mitchell said she had a feeling the
man had bought the water in preparation for the year 2000. He was a
new customer she had never seen before. And he wanted the water in
five gallon bottles but had to settle for 2.5-gallon boxes. She
said he estimated he would need five gallons a week.
</P>
<P>
   To some, that isn't even enough water to brush teeth.
</P>
<P>
   To others, though, the coming of the new millennium has provoked
a need to prepare for anything that might come along so storing any
water at all is a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell and representatives of Culligan Water Co
</P>
</TEXT>
