A5407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRIVE-THRU-BAN07-COX     12-06 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVE-THRU-BAN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta considers ban on drive-throughs
 &HT;    By Alfred Charles
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Drive through windows could become a thing of
Atlanta's past starting today when the Atlanta City Council
considers a controversial ordinance that would ban the construction
of new drive-through windows in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, an effort to make the congested city more
pedestrian-friendly and reduce pollution, was introduced by
Councilman Lee Morris and narrowly survived a close vote last week
to make it out of committee.
</P>
<P>
   It has ignited a firestorm of criticism from motorists and
business groups who argue that the legislation is misguided.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a key member of the council said she believes the
measure _ which would affect everything from banks, fast food
restaurants and dry cleaners _ has enough council support to be
approved. It would need eight votes, and then two additional ones
to override a mayoral veto.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, permits for the construction of new drive-through
windows would not be issued. Existing ones could remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't keep building our communities around automobiles,''
said Morris, the Buckhead representative who proposed the idea five
months ago. ``We could the be the first of many more cities to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The town of Carrboro, N.C., recently banned drive-through
windows from its downtown to preserve the area's character. Cities
in California like Santa Monica and Burbank have imposed some
restrictions, but largely for aesthetic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta followed suit, it would be the first major American
city to do so. Morris' legislation would have a profound affect on
Atlanta drivers who, according to experts and recent published
reports, spend more time in their cars than any other metro area in
America, logging an average of 34 miles a day per car and $1.5
billion a year in fuel and time.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, some motorists are opposed to the Morris plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inconvenience and hardship that a drive-through ban would
impose on the average citizen, especially mothers with young
children, senior citizens and people with disabilities, would far
outweigh any benefit to the environment,'' said Martha Hunt, an
Avondale Estates resident who drives into Atlanta often.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has also come under sharp attack from industries
that would be hit hard by the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will create havoc for a lot of businesses and the city will
lose revenue,'' said Robert King, president and chief executive
officer of the Georgia Hospitality &AMP; Travel Association, which
represents the Georgia Restaurant Association. ``The ordinance is
well-intentioned but misguided.''
</P>
<P>
   Some council members agreed, saying the move would stifle
business, especially in southwest Atlanta. ``I want more banks and
institutions that have drive-throughs in my area,'' Councilman Jim
Maddox said during last week's committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Debi Starnes, who usually votes against Morris on
most issues, said she supports his legislation because it would be
a significant step in cleaning up the city's polluted air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encourage Mr. Morris to speak more passionately about it,''
she said. ``I believe it will pass.''
</P>
<P>
   In other matters, the council is expected to act on: legislation
that would impose a $1 surcharge on cellular phone use for Atlanta
customers, money that would be used for the 911 center; ask state
lawmakers to form a 2-year commission that would study allowing
pari-mutel betting and casino gambling, an effort to bring gaming
to Underground Atlanta; and new Civil Service policies for water
workers that will be affected by privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
