<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      12-06 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAYOFFS ARE ON THE RISE, BUT WITHOUT PAST RANCOR
</P>
<P>
   Plant closings, layoffs and forced early retirements are rising
sharply again as evidenced by the cutbacks announced recently at
Bankers Trust, Boeing and Johnson &AMP; Johnson. But the outcries and
conflict that characterized the waves of downsizing in the 1980s
and early 1990s are largely gone. Rather than protest, unions are
more likely to help laid-off members make the transition to other
jobs. And corporate executives no longer call attention to
downsizing as healthy for profits and stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom, Europe's largest phone company, plans to cut
20,000 jobs, or 11 percent of its work force, by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   $7.5 BILLION DEAL SEEN FOR PACIFICORP
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Power PLC is expected to announce Monday that it is
buying Pacificorp, a major provider of power in the Northwest, for
$7.5 billion in stock, people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. GIFT COMES UP SHORT FOR '98
</P>
<P>
   When Ted Turner, the vice chairman of Time Warner, announced
last year that he planned to donate $1 billion to the United
Nations over the next decade, he said the contribution was to come
in annual gifts of $100 million over 10 years. As 1998 nears its
end, he acknowledges that his contribution so far _ $75 million in
Time Warner stock _ has fallen short. But he said he planned to
make up the difference by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   WB EXECUTIVE CONSIDERS LEAVING
</P>
<P>
   Garth Ancier, the president for programming at WB, the growing
fifth network owned by Time Warner, said he would decide by the end
of this week whether to stay with the network or leave when his
contract ends in May.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON.COM TO MAKE REFERRALS
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the online store, is about to introduce a service in
which it will refer its customers to other Internet merchants
selling goods that it does not carry, according to people briefed
by the company on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ TURNS TO POWER OF PCs
</P>
<P>
   The assumption that personal computers could not provide the
performance and reliability of mainframes may be challenged by an
announcement planned for Monday that the Nasdaq stock market
intends to move one of its key systems onto powerful PC server
computers running Microsoft's Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates' portrayal of technology for improving the
readability of text on flat-panel screens as a Microsoft innovation
has set off a debate among some researchers.
</P>
<P>
   PEDDLING `LITERATE SMUT' ON LINE
</P>
<P>
   The online magazine Nerve, which its editor says is in the
business of offering ``literate smut,'' is making a foray into
electronic commerce with gifts like silk pajamas and candles. The
magazine is also seeking to extend its brand name by pushing for a
renaissance of the game Twister.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT EXPANDS INTEGRATED SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Sprint intends to announce Monday that big-business customers
will be able to sign up next month for its integrated
communications technology, which is meant to tie together voice,
data and video networks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
