<HEADER>
A5419 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     12-06 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE GIFT THAT HELPS YOU SAY IT BETTER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So, in the interests &LR;  of creating a more perfect world for the
holidays, you want to whisper a sweet little something into your
honey's ear? Something, perhaps, in which you get across the
message that you don't like his nose hair, or that she ought to do
something about that mustache, or that she talks too much, or that
he interrupts too much?
</P>
<P>
   Gentlehints.com ``stands ready to apprise these individuals in a
gentle, tactful and sensitive manner _ your identity is never
divulged. Your recipient will receive both a thoughtfully worded
letter and an appropriate item to reinforce the message contained
in the letter.'' Most messages cost $7.95, with several exceptions,
including the nose hair warning. The clipping device retails for
more than that, raising the price accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   More information is available at www.gentlehints.com or at (310)
442-9794.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - James Hewitt &LR; , who wrote a kiss-and-tell book about his
affair with  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; , has revealed in the Evening Standard
that he is an alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Joe Humphreys &LR;  wonders whether the Quake City Shuttle coupon
that says a ride for one person is $10, and ``only $18 for up to
two people,'' is an ax murderer's special.? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  - Tucked into invitations for its holiday party, the
advertising agency Deutsch/NY included $5 for cab fare, says
Advertising Age, and a note asking the cab-driver to take the
bearer home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jesse Ventura &LR; 's memoir, ``I Ain't Got Time to Bleed,'' is
the object of a bidding war among New York publishers. The title is
based on a line Ventura spoke in the movie ``Predator.''
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC says the Minnesota Legislature has given its permission
for Ventura to pursue the project. The governor-elect's literary
agent is hoping for at least a million bucks; the manuscript is
promised to publishers in 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   - In response to last week's item about a former member's
disappointment with the Church of Satan, Magister  &UR; Peter Gilmore &LR; 
writes that no membership kit is ever promised by the church. ``For
$100 he gets a membership card _ that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   - The hosiery company Wolford is marketing what it calls the
Waistsock for men. GQ says Wolford is boasting that it provides ``a
perfect fit and exceptional comfort, but to us pantyhose is
pantyhose.''
</P>
<P>
   - Clothing designer  &UR; Vivienne Westwood &LR;  told SOMA magazine that
she finds great pleasure in reading and looking at paintings, but
``I would like to say that all the paintings at the new Getty
museum have been ruined by cleaning. Classic paintings, they are
all ruined. ... Some nerd has cleaned them. If I took your skin, I
wouldn't recognize you, now would I?''
</P>
<P>
   - The notes of apology  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  sent to her Watergate
apartment complex neighbors when she moved out this fall, signed by
her own hand, could fetch $100 to $200 on the autograph market,
reports Washingtonian magazine.  &UR; Caspar Weinberger &LR; , one of the
boys next door, never received his; speculation is that it was
scavenged from his mailbox. Several residents said they planned to
frame the note.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; TELLING A BOOK BY ITS COVER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Book designer  &UR; Michael Ian Kaye &LR; , who works for Little, Brown,
has ``had a galvanizing effect'' on the publisher's success rate,
says the latest issue of the design magazine Metropolis. ``I like
to think that what I'm doing'' with book jackets ``is appealing to
the salesclerks,'' said Kaye, ``the people who unpack the boxes and
put the books on the shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   The crucial result of that appeal, says the magazine, is the
salesperson's placing the book facing out, with its front cover
visible to the shopper.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye's most daring covers, for a set of four gay fiction
anthologies, played with semantic stereotypes: one featured packets
of pansy seeds, another a faggot (a bundle of sticks), another four
queens from a deck of cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wanted those soft sepia photographs of a young man at
a typewriter,'' he said. ``Only a gay art director'' could have
gotten away with it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Oprah believes in the higher potential of this country. It
is &LR; 
 &UR; our good fortune that she has come to a position of &LR; 
 &UR; prominence.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Jonathan Demme &LR;  about  &UR; Oprah Winfrey &LR; , in InStyle magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
