<HEADLINE>
YET ANOTHER PROGRAMMER MUST DECIDE: STAY OR GO?  
 WITH CELEBRITIES IN TOW, PUBLISHERS GO A-COURTING  
 FREEDOM FORUM CHANGES FOCUS OF FELLOWSHIPS  
 IN NEW AUDIENCE SURVEY, CBS GETS A BIT YOUNGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two top network programmers have already left their networks in
the last month, and now a third is close to a decision to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Ancier, the president for programming at WB, the growing
would-be fifth network owned by Time Warner, said he would decide
by the end of this week whether to stay with that network or to
leave when his contract ends in May.
</P>
<P>
   If he does not reach an agreement with WB, Ancier is widely
expected to join NBC as its chief program executive. Last month,
Warren Littlefield left that job and was replaced by Scott Sassa in
an interim move. Sassa is eventually to move up and replace Don
Ohlmeyer as president of NBC's West Coast operations.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Fox appointed Doug Herzog, the president of the
Comedy Central cable channel, to replace Peter Roth, its president
of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in negotiations,'' Ancier said. ``I have to make a
decision whether to stay or not. In the next week, we're going to
figure out whether I'm staying.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancier is among the most experienced programmers in the network
business, having previously worked both at NBC and at Fox, where he
was that network's first executive in charge of programming.
</P>
<P>
   Ancier is contractually obligated to negotiate only with WB
until February, when he can talk to other prospective employers.
But it is extremely unlikely that he will be able to join NBC or
any other company before his contract ends in May. Warner Brothers,
the studio that owns WB, has strictly enforced its contracts with
employees in the past, including its pact with Leslie Moonves, who
was in charge of television production for the studio before going
to CBS to be that network's top programmer.
</P>
<P>
   Ancier said: ``I agree with that. When you sign a contract, it's
the honorable way to see it to the end. If I leave, it won't be
because I don't love the company. I think an amazing tone has been
set here.''
</P>
<P>
   WB has advanced far faster than the other would-be fifth
network, UPN, which began at the same time. WB now has a core of
programs that are extremely popular with younger viewers,
especially teen-agers, including ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Buffy, The
Vampire Slayer'' and ``Seventh Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   WITH CELEBRITIES IN TOW, PUBLISHERS GO A-COURTING
</P>
<P>
   After months of fits and starts, the trade association for
publishers is ready to do for books what milk producers
accomplished with celebrity milk mustaches: make reading hip.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Association of American Publishers is announcing
a monthlong campaign in May to court a younger generation of
readers with a catchy slogan (``Get Caught Reading''), fashion
magazine advertisements and celebrity volunteers (Rosie O'Donnell
and Whoopi Goldberg) to promote reading and, most important, book
buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just been very impressed with how receptive everyone has
been to the idea,'' said Patricia Schroeder, the former Colorado
congresswoman and the association's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   There were many hurdles before the association reached this
point of showing off photos of Rosie O'Donnell musing over a copy
of ``The Bean Trees'' by Barbara Kingsolver. At one point the
association considered a campaign, but backed away from a price tag
estimated in the millions of dollars. This newest campaign, which
is being subsidized with volunteer labor and seed money of about
$60,000, also had to appeal to all publishers, who naturally would
like celebrities to pose holding copies of their newest titles.
</P>
<P>
   But on this detail, the association achieved unity by declaring
that celebrities would promote only older, backlist titles of their
choosing. The notion was that magazine publishers would be more
willing to devote free advertising space if the campaign dealt with
titles of the past, Ms. Schroeder said. The publishers also were
striving for a campaign that tries without eat-your-peas
preachiness to reach their target group of 18-to-34-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is really needed,'' said Robert Miller, the
publisher of Hyperion, who is on the campaign's steering committee.
``We are in danger of losing the younger generation and we need to
show them that books aren't just something like a flu shot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
