</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM FORUM CHANGES FOCUS OF FELLOWSHIPS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As fellowships go, the Freedom Forum's fellowships have a
Cadillac quality. Originally intended for writers working on books
or other in-depth projects about the press, they provide an office,
a half-time research assistant, a huge online data base of research
material, weekly seminars, and the close proximity of 9 or 10 other
fellows.
</P>
<P>
   It beats spending your time alone at home with writer's block,
even without the financial stipend that can reach $40,000 a
semester or $75,000 a year. Victor Navasky, the editorial director
of the magazine The Nation and a former fellow, said the
fellowships were ``the most valuable thing'' the Freedom Forum did.
</P>
<P>
   So when the foundation decided recently to disperse new fellows
around the country and preselect most of their research topics, the
news was greeted with dismay as it ricocheted around the book-party
circuit populated by former fellows like the authors Ken Auletta,
Sally Bedell Smith, Richard Reeves and Navasky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great program,'' said Auletta, who added, ``The
eminence of the big-shot names should not be allowed to obscure the
fact that a lot of junior and midlevel people came here and
produced a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Among projects that have attracted the past support of the
Freedom Forum have been: Auletta's book ``Three Blind Mice''; Ved
Mehta's book, ``Remembering Shawn's New Yorker''; Reeves' new book,
``What The People Know''; Lawrence K. Grossman's book ``The
Electronic Republic,'' and a study of Time Inc. founder Henry Luce
by the Columbia University history professor Alan Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   Writing will continue, but most of it will be on subjects of the
Freedom Forum's choosing, according to the forum's chief executive,
Charles Overby. Barring disapproval by the foundation's trustees,
the fellowships in their current form end this spring. Next year,
the $500,000 budget that underwrote the New York program will be
spread around four centers _ at the Newseum in Washington, at its
New York City counterpart, at Vanderbilt University in Nashville
and in the San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Future fellows will focus on projects that have ``the highest
interest to the Freedom Forum's operating programs,'' Overby said.
As a hypothetical example, he said, a new fellow might base a
long-term study on the front pages of newspapers around the
country, which are assembled at the Newseum every day.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   IN NEW AUDIENCE SURVEY, CBS GETS A BIT YOUNGER
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is about to stop calling CBS the network for old folks,
but in what seems to be that network's never-ending quest to get a
little younger, the current television season is providing at least
some baby steps in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, CBS' audience is getting younger. Or, perhaps more
accurately, it is getting a little less old.
</P>
<P>
   According to an annual median-age survey conducted by Steve
Sternberg, a senior partner of TN Media, a firm that advises
advertising clients on buying commercial time on television, the
median age for CBS' prime-time audience has dropped this season by
almost half a year. That is the good news because advertisers covet
a younger audience. The not-so-good news is that CBS still has the
oldest audience in television by almost a full decade.
</P>
<P>
   For the period from Sept. 21 through Nov. 22, the median age of
CBS viewers was 52.2 years, down from 52.6 for the corresponding
period last season. The next-oldest audience on television is
NBC's, with a median age of 42.7. But that is up 2.4 years from
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, every network but CBS saw the age of its viewers
increase this season. For WB, which has gained a reputation as the
network for teen-agers, this qualifies as good news because
advertisers pay more to reach young adults than teen-agers. The
median age for WB grew from 24.2 to 26.7. The biggest age jump was
at UPN. It is up to 36.7 this season, from 31.7.
</P>
<P>
   The modest drop in age is not exactly cause for celebration yet
at CBS. The network is still dominated by shows whose viewers are
mostly over 50, the least valuable to most advertisers. CBS had no
show with a median age younger than 47.8 years. That show, the
youngest show on CBS, was ``Nash Bridges'' starring Don Johnson. _
BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
