<P>
   DRIVE-THRU-BAN _ ATLANTA _ Drive through windows could become a
thing of Atlanta's past starting today when the Atlanta City
Council considers a controversial ordinance that would ban the
construction of new drive-through windows in the city. (Charles,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-REPORTS _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Grand Junction Police
Chief Gary Konzak raised some eyebrows when he said last week that
Grand Junction has one of the highest crime rates in the state.
Federal crime statistics prove him right. (Joyce, Daily Sentinel)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-H20-STOCK _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ The coming of the
new millennium has provoked a need to prepare for anything that
might come along, and many are taking that to heart by storing
water and buying water-purification kits. (Cleary, Daily Sentinel)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   STRIKES _ ATLANTA _ Despite a state law that demands mandatory
prison time for the type of crime probationer Timothy Carl Dawson
committed in 1995, a judge ordered probation. Dawson is now
suspected of killing five people _ four of them in hotel rooms. And
there are at least another 49 like him, probationers who would be
in jail but somehow have avoided the 10-year prison term demanded
by the Georgia Sentencing Reform Act, better known as the state's
``two-strikes-and-you're out'' law. ``I simply cannot understand
why any judge, who is sworn to uphold the law, won't follow it when
it's plainly written in black and white,'' said Gov. Zell Miller,
the architect of the law. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BASKET-HOLD-DEATH _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In light of a recent
death, mental health officials in Florida believe that unless
national standards for training and the use of physical restraint
are developed, more deaths of mentally ill patients will occur.
(Cooper, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TX-LAWMAKER-PENSION _ AUSTIN, Texas _ During his first eight
years in office, Texas paid state Rep. Charles Finnell $400 a month
to make laws. For the next 21 years, the state paid him a princely
$600 a month. Last month, Finnell's constituents fired him. Come
January, Texas will set him up with a retirement package worth
about $5,700 a month, or more than $68,500 a year. Life in the
below-minimum-wage Texas Legislature is not all that lucrative. But
ahhhh, the afterlife. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WEB-VIAGRA _ ORLANDO, Fla. _ Concerned about the danger of Web
sites that offer Viagra prescriptions without any face-to-face
doctor-patient contact, the state's Board of Medicine said that
doctors who prescribe the drug online could face criminal
prosecution or board discipline. (Mnookin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
