<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTICE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER ATTACK, JUDGES SEEK SUPPORT FOR THEIR INDEPENDENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Two Supreme Court Justices joined 120 other
judges, bar leaders, and legal scholars here this weekend to
consider ways to bolster public support for judicial independence
at a time when judges are coming under frequent attack for their
rulings, their budgets, and perhaps most fundamentally, their
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe in judicial independence, you believe in
freedom,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy told an American Bar
Association symposium. He added: ``The bar must support the
judiciary in its cause when it is under attack. Judges do not have
political clout. They need the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   This conference, co-sponsored by the University of Pennsylvania
School of Law, was the first of three the bar association will have
on the subject over the next five months. The ongoing project will
include a national survey of public attitudes toward the judicial
system, to establish a baseline to measure the impact of those
proposals that are put into effect as the result of the project.
</P>
<P>
   In launching the program here, Philip S. Anderson, a Little
Rock, Ark., lawyer who is the bar association's current president,
cast a wide net. Thirty state court chief justices attended or sent
other judges or representatives of their court systems.
</P>
<P>
   While not everyone at the invitation-only conference agreed on
the dimensions of the problem, there was rueful assent to the
observation of one of the keynote speakers, Professor Steven Lubet
of the Northwestern University School of Law, that ``everyone loves
the concept of an independent judiciary, but only about half of us
really like independent judges, especially when we disagree with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also widespread agreement with a definition offered by
Justice Adolpho A. Birch Jr., a member and former chief justice of
the Supreme Court of Tennessee. ``Judicial independence is the
judge's right to do the right thing or, believing it to be the
right thing, to do the wrong thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stars of the gathering were undoubtedly Kennedy and Justice
Stephen G. Breyer. Their decision to travel here, during a busy
period for the court, both underscored and validated the concerns
of the other judges, particularly those who ``are only an election
cycle, at most, away from unemployment,'' as Judge Wendell L.
Griffen of the Arkansas Court of Appeals described the
vulnerability felt by state judges who must face the voters either
for election or for retention in office.
</P>
<P>
   Most state judgeships are filled by election, and there was
considerable discussion about the threats to the image of an
independent judiciary posed by negative campaigns and by the
judicial candidates' need to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   One judge who described her own experience for the group was
Kate Ford Elliott of the Pennsylvania Superior Court, who lost a
race for the state supreme court last year after her opponent ran a
commercial in the last four days of the campaign accusing her of
having ``let criminals loose on technicalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Elliott remained on the Superior Court, an intermediate
appellate court. ``I don't decide Microsoft versus Netscape,'' she
said during a panel discussion of judicial elections. ``I decide
whether Joe Smith gets to have his child for the weekend'' and
similar cases ``very important for people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're allowed to do that because people trust us,'' she
continued, asking how a judge ``can you ever maintain that covenant
of trust'' after enduring a reputation-damaging political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Harold F. See of the Alabama Supreme Court held the
group spellbound with a videotape of the attack ads his opponent
ran against him in a 1996 race. Over the image of a skunk nosing
through the underbrush, the narration called See ``a slick Chicago
lawyer'' who never passed the Alabama bar exam. In fact, he had
taught for 20 years at the University of Alabama Law School and was
admitted to the Alabama bar without having to take the exam. He
spent $2.4 million and won the election.
</P>
<P>
   Because of such experiences, state judges rarely express much
sympathy for federal judges, protected as they are by life tenure.
Yet several of the scholars at the conference observed that life
tenure, a rare arrangement among the world's judicial systems, was
itself a source of political vulnerability for judges who are
easily portrayed as arrogant in their insularity and
unaccountability.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if there was one incident that galvanized the current
concern over judicial independence, it was the bipartisan attack,
early in the 1996 election year, on a federal district judge in New
York, Harold Baer Jr. In a decision questioning the credibility of
New York City police offices, Baer had ruled that the police lacked
an adequate basis to pull over and search a car in Washington
Heights and that the 80 pounds of cocaine and heroin they found
could not be used as evidence. After Republicans including Sen. Bob
Dole denounced Baer, a recent Clinton appointee, President
Clinton's spokesman suggested the President might seek the judge's
resignation. Within a few weeks, Baer reconsidered the case and
reversed his own ruling.
</P>
<P>
   That episode, as well as subsequent calls by several Republicans
in Congress for the impeachment of federal judges on the basis of
their rulings, led a number of groups, including the American
Judicature Society and the Century Foundation, formerly the
Twentieth Century Fund, to organize projects on judicial
independence. The Century Foundation's bipartisan group, Citizens
for Independent Courts, plans to issue a report in June on several
related issues, including how to define the line between legitimate
criticism and intimidation of judges.
</P>
<P>
   In brief remarks to the group here, Breyer stressed his view
that judicial independence exists not for the benefit of judges,
but of the people. He said that around the world, a realization was
growing ``that people's liberty and their prosperity depends in
part on their judicial institutions'' and that ``strong judicial
institutions depend on judicial independence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Judicial independence is in part a state of mind,'' he said,
`'a matter of expectation, habit and belief among not just judges,
lawyers, and legislators, but millions and millions of people.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, ``I don't think judges can help'' in their own
cause because judges' views are easily dismissed as ``institutional
self interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes up to others to do the explaining,'' he told the
bar leaders and law professors, adding: ``That's why you're here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
