<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE'S SHIFT ANGERS BACKERS 
WHAT GOES AROUND, ETC. 
ANOTHER DOLE FOR PRESIDENT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Nev., N.C., Kan.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since he said he might seek his party's nomination for
president in 2000, Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., has been angling hard
for the support of the religious right. Always solidly
conservative, he has become even more so in recent months,
repeatedly punching the buttons that most energize Christian
conservatives _ no more abortions, no more federal financing for
the arts, no more immorality in high office.
</P>
<P>
   The response from this powerful political group has been
encouraging, and the senator's friends say he is increasingly
inclined to jump into the 2000 contest.
</P>
<P>
   But a few days ago, Ashcroft suddenly made a major adjustment in
ideological course, one that turned heads and has left some members
of the religious right angry and others wondering just where the
senator stands on the causes dearest to them.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Detroit Economic Club _ all serious
presidential aspirants drop in on this powerhouse collection of
business captains _ he veered back to the political center, taking
a swipe at the religious right on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party, he warned, is fast approaching the point
where ``the things that are dividing us are defining us.'' Then he
added:
</P>
<P>
   ``We must never confuse politics and piety. For me, it is
against my religion to impose my religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, he talked only economics to the economics crowd. Not
once did he mention abortion, federal support for the arts or the
Clinton-Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   His omission drew quick reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the religious conservative who heads the Family
Research Council and who is also considering a run for the
Republican nomination, charged that Ashcroft was driving his own
divisive wedge into the party's ranks by ``ignoring the craving of
Republicans and conservatives for someone who will defend innocent
human life and the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Weyrich, an Ashcroft supporter who runs the Free Congress
Foundation, cautioned the senator to choose his words more
carefully in the future. ``You simply can't afford to have your
base in an uproar over speeches you give,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft aides insist that while the senator is in fact
beginning to change his political emphasis a bit, he has not
changed his core beliefs. They say that in the wake of the Nov. 3
Republican election debacle, he wants to focus less on emotional,
hot-button issues and more on the kinds of issues that proved to be
Republican winners that day, notably tax cuts, fiscal
responsibility and welfare and education reform.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to disappointed members of the religious right and to
many political pros, Ashcroft suddenly sounds like an echo of Gov.
George Bush of Texas. Bush has been talking a lot recently about
party unity and moderate, ``compassionate'' conservatism, and polls
indicate he leads the Republican presidential pack.
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, Betting on a Vote Recount
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1974, when he came within 624 votes of winning a seat in
the U.S. Senate, Harry Reid, a Nevada Democrat, demanded a recount.
It cut his margin of defeat to 611 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, Reid finally made it to the Senate and last
month he won re-election to a third term _ by a margin of just 401
of the 415,000 votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   What goes around often comes around for those who stay in
politics long enough. So now Reid finds himself facing a demand for
a recount by his Republican challenger, Rep. John Ensign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad political move,'' argues the senator, citing personal
experience and noting for extra measure that no Nevada election
result has ever been reversed by a recount.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't change the outcome,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ensign counters that since the initial ballot count had him
losing by just .09 percent of the vote, he would be ``letting a lot
of supporters down'' if he did not demand a second count. And he
has put his money where his mouth is, anteing up the $59,108 that
Nevada's secretary of state calculates a recount will cost.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a partial recount has already been conducted in a
Nevada county in which 6,000 paper ballots were improperly aligned
in voting machines. But that count cut Reid's lead by only 58
votes, to the 401 figure.
</P>
<P>
   If the full, statewide recount leaves him still a loser, Ensign
says he may appeal to the Senate for a review.
</P>
<P>
   Reid professes not to be worried. He points out that if there
were any serious doubt among his Senate colleagues about his margin
of victory, he would not have been elected last week to the
second-ranking Democratic job in the Senate, minority whip.
</P>
<P>
   A footnote:
</P>
<P>
   If Ensign does manage to get the results reversed, his $59,108
will be refunded.
</P>
<P>
   A Draft Campaign for Elizabeth Dole
</P>
<P>
   Earl Cox, the Republican organizer who once led an effort to
draft Colin Powell for a presidential run, is at it again.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by his failure to dragoon the popular retired Army
general into running, he now wants to draft another popular
Republican, Elizabeth Dole, president of the American Red Cross and
wife of Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, Cox set up a ``Draft Elizabeth Dole''
headquarters in an old railroad depot in Salisbury, N.C., Ms.
Dole's hometown, and next he plans to open a second office in
Kansas, her husband's home state. With the help of a former
Salisbury mayor, Margaret Kluttz, he is also sending out letters
that seek support for a draft from members of Congress and
Republican chairmen around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth Dole has an impeccable reputation for being a person
of high moral character,'' the letter states. ``Her government and
corporate experience have earned her a reputation for being a
strong and honest leader. Untainted by politics, Elizabeth Dole is
well qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, who has never run for elective office but has twice
been a presidential Cabinet officer and has often been mentioned as
a possible vice presidential choice as well as a presidential
choice, has offered multiple answers on whether she might run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to,'' she said flatly in one interview early
this year. But then, in a speech in September, she pulled back a
bit and said, ``I guess I've learned in this world never to say
never.'' Finally, in an interview last month with The Salisbury
Post _ at a time when some polls had her running second in a
theoretical race for the GOP nomination _ she said: ``I have
thought seriously about it, and I've learned never to say never and
then sort of leave it there.''
</P>
<P>
   So there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
