<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5475 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-06 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES TODAY HAVE BIG MONEY APPETITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``And I think we'll need some Rice,'' one of the shoppers
decides as the camera pans over to Jerry Rice, sitting inside the
meat counter at a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly you have seen the ad on television, pitching a video
service that promises to deliver all the pro football games one
person can digest on an autumn Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Rice _ San Francisco's superb wide receiver _ the
video ad features quarterbacks Brett Favre, John Elway and Troy
Aikman. They agreed not only to climb inside a meat counter and sit
there like butterflied legs of lamb, they also allowed themselves
to be hauled out of the supermarket in shopping carts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, these players are all superb talents. They have already
achieved status as multimillionaires. But for a few extra bucks
they willingly contribute to the meat-on-the-hoof stereotype of
professional football players.
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you how it was in my day.
</P>
<P>
   If Favre played for one of Vince Lombardi's Green Bay football
teams, he would learn upon reporting to the next practice session
that he had been traded to Albertson's for a case of pork and beans
and 30 pounds of ham hocks.
</P>
<P>
   Would boyhood heroes of an earlier era _ Joe DiMaggio, Ted
Williams, Bill Russell, Jim Brown, Dick Butkus or Y.A. Tittle _
have allowed themselves to be tossed around like a packing-plant
shipment of rump roasts, picnic hams and turkey hind quarters?
</P>
<P>
   They would not. For starters, Russell wouldn't fit inside a meat
case. They all had too much personal pride.
</P>
<P>
   Would Julius Erving or John Havlicek have signed on as pro
rasslers, like Karl Malone and Dennis Rodman did after the 1998 NBA
season?
</P>
<P>
   Would Lord Laurence Olivier accept the starring role in a remake
of ``Pee-wee's Big Adventure''? I think not.
</P>
<P>
   Shove a camera and a few bucks in front of today's pro athletes
and they'll not only ``say cheese'' they will recite 600 varieties
_ from Asiago to Zamorano _ while modeling tutus in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The problem seems to be that today's athletes are eating too
high on the hog and have appetites that cannot be appeased. In the
old days, athletes were happy just to come home to a hearty,
inexpensive dish like this one.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star Ziti
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dried marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean ground beef or ground turkey
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces ziti or penne pasta
</P>
<P>
   2 and one-half cups of your favorite spaghetti sauce
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups shredded mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Dump the ground beef or turkey into a mixing bowl and add the
garlic, onion, basil and marjoram. Moosh everything around with
your hands. (If you have just been petting some friendly dog, don't
feed this dish to your guests. Give it to the critter.)
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a skillet. Add the turkey mixture and
saute, busting it up with a wooden spoon as it browns. Stir in the
wine and vinegar and saute 3 minutes more. Dump in the spaghetti
sauce, salt, black pepper and red pepper flakes and slow cook
another 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile you should have been cooking the pasta tubes in
boiling, salted water.
</P>
<P>
   When the pasta is just done, drain and dump it into a casserole.
Add the turkey sauce and gloop everything around with that spoon.
Mix in the mozzarella, then sprinkle the top with Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Shove the casserole into a pre-heated, 400-degree oven until top
is beginning to brown, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves six, followed by a light, healthy dessert like this one.
</P>
<P>
   All-Conference Compote
</P>
<P>
   2 cups orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Minced zest from one lemon
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds assorted fresh fruit
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup orange-flavored liqueur
</P>
<P>
   Use whatever fruit is in season. Thanks to air-freight shipping,
something good is always in season. Last time we prepared this
dessert, we used bite-size pieces of fruit from one papaya, two
peeled peaches, 1 cup blueberries, 2 unpeeled apricots, one-half
pound pitted cherries and two-thirds pound of fresh strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except the strawberries, cover and
refrigerate. Just before serving, mix in the strawberries. Serves
eight wide receivers or four offensive linemen, with biscotti.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
