<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH07-COX     12-06 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judiciary allows more time to mold Clinton defense
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee granted the White
House more time to defend President Clinton Sunday, as it appeared
likely that the House would approve at least one article of
impeachment against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mooney, general counsel to Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde
(R-Ill.), informed White House lawyers that they would be granted
30 hours over the course of two days this week to mount a defense
against allegations that the president lied under oath, obstructed
justice and abused his presidential powers to conceal his affair
with former White House intern Monica Lewinksy.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's request for more time came after Clinton
vote-counters canvassed Republicans and found there appeared to be
enough votes in the House to approve one or more articles of
impeachment against the president. The implications of the request
were not lost on Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that your recent maneuvers may be little more
than an attempt to delay the committee and turn attention away from
the facts before it,'' wrote Mooney to White House Counsels Charles
Ruff and Gregory Craig.
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Sunday accepted Hyde's offer, but they're not
happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who want to pursue the derailment of the president have
not been deterred,'' said Clinton aide Jim Kennedy. ``There's a
chance they will succeed, but we hope to argue that impeachment of
the president is not in the best interest of the country. The
independent counsel spent four years and $40 million investigating
the president. The committee has spent four months doing the same.
Our request for a mere four days has now been cut in half.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Thanksgiving, the impeachment votes seemed to tilt in
favor of averting an impeachment trial by having Clinton face
censure and a fine. But that option seemed to fade after the
president's response to 81 questions posed by the Judiciary
Committee's Republican investigators. Even Democrats have called
Clinton's answers ``evasive'' and ``legalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His answers to the 81 questions were outrageous,'' said Rep.
Christopher Shays (R-Conn.), a member of the moderate group that
had supported censure over impeachment. ``I mean, he still doesn't
get it. He still doesn't tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome on impeachment now seems up for grabs, with both
sides tallying up different vote counts. This week's high stakes
vote in the Judiciary Committee has thrown Republicans such as
Majority Whip Tom Delay (R-Texas) into action. Delay has been
urging members to send the president and the public a message of
disapproval with their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they have been told that a vote for impeachment
is more of a symbolic move because the Senate will not remove the
president. But even that is not certain.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) said on NBC's ``Meet
the Press'' that he is now preparing for a Senate trial in light of
the likelihood that the House will vote for at least one article of
impeachment. Just last week, he told reporters that he had no plans
for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Senate will have a trial,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he doesn't want to strike a deal with Clinton to avert
the time-consuming trial, but will allow the constitutional process
to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of latitude here,'' he said. ``I think we
should do a trial if there are articles of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, known for his keen ability to predict vote outcomes, told
CNN on Sunday that he knows of only ``five or six'' Republicans who
will vote against an impeachment resolution in the full House later
this month. And he said those votes will be canceled out by five
Democrats who will vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, outraged that Clinton is not being given as much time
as he needs, say the Republicans are ``railroading the process'' by
making the rank-and-file members of the GOP believe that the
impeachment vote is just a statement of disapproval against the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``House Republicans are trying to convince themselves that this
is a routine procedural vote, nothing more than an ultimate rebuke
of the president, that the Senate will bail them out,'' said Jim
Jordan, press secretary to Judiciary Committee Democrats. ``Clearly
this is self-delusional. This is a vote of enormous ramifications
historically, constitutionally and politically. No one gets a free
pass on this vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde held a conference call with Republican members over the
weekend to discuss their options. In a statement, Hyde made it
clear that he intends to finish the panel's work by the end of next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Under the latest plan, the White House will be given from 9 a.m.
until midnight on Tuesday and Wednesday. The committee will hear
from Abbe Lowell, the chief Democratic counsel on Thursday morning
and from Republican Chief Investigative Counsel David Schippers in
the afternoon. Opening statements on articles of impeachment will
begin Thursday night and the debate will continue into Friday and
possibly the weekend. GOP leaders have set aside Dec. 16 and 17 for
votes on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   It would take 218 votes to send the trial to the 100-member
Senate, where a two-thirds majority would be required to remove
Clinton from office. In the current House, which expires next
month, there are 228 Republicans and 206 Democrats and one
independent, who tends to vote with the Democratic side. Three
Democrats have indicated they would support impeachment, which
means that the White House would need 14 Republicans to vote
against the measure in order to defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has asked the White House to turn over a witness list to
the committee by noon today.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aide Kennedy identified three witnesses the White House
would like to call: Bruce Ackerman, a constitutional scholar at
Yale University; Nicholas deB. Katzenbach, U.S. Attorney General
during the Johnson administration; and Sean Wilentz, a historian at
Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   And the White House is not the only one asking for more time to
deliberate the facts. California Democratic Rep. Zoe Lofgren said
she still wants more evidence from independent counsel Kenneth
Starr concerning Julie Hiat Steele. Steele has suggested to
investigators that Starr's office intimidated her by telling her
they would reveal that she improperly adopted a baby from Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has remained silent on the subject despite three letters
from Lofgren. And in an indication that Republicans aren't getting
much cooperation from Starr either, the committee approved a
subpoena last week requesting information about former Democratic
fund raiser John Huang. The committee wants Huang, who has already
been given partial immunity from Starr, to explain $550,000 Huang's
former employer gave to presidential friend Webster Hubbell after
he had left the No. 3 job at the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
