<HEADER>
A5577 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMES-SFCHRON-GAMES &LR;      12-06 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PC GAMES SCORING AS WORKPLACE TOOLS  &HT;     BY DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - GAMES   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer games are not just for teenage boys with baggy pants.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay truck drivers, New York bankers and oil refinery
workers are playing computer games _ as the latest form of
corporate in-house training.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the corporate games are even built on the same software
that powers popular computer games like Quake and Unreal _
high-speed action games that involve killing hideous aliens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people go home and turn on Nintendo 64 for fun, there must
be something compelling,'' said Pjotr van Schothorst, who develops
new ways of training employees at Royal Dutch Shell in Holland.
``We want to see: Can we tap into those concepts?''
</P>
<P>
   The company is working on game-like environments for a host of
purposes, including training workers who are headed for oil
platforms, or familiarizing employees with the complex underground
locales of oil reservoirs. Ultimately, Van Schothorst envisions
making the games available to the public as a recruitment tool _
``to show that working for an oil company can be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Shell has hired some of the same star gamemakers from the world
of PC action to make its in-house products. Noah Falstein of
Greenbrae, a former game producer from LucasArts Entertainment Co.,
traveled to Holland earlier this year and is working on prototypes
for Shell.
</P>
<P>
   Falstein once made games based on ``Star Wars'' and ``Indiana
Jones'' movies and has seen the game industry evolve into a
Hollywood business model, in which games cost so much to produce
that companies feel pressure to score a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   While the corporate work does not carry those burdens _ it
doesn't need to be a hit with anyone other than the client _ it
does present designers with other challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negative side,'' Falstein said, ``is that people within
the corporate chain have distinct ideas about what's necessary.
They might have a whole set of legal requirements that are
important but quite boring.''
</P>
<P>
   It's precisely the stultifying nature of much corporate learning
that has made using games so appealing.
</P>
<P>
   So much of what businesses force-feed their employees is boring
lectures, fat binders and PowerPoint presentations _ yet the
content often is critical information about how the company works,
what's expected in the employees' jobs, or what policies the
employees need to follow. Conversely, said Marc Prensky, a vice
president at Bankers Trust in New York and the founder of its
subsidiary Corporate Gameware, ``Games have an incredible amount of
engagement but no business content.''
</P>
<P>
   The first game Prensky made, before he arrived at Bankers Trust,
was &UR;  &LR; for airlines. He called it Where in the World Is Carmen
Sandiego's Luggage?
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's developed several games at Bankers Trust, both
for the company's internal use and to sell to other firms,
including CadLab and Reuters. In Straight Shooter, which could be
used in any type of organization, players comb the Earth looking
for potential clients. ``Along the way, you have to overcome
problems like monsters _ you shoot them with ideas from your cell
phone,'' Prensky said. ``The client tells you, `If you get this
question right, I'll be your client.'''
</P>
<P>
   With that game, any type of questions can be inserted, making it
a fun way to brief employees on ethics, sexual harassment policies,
or even product information. If employees get a low score, the
cartoon client tells them, ``Go back to b-school. Call me when
you're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   In another game, The Monkey Wrench Conspiracy, players are
intergalactic agents trying to save the universe _ by learning
tasks that relate to their company's business. ``There are puzzles
to solve and things to jump over and muck not to get caught in,''
Prensky said. ``We've taken the genre of the commercial game and
combined it with real deep business knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Prensky hopes his games help companies reach their newest
employees, members of the ``Nintendo generation.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where games like Quake and Unreal come in. While Id
Software, the Texas maker of Quake, lets people use its engine free
of charge, Epic Mindgames, the Canadian firm that makes the popular
alien-shooter game Unreal, licenses its software.
</P>
<P>
   One Canadian company used the Unreal engine to train employees
at an occupational health and safety company by ``creating a
building with a bunch of occupational health and safety hazards,''
said Mark Rein, vice president of Epic. ``We're very interested if
people want to use the engine to do these kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   For more-traditional workers who don't want an Unreal-style
twitch game, producers like Prensky build games in such a way that
players can opt for a more standard quiz format. After all, workers
who came of age before the computer game craze prefer their own
generation's games, such as Jeopardy and Wheel of Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Those games, with content tailored to individual companies'
needs, have proven to be popular with many companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the mandatory six-month training program that all Ford Motor
Co. sales and marketing workers take, ``at the end of each week, on
Friday afternoons, people were fading off on us,'' said Paul
Ventimiglia, developer of computer-based training at the Detroit
automaker. ``Now, we play Jeopardy every Friday. When they know the
game is coming up and there's a contest, they say, `We've got to
know this. Our team is at stake.' They pay attention to things more
and enjoy it more obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   To spice up a training CD-ROM for restaurant workers, 3DJoe, a
firm in San Francisco's Multimedia Gulch, created a
three-dimensional digital character, Buddy, with an absurdly huge
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to talk the language of your audience,'' said Hugo
Campos, art director at 3DJoe.
</P>
<P>
   In his work for San Francisco's Bechtel Corp., making CDs used
in bidding for expensive construction projects, Campos plays it
straight. The buttoned-down company doesn't want to let frivolity
slip into its presentations.
</P>
<P>
   But in the restaurant CD, Check Please, users can click on a
screen showing a kitchen or restaurant scene, and Buddy emerges to
explain that facet of the business _ how to sell extra desserts,
for instance, or how to pronounce different wines' names.
</P>
<P>
   The 3DJoe programmers also inserted a couple of ``Easter eggs,''
or hidden actions in which Buddy is found sloshed behind the bar or
yelling into a cell phone, griping to his agent, ``I can't work
with these people!''
</P>
<P>
   The Easter eggs became a selling point for the CD, Campos said.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations' interest in livening up their training has created
business opportunities for high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia of San Francisco takes products it originally made
for game and Web site design and sells them to large corporations
for in-house training.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, QVC and Frito-Lay are among the customers of Macromedia's
Learning Division. QVC trains tour guides of its West Chester,
Penn., headquarters, as well as the salespeople at various
facilities who take calls from television shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay trained more than 1,200 truckers about drug and
alcohol abuse by hiring BusinessWorks, a Texas firm, to create a
CD-ROM truck stop. At Rosie's Place, truckers can click on
``scrambled regs,'' or regulations, or ``sloppy joes,'' meaning
those messy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   An actress plays Rosie, a waitress who guides users through the
program. ``She's got this cute little accent and serves up this
good serving of information,'' said Bob Kaiser, president of
BusinessWorks.
</P>
<P>
   Truckers can stop in at training centers around the country to
take the training, even if they only want to spend a few minutes at
a time. ``They're getting used to the computer,'' said Larry
Merrifield, field fleet safety manager at Frito-Lay. ``They were
afraid of it at first, but they prefer it to us calling a meeting
on Saturday or Sunday, a four-hour session on drug and alcohol
training.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more cerebral computer games was SimCity, the game in
which players build simulated cities and then deal with taxes,
crime, floods and fire. The game, made by Maxis, a Walnut Creek
company that is now a division of Electronic Arts, had an early
corporate adopter in Chevron, which commissioned a game called
SimRefinery.
</P>
<P>
   Although that game never took off, the division of Maxis that
made corporate games developed into such a viable business that it
spun off as a separate company, Thinking Tools in Monterey.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking Tools now makes such products as TeleSim, a game that
simulates the telecommunications industry that's been used by at
least one Canadian phone company. &UR;  &LR; ``It puts you in the role of
decision-maker at a telephone company,'' said Thinking Tools
founder John Hiles.
</P>
<P>
   When the user makes a business move, the computer has a
competing telecom firm ``trying to eat your lunch and responding to
your moves,'' Hiles said.
</P>
<P>
   Hiles said he sees so many business people frittering away time
on airplanes playing solitaire on their laptops. ``They can be just
as glued to a simulation game,'' he said, ``and they'll be just as
excited because it will be relevant to them and their business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
