<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5582 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      12-06 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NEW ORLEANS _ The Cowboys moved the ball exactly zero yards to put
their first _ and only _ points on the board Sunday. It would prove
to be their most productive possession.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what Cowboys players would label the worst performance of
their careers, they allowed the New Orleans Saints to manhandle
them 22-3 at the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   With Arizona losing to the Giants later in the day, the Cowboys
(8-5) would have clinched the NFC East title had they won Sunday.
But while the defeat did nothing to set Dallas back in the
standings, it was a huge blow to some Pro Bowl egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want to put this out of your mind?'' receiver
Michael Irvin said. ``Why would you want to put it out of your
body? You've got to remember this feeling so you can say, `I'm not
going to let this happen again.' And that 24-hour rule (before you
forget this game and begin thinking about the next), I don't buy
into that, either.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Cowboys' offense managed 36 points in a Thanksgiving
Day loss to Minnesota, being kept of the end zone was unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we, 8-5? I guess the worst we can finish now is
8-8,'' Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith said. ``I've been here
nine years. I haven't seen anything like this before in my life.
What we've done in the past is history. What we are going to do in
the future remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith had reason to be frustrated: His 15 carries netted six
yards. Throw in Sherman Williams' two yards, and the Cowboys
totaled eight yards on the ground (on 18 carries), a franchise
standard for futility. The previous low was 20, against the Saints
in 1989 and the Giants in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``They caused a lot of confusion,'' said Smith, whose average of
0.4 yards per carry was a career worst. ``If ever there was a
complete shutdown, today was a complete shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a 16-for-32 passing performance by Troy Aikman, the
Cowboys managed 182 total yards, their worst output this season. It
was the first time this year their offense didn't score a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the best defensive game I've seen in a long time,''
said Saints coach Mike Ditka, who used continuous blitzing to
pressure the Cowboys' line. ``You've got to take me back to the
'50s or the '80s. This is the best I've seen. And you've got to
realize that offenses are much more sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was an indication of things to come, it came when
Smith was knocked back four yards to open the game. Aikman was then
chased into the end zone and made a desperate attempt to get rid of
the ball. He was called for intentional grounding, giving the
Saints a safety.
</P>
<P>
   And it only got worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the dog beat out of us,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
said. ``We've got a lot of work to do to get ourselves back to
where we think we've got a chance to compete in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had six first-half possessions. They moved the ball
25 yards on one, 33 on another. The other four covered minus-four,
minus-three, zero and minus-one yards. They had another drive of
minus-15 yards in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Cowboys finally managed to move from one end of the
field to the other on their final possession, it looked like a
comedy of errors. Thanks to Saints miscues that included penalties
for having 12 men on the field and pass interference, the Cowboys
got 10 shots at the end zone from inside the New Orleans 10. Aikman
threw six incomplete passes, Smith was hammered for a loss of three
yards on one carry, and the other attempts simply came up short.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you saw, we stunk out there today,'' Smith said. ``We
didn't do anything. We have nothing to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys actually held a brief 3-2 lead, but if there were
such a stat, the field goal would have gone down as unearned. Kevin
Mathis made one of the Cowboys' only big plays of the day,
intercepting a pass from Kerry Collins that was intended for Sean
Dawkins.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys got possession at the New Orleans 16, and Aikman
threw three straight incompletions. Richie Cunningham then booted a
33-yard field goal for Dallas' only points of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job of blitzing us, and we didn't make
adjustments fast enough,'' Gailey said. ``We thought we had it
worked out. We did not have it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense was expected to be Dallas' weaker side after a slew
of injuries to the secondary, but it actually looked like the
Cowboys' strength. It forced the Saints to turn the ball over on
downs on their first possession, then added the interception in the
first quarter. And Dallas twice held the Saints to long field goals
and once forced a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Saints' 328 total yards came on an 89-yard scoring
strike from Kerry Collins to Andre Hastings, who outraced Mathis to
the end zone late in the first half. Their only other touchdown
also came in the second quarter at the end of a seven-minute,
80-yard drive. Collins hit Aaron Craver with a four-yarder for the
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have got to be questions,'' Cowboys linebacker Randall
Godfrey said. ``Sometimes, you see Dallas as dominating. Sometimes,
this is the team. We show up like we're going to play. Then we show
up, and things like today happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
