<HEADLINE>
E-COMPARE'S GRAND PLAN _ FREE STOCK  &HT;     BY JON SWARTZ
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - NET FILES   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Nothing in life is free _ especially Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   So why is E-Compare Corp., an online shopping service, giving
away shares for free?
</P>
<P>
   The privately held Mountain View startup hopes that distributing
free shares will create a valuable Internet commodity: traffic on
its Web site. More eyeballs translate into sweeter advertising
deals and more revenue. ``We want to draw people into our service;
once we do, we're convinced they'll come back for more,'' said
President Steve Grand.
</P>
<P>
   E-Compare _ which provides price listings for books, and plans
to add CD titles next month _ is offering up to 10 shares of stock
for anyone who registers at  &LR; www.ecompare.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Grand, a 37-year-old high-tech consultant, said he plans to
eventually take the company public. Of E-Compare's 54 million
shares outstanding, the Web-surfing public will own 19 million and
the rest will remain with the company.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,300 people have scooped up shares since E-Compare began
advertising on its Web site last month, Grand said.
</P>
<P>
   Some might suggest that the offer sounds like a scene straight
out of the Mel Brooks comedy, ``The Producers,'' in which a
hard-luck Broadway producer and a meek accountant oversell stock in
a play they hope will flop, so they can pocket the money and run.
</P>
<P>
   But an SEC spokesman said last week that such bargains don't
violate securities laws ``as long as there is no compensation or
strings attached.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Compare is following in the footsteps of Travelzoo.com
( &LR; www.travelzoo.com) &LR; , a Bahamas budget travel company with 700,000
``owners'' _ each of whom picked up free shares by simply showing
up at the company's Web site. Travelzoo.com held its first company
meeting online last month to elect board members who will not be
paid but have voting authority.
</P>
<P>
   E-Compare's announcement ``validates what we are doing. There
was a lot of skepticism about us; it is good to see that others are
following,'' said Travelzoo.com CEO Ralph Bartel, 32, who lives in
Aalen, Germany. ``If 1998 was the year of paying lots of money for
Internet shares, maybe 1999 will be the year of getting free
Internet stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartel said his company will go public only when it is
consistently profitable. ``There is no concrete plan at this
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, E-Compare occupies the same office space in Mountain
View as Travelzoo.com. There is no affiliation between the
companies, according to Bartel and Grand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE WILD, WILD WEST &QL; 
My condolences to customers of Atbigger.net, the all-you-can-eat
Internet service provider that charged $60 for unlimited, lifetime
online access but petered out in October with money problems and
was bought by another financially challenged ISP, Brigadoon.com.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, flustered Atbigger.net customers have inundated my
voice- and e-mail with complaints about shoddy service from
Brigadoon.com _ if any service at all. ``The service seems to have
stopped altogether,'' said Harold Novikoff of Millbrae. Len Shaffer
of Emeryville hasn't had service since mid-November; he's
considering a switch to Pacific Bell Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's just the lastest in a string of travails for
Atbigger.net's beleaguered customers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a vow last month to post online information for
Atbigger.net's 40,000 stranded subscribers, Brigadoon.com has yet
to notify anyone via e-mail, its Web site, telephone or letters.
Most troubling, Brigadoon.com wasn't even answering its phones at
one point last week. ``It's been nothing but busy signals for
days,'' said Kate Adams of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But help may be on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Brigadoon.com CEO John Hansen said the Bellevue,
Wash., company was in the process of transferring Atbigger.net
customers to its national Internet service over the weekend. He
suggests that Atbigger.net members call (206) 652-9365, Ext. 0;
e-mail  &LR; wmparker &LR; brigadoon.com &LR;  or  &LR; admin &LR; brigadoon.com &LR; ; and check
out  &LR; www.brigadoon.com  &LR; for more information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend on honoring our commitment,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of Atbigger.net's customers felt that they got
their money's worth from the thrifty service, investors and
creditors aren't likely to see any of the money they sank into
Atbigger.net.
</P>
<P>
   But is this a surprise _ considering that a pair of former
Atbigger.net officials allegedly once rushed to a South Bay bar to
corner another executive to ``kick his ass''? (The ``targeted''
executive said an icy encounter did take place in a restaurant but
that there was no violence.) &UR;  &LR; Or that faulty equipment from a
prominent Bay Area networking company was at the root of
Atbigger.net's technical glitches? Or even that the company had not
filed federal income taxes in 1996 and 1997? (The IRS is scheduled
to meet with the company's co-founders later this week to hash out
$400,000 in back payments, sources said.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, former executives have engaged in finger pointing,
accusing one another of corporate bungling and malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
   All intriguing rumors, but of little solace to Atbigger.net
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
iCATCHING SALES: &QL; 
Apple Computer's stylish Internet box, the iMac, is the Energizer
Bunny of low-end computers. It keeps selling and selling and
selling ...
</P>
<P>
   For three-straight months, it has been the top-selling product
in computer superstores, according to ZD Market Intelligence in La
Jolla (San Diego County). In October, the iMac accounted for 4.7
percent of total PC shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the Apple faithful have never been able to buy a Mac
for less than $1,500 _ until now,'' said analyst Matt Sargent.
``This is a consumer product with staying power.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; And sales could pick up significantly if rumors of an iMac
price cut and introduction of a high-end model are correct.
</P>
<P>
   The scuttlebutt is that Apple will shave the $1,299
beach-ball-shaped computer's price to $999 early next year to
compete with sub-$1,000 PCs. What's more, a second iMac model _
with a faster processor and more disk space _ could debut in 1999
for $1,299, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   An Apple spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SITES OF THE WEEK &QL; 
Just 17 more shopping days until Christmas, and millions of
Americans already are surfing the Web instead of crawling the
malls.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are the usual online stops for tried-and-true
holiday gifts: Amazom.com ( &LR; www.amazon.com) &LR; , eToys
( &LR; www.etoys.com) &LR;  and 1-800-FLOWERS ( &LR; www.1800flowers.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   But to show you really care, why not exhibit some ingenuity and
explore some back roads on the information superhighway for your
gift list?
</P>
<P>
   Despair Inc., a Dallas distributor of self-deprecating posters,
postcards and calendars ( &LR; www.demotivators.com &LR; ), peddles products
that champion ``the often overlooked merits of `Mediocrity,'
`Procrastination' and even outright `Failure.''' The posters, such
as a skier taking a header over the headline ``Ineptitude'' are
dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   Try to find  &LR; that  &LR; at your nearest shopping mall or catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, for the Scrooge sect, there is
 &LR; members.aol.com/dasgozst2 &LR;   &LR; /fantasy.htm &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
