<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs picked for Peach Bowl, passed over by Outback
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's holiday plans went from the Outback to
the Bulldogs' own back yard on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the No. 19 Dogs were snubbed by Tampa's Outback
Bowl, which chose unranked Kentucky to play No. 20 Penn State on
New Year's Day. The Wildcats lost to Georgia 28-26 in Lexington on
Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, coming off a 21-19 loss to Georgia Tech in the
regular-season finale, settled for an invitation to the Chick-fil-A
Peach Bowl. The Dogs will face No. 12 Virginia in the Georgia Dome
on New Year's Eve in a game that will be nationally televised by
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first matchup of top-20 teams for the Peach Bowl,
which will have a payout of more than $1.5 million to each
participating school this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't have anything to say about anyone else's
selection,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ''Our loss to Georgia
Tech was really disappointing, but then again we had one of the
best records in the SEC. I'm very glad the Peach Bowl selected us.
It looks like they've got two better ranked teams than the
Outback.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing to the Yellow Jackets for the first time since
1990, Georgia officials still seemed relatively confident that the
Dogs would return to Tampa, where they blasted Wisconsin 33-6 in
last year's Outback Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   However, Outback officials instead chose the Wildcats, who
finished 7-4, including a 4-4 record in the SEC, which put them two
games behind Georgia in the Eastern Division.
</P>
<P>
   Outback Bowl Chairman Jim McVay said the bowl's selection
committee was attracted to Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch, a
Heisman Trophy finalist, who's expected to enter the NFL draft
after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the names that kept coming up on the SEC side as we
evaluated was Tim Couch,'' McVay said. ''We said, 'We better grab
this guy, bring him in, match him up against a real strong Penn
State team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The selection committe also was lobbied by Outback Steakhouse
co-founder Chris Sullivan, a University of Kentucky graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been a good alum and doing what you would expect him to
do,'' Outback Bowl spokesman Mike Schultze said earlier this week.
''He's lobbying for his team. At the same time, we have to be
objective and look at all the teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peach Bowl also looked at other teams, so it could have been
much worse for the Bulldogs. Peach Bowl Chairman Bob Coggin said
his committee also considered Alabama, which will play Virginia
Tech in Nashville's Music City Bowl. Throughout the week, some
Georgia officials feared the Bulldogs would fall as far as the
Independence, which chose Mississippi and Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel blessed and, frankly, amazed that a Georgia team at
8-3 was available,'' Peach Bowl president Gary Stoken said.
</P>
<P>
   Stoken said 61,000 tickets already have been sold for the game,
which is a rematch of the 1995 Peach Bowl, when the Cavaliers
stunned the Dogs 34-27 on Demetrius Allen's 83-yard kickoff return
for a touchdown with only 57 seconds remaining. That heart-breaker
was Ray Goff's final game as Georgia's coach.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia already has sold 18,000 tickets this year. Georgia sold
25,000 tickets to the game in 1995, and Bulldogs athletics director
Vince Dooley seemed confident that the school would match that this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel really confident that Georgia will sell this game out
for us,'' Stoken said. ''We think it's going to be a real tough
ticket in this city. We think we'll have a sellout in a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan said his team will begin light running today. Workouts
will begin on Wednesday, but the Bulldogs won't practice next week
during final exams. Full-contact practices will start on Dec. 20,
then the team will break for Christmas before meeting in Atlanta on
Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
