<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons play to control winning fate
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If it wasn't obvious before, it should be crystal
clear now that this is a very special season for the Atlanta
Falcons. If they can beat the Indianapolis Colts, while
sleep-walking no less, something special is going on.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta won 28-21 Sunday in the Georgia Dome behind quarterback
Chris Chandler, who passed for 297 yards, two touchdowns, and ran
for a score and Jamal Anderson, who rushed for a game-high 122
yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who have secured a playoff berth, maintained their
one-game lead over the San Francisco 49ers atop the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   All that might seem typical for a team that is 11-2, with more
victories than all but one of 32 previous Falcons teams.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday was not typical.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has never before beaten the Colts, who showed up Sunday
with a 10-0 record against the Falcons. So it looked like the old
ghost had risen from the grave again after Indianapolis took a 21-7
lead on Marshall Faulk's 3-yard touchdown run with 5:10 left in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, after the Falcons surrendered their first rushing
touchdown in 25 quarters, even-mannered strong safety William White
blew his stack on the sideline. If they were looking closely, many
of the 61,141 fans could see the veins bulging from his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Teammates) were telling me later I lost my religion. I just
wanted to let the guys understand that we're 10-2, not 2-10,''
White said. ``We're playing for something. We can get a (playoff)
bye; we can get homefield and everything if we just keep winning.
That's the way you've got to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I said everything right, no curse words. But my wife
(Nikol) was in the second row. She told me I have to pray extra and
ask for forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also relied on a little 1998 season history. It was
the third straight game the Falcons have trailed early in the game
against inferior opponents. Two weeks ago, the Bears led 13-3 in
the third quarter. Last week, the Rams were ahead 7-3 in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the comeback began earlier, with Atlanta scoring two
touchdowns in the final 1:21 of the first half to forge a 21-21
tie. The Falcons then scored early in the third quarter, after a
Ray Buchanan interception, to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The offense and defense both helped dig a hole for the Falcons
early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end O.J. Santiago fumbled on the third play of the game,
giving Indianapolis the ball on the Atlanta 26. Three plays later,
Faulk scored on an 11-yard pass from rookie quarterback Peyton
Manning (19-of-27, 159 yards, two touchdowns, two interceptions).
</P>
<P>
   The Colts drove 58 yards on five plays on the next possession
with Manning hitting wide receiver Torrance Small with a 30-yard
touchdown pass. With 5:36 left in the first quarter, Atlanta was
behind 14-0 and confused by the Colts' two- and three-tight end
sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared to death of Indianapolis . . . because they
really do have an explosive offensive team,'' Falcons coach Dan
Reeves said after his team won for the 17th time in 21 games.
``They do some things a lot different offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons pulled to within 14-7 a few minutes later on a
40-yard flea flicker pass from Chandler to wide receiver Tony
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until Faulk's short scoring run that the Falcons
defense had success by inserting a fourth linebacker, Craig Sauer,
when the Colts went with three tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis scored touchdowns on three of their first four
possessions, churning out 131 yards of offense. The Colts managed
just 113 yards after that.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson's 1-yard touchdown run cut the lead to 21-14, the
Falcons stopped the Colts on three plays. A 16-yard punt return by
Tim Dwight gave the Falcons the ball at their 34 with 35 seconds
left. Atlanta used two pass plays and a facemask penalty to drive
to the 3.
</P>
<P>
   After an incomplete pass, Reeves sent the field goal unit out
with five seconds left in the half. The crowd booed. And Reeves
decided to try one more play before kicking a field goal. When
Chandler could not find an open receiver, he ran for the score on
the final play of the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the last second, they jumped outside and doubled Tony,'' he
said. ``I looked (inside) for O.J., but I found a big hole and ran
in. Maybe we just haven't found a way to really get up for teams
like the Bears and the Colts. It must be something mental.''
</P>
<P>
   A mental mistake by Manning that opened the door for the
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the second half, he tried to force a ball
over the middle to Small, thinking free safety Eugene Robinson was
in single coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But cornerback Buchanan, a former Colts player, jumped in front
of both players to get his sixth interception of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton looks right at his receivers,'' Robinson said. ``When
he learns to look them off, he's going to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan returned it 18 yards to the Colts' 14. Three plays
later, Chandler rolled out to the right, and hit Mathis for a
4-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-21 lead held up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We control our own destiny,'' White said. ``We need to start
playing like we belong . . . no matter if it's the 49ers or the
Sisters of the Poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
