<HEADER>
A5591 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITALBAY-SFCHRON-DI     12-06 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITALBAY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRED'S COVER STORY ON MICROSOFT AN UNINTENTIONAL PR BONANZA  &HT;     BY TOM ABATE
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - DIGITAL BAY   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The cover story in December's Wired magazine really pushed my
antitrust button.
</P>
<P>
   Overlaid on a larger-than-life photo of Bill Gates was the
headline: 83 reasons why his reign over the computer industry is
over. What a revelation! The last thing I'd heard was Microsoft
snickering as Netscape sought asylum with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, I had to read on.
</P>
<P>
   Inside was a succession of bullet points explaining why
Microsoft is losing its stranglehold on computing.
</P>
<P>
   Reason No.1 set the tone for the blithe utterances that
followed. ``Funky Karma'' would come back to haunt Microsoft.
Reason No.7: its ``Divorce'` with Intel would leave Redmond in a
lurch.
</P>
<P>
   And so they went, a stream of two- or three-sentence sound
bites &UR; .  &LR; No.33 nearly sent me over the edge of the BART platform
where I stood reading. Microsoft's earnings, which have risen an
average of 43 percent a year since 1993, could slow to a 23 percent
per annum rise going forward. A mere 23 percent earnings growth
hardly made life seem worth living!
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Even Wired called its article ``a supreme act of
imagination.'' Now I have nothing against good fiction, but I am
lathered over the lousy timing of this suggestion that we trust the
invisible hand of laissez-faire capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In every industry, on every continent, mergers ars busting
records. Oil companies, car companies, phone companies, drug
companies, everywhere _ the huge are getting huger.
</P>
<P>
   And in the midst of this orgy of corporate copulation, our
antitrust regulators finally have got their feeble statutes around
the wrists of one titan and hauled its videotaped essence into
court to answer charges of unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way to overstate the historic significance of the
Microsoft antitrust case. At a time when corporations are
redefining competition as a series of global Sumo matches, the
federal government is trying to impose a few simple rules, like no
grabbing below the belt.
</P>
<P>
   And brash, bad Microsoft is so worried _ you can practically see
the sweat beading up on the mighty brow of Redmond _ that it's
touting any sign of competition as reason for the trust-busters to
back off.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this lands Wired's 83 reasons, which read like
the thoughts of Chairman Mao meets Fortune magazine. The result is
an unintentional PR bonanza for Microsoft, which is frantically
trying to conjure up the impression that it's not such a juggernaut
after all.
</P>
<P>
   I ran these ruminations past Wired Editor in Chief Katrina Heron
who said I, like most of the media, have fixed on the antitrust
trial as if it were a stake poised above Microsoft's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying something seismic is going on. It's a sea change;
the trial is just a part of it. Add up all the reasons we give and
look at &QL; 
the big picture,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She did settle one mystery. Why 83 reasons and not 50 or 100?
``We felt Microsoft was such a big company, it deserved a prime
number,'' she said. Personally, I would've settled for three good
reasons _ if Wired had articulated them.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I'm sure there are people who believe that new market
forces, notably the Internet, are changing the business climate in
which Microsoft rose to hegemony. And like the comet that once
humbled the dinosaurs, these market forces could lay the groundwork
for Gates' fall.
</P>
<P>
   I just don't happen to hold the opinion that we should quit
worrying while everything irons itself out. Sure, the Internet is
reshaping the computer landscape, And though it lacks the sudden &LR; 
impact of a comet, it is  &LR; creating new pathways of commerce,
information and power.
</P>
<P>
   But the Net hasn't changed human nature or the temptation to be
a market bully _ or the need to arm commercial cops with more
firepower than ``funky karma.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
