r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUOKKA-SFCHRON-QUOKKA     12-06 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUOKKA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBER SPORTS COVERAGE PUTS FANS IN THE THICK OF IT  &HT;     BY JON SWARTZ
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - QUOKKA   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's the final leg of the women's marathon race at the 2000
Olympics, and a handful of runners strain toward the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   A cybersurfer clicks on the visage of the Italian athlete to
monitor her heartbeat, then the image of an Ethiopian competitor
for the status of an ailing knee. The surfer checks a splashy
infographic on the bottom of his computer screen for track
conditions and that stiff northernly breeze blowing into the faces
of the runners.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, live video images of the race's conclusion
flicker across a large monitor or Internet-based television screen.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't your father's television coverage of the Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
   This is the future of international sports coverage, according
to Quokka Sports Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco startup wants to give sports viewing a
decidedly 21st century look, and industry insiders think it will.
Many are calling Quokka the next Big Thing on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old company's coverage this year of two
around-the-world sailing competitions has drawn rave reviews, large
online audiences and even generated a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Quokka has developed sophisticated technology that delivers
cereal spoon-dropping visual content over high-speed Internet
connections to consumers. Some even are calling it ``The Wide World
of Sports'' of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   If Quokka makes good on its grandiose plan, anyone with a
personal computer, set-top TV device, pager or Internet appliance
will soon be able to view through Quokka's Web sites a panorama of
camera angles, sounds, splashy graphics and statistics of
international sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   And Quokka wants to take the concept even further: It plans to
post the vital signs _ possibly in real time _ of participating
athletes, right down to heart rates and blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the opportunity to be a giant in digital sports
entertainment,'' said Barry Weinman, a Quokka board member and
partner at Media Technology Ventures in Los Altos. ``Sports viewing
will be more than sitting on a couch and cracking open a
six-pack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They could change the way we look at sports,'' said Ann
Kirschner, vice president of NFL Interactive in New York. ``I'd
love to see an Internet-age Olympics, where I get a personalized
view of all the Olympics events. That's a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Heady stuff for a company whose headquarters _ a microchip's
throw from Multimedia Gulch _ is bursting at the seams with 120
employees. Quokka CEO Alan Ramadan says Quokka plans a move into a
larger facility next year, where it hopes to create the first
digital media studio in the city. There, satellite transmitters and
networking links will send and receive sports reports globally.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan grasped the possibilities of ``digital sports
entertainment'' while chief technology officer on oneAustralia in
the America's Cup sailing race in 1995. Trailing the sailing vessel
in another boat, he was fixated as the event unfolded on a computer
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was far superior to TV coverage,'' Ramadan said. ``With
computerized data, we were able to trace the slightest wind changes
and determine the leader of a race to the second. I thought, `Why
not make this available to everyone?'''
</P>
<P>
   He co-founded Quokka in 1996 with John Bertrand _ a national
sports hero in Australia for wresting America's Cup from the United
States as captain of Australia II in 1983 _ and IBM veteran Dick
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The company's big splash, so to speak, was its coverage of the
1997-98 Whitbread Round the World Race. Its coverage blanketed the
nine-month boat race with video feeds and still photos, e-mail
reports from the crews involved and reports from journalists at
each port. The site generated $7 million in revenue and drew kudos
from the sports press. An estimated 1.8 million people viewed the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Quokka has developed a Web site for the
International Olympic Committee ( &LR; www.olympic.com &LR; ), is producing
the online coverage of a solo around-the-world sailing race
( &LR; www.aroundalone.com &LR; ), and is in the process of creating pages
for an expedition in China.
</P>
<P>
   During the dangerous Around Alone race last month, Quokka made
headlines for telling the harrowing story of Russian sailor Viktor
Yazykov, who performed surgery on his badly infected elbow in the
middle of a South Atlantic storm. Yazykov received e-mail
instructions on his laptop computer from Dr. Daniel Carlin in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to tell the story from the inside out. We want
consumers to view events through the eyes, hearts and minds of
athletes,'' Ramadan said. ``It's like reading a novel instead of a
summary.''
</P>
<P>
   The new media company so far has the attention of traditional
broadcasters and established sports leagues. NBC and the NFL are
among the organizations that are discussing possible partnerships
with Quokka.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Time Digital recently named Ramadan one of its
50 most influential people, and the upstart has raised more than
$15 million in funding from Intel Corp., Stanford University, Accel
Partners, Trinity Ventures and others.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, a lineup of high-tech heavyweights _ led by
Intel, Compaq Computer and Eastman Kodak _ are working with Quokka
to develop this hybrid of digital sports entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It can be one of the defining companies in establishing a
new model for digital media, and in establishing a combination of
new revenue streams,'' said Bruce Golden, of Accel Partners in Palo
Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers expect Quokka to reap revenues from banner
ads, sponsorships, product placements, e-commerce transactions,
pay-per-view events and digital rights. It isn't farfetched to
envision Quokka teaming up with NBC Sports to provide wall-to-wall
coverage of the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while NBC could broadcast women's gymnastics and
cable network MSNBC handle a men's basketball game between Croatia
and Germany, Quokka could offer in-depth coverage of the men's
marathon and several other events _ all at the same time. In
essence, there is no limit to the number of ``channels'' that
Quokka can create on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``There is so much to cover at an Olympics; that's our big
programming challenge,'' said Bob Meyers, senior vice president of
NBC Interactive in New York. ``But the Net is a game changer: It
lets you watch whatever you want, when you want it. Television is
stricter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quokka won't replace or erode broadcast TV; rather, it will
enhance and supplement coverage,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Quokka's goal is hardly a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Its success is partially contingent on widespread use of digital
television and advancements in video-streaming technology, both of
which could be a few years away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get a couple of lucky breaks and these technologies
improve, they could do incredible things,'' the NFL's Kirschner
said. ``But not everything is under their control.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential technological pitfalls hardly dissuade Ramadan and
crew, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be comfortable without a safety net because the
industry changes so fast,'' Ramadan said. ``Our company sheds its
skin every six months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 2044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
