<HEADLINE>
BALF HITS THE WEB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's called balf _ a combination of the words
baseball and golf.
</P>
<P>
   It's played with a clat _ a combination of the words club and
bat.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``The sport of the third millennium'' by its
founder, Mark Schuster of Crafton, Pa. That's a combination of hope
and hype.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds too much like another twisted plot line for the
next movie from the ``South Park'' guys, check out the game's
official Web site ( http://balf.com ) for further clarification.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's been around officially since 1994, balf
tournaments seem to be (sort of) the rage in the Eastern part of
the country. Especially, for some reason, in North Mankato, Minn.
On Schuster's original site (
http:/members.aol.com/clatmaster/balf.htm ), still floating around
on the Web, there are names and numbers of those who were (and
could still be) interested in starting a league or tournament in
Valencia, Santa Barbara and Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   The balf site seems to also be the easiest place to buy the
tools of the trade _ a BalfClat driver (a fiberglass-covered 34
inch, 19 ounce stick) and a BalfClat putter (basically, a driver
with a putter head attached at the end of the barrel), used to hit
a regular old golf ball. At $89.98 a set, the clubs are a
registered trademark of Hillerich &AMP; Bradsby, the guys who make
Louisville Sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the official sport paraphernalia, such as balf
bags, sweat shirts and leather jackets (that are a bit pricey). So
someone must be serious about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Just one note of caution: Balf is not affiliated with the Boston
Adult Literacy Fund, which can be accessed
(http://www.tiac.net/users/balf/) by accident if one isn't careful
with the Yahoo search. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
