<HEADLINE>
ADS TAILORED TO WEB USERS 
ALARMING ORNAMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Imagine that, as you drive down the road, each billboard you
pass instantly changes to advertise a product tailored to your
specific tastes and needs.
 &HT;    That might be impossible to do on a highway. But some companies
are striving to do the equivalent on the Internet. Vignette and
Broadvision, for example, are two companies that draw on a computer
user's browsing and buying history to customize online shopping.
 &HT;    Be Free Inc., a small start-up in Marlborough, Mass., that
recently received a $17.6 million infusion of venture capital, says
it expects to be awarded a patent Tuesday for a method of passively
collecting behavioral profiles and psychographic data (information
about attitudes and lifestyles) for individual computer users,
storing this information in a huge database and then using it to
decide what consumers should see which advertisements.
 &HT;    Many Web surfers already experience tailored advertising. If you
buy John Grisham's latest from Amazon.com, for example, the next
time you visit the site you are likely to find several other legal
thrillers on a recommended book list.
 &HT;    But that targeting takes place within a specific web site. Be
Free says its patented system can acquire this information from
thousands of Web sites and then correlate it to develop
well-rounded profiles of consumers.
 &HT;    Tom Gerace, 27, started the company three years ago with his
brother Sam Gerace, 35. Be Free does not yet provide its proposed
service but plans to do so by late summer or early fall of next
year. ``We've got to have relatively large data collection,'' Tom
Gerace said. ``We've been collecting data for 13 months now, and we
have 20 million unique user profiles.''
 &HT;    The company currently specializes in what is known as affiliate
marketing, putting in place technology that enables online
companies to pay commissions to content providers who send paying
customers their way. Among its clients, Be Free says, are
Barnesandnoble.com., owned by Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc.; Reel.com, owned
by Hollywood Entertainment Corp., and Travelocity, owned by
Microsoft Corp.
 &HT;    ``We have watched an anonymous consumer view the weather in
North Carolina every two weeks, buy golf books and then buy golf
clubs,'' said Tom Gerace, executive vice president of business
development at Be Free. ``When they see a promotion on Travelocity,
they should see a promotion for golf vacations. But today they're
as likely to see an ad for steaks or for stock quotes.''
 &HT;    Be Free contends that its technology _ which makes use of such
electronic trail markers as ``cookies'' and digital certificates _
does not threaten consumer privacy.
 &HT;    ``We don't collect data that can be used in any way to match
this profile with a real-world person,'' Tom Gerace said. ``We
create a firewall between this rich behavioral information and the
living, breathing human being behind it.''
 &HT;    Will the patent raise eyebrows in the marketplace, as several
involving electronic commerce already have? Engage Technologies,
for example, drew attention when it announced in August that it had
compiled a database of 30 million digital dossiers very similar to
the type Be Free says it has patented.
 &HT;    ``There will be a number of people who will be concerned about
the patent and whether they violate it,'' Tom Gerace said.
``Obviously, we can leverage the patent in a number of different
ways to strike partnerships. But it's not our goal to be
litigious.''
 &HT;    Ken Cassar, an analyst at Jupiter Communications, a new-media
research firm, has not read the patent, which Be Free applied for
in 1995. But based on Be Free's description, he said, it may well
turn out to be a headache for competitors.
 &HT;    ``Patents can really shake a market up and put the squeeze on
companies that have been doing something for a while but didn't
apply for a patent,'' he said.
 &HT;    ``The Patent Office has got to be realizing that they need to
streamline the process,'' he added. ``The marketplace is moving so
fast. A three-year delay is decades on the Internet.''
 &HT;    Be Free Inc. expects to receive patent 5,848,396 on Tuesday.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Ornament Signals, Go Check the Tree
</P>
<P>
   After watching a newscast about a house that burned down when a
Christmas tree caught fire, David Solak was inspired to invent a
smoke alarm disguised as a tree ornament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't just make a noise on the Christmas tree,'' Solak
said. ``It has a transmitter that sends a signal to a receiver,
which you can keep by your bedside or somewhere else in the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Solak, an engineer who lives in Seven Hills, Ohio, has licensed
patent 5,821,865 to Trinity International, based in Columbus, Ind.,
and plans to begin selling the device next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Intellectual Property Owners, a trade association, is
accepting applications until Dec. 18 from inventors who would like
to exhibit at the 1999 National Inventors Expo and Conference,
which will be held in March at Epcot Center in Orlando, Fla. More
information can be found on the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office's
Web site, at www.uspto.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
