<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD-LEWIS: THE TIME HAS COME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Evander Holyfield, as cocky as you'll ever see
him, was referring to Lennox Lewis' prolonged efforts to reach a
deal on their March 13 fight when he said: ``You better be careful
what you wish for, you might get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Lewis has known all along that Holyfield is no Oliver
McCall, no Henry Akinwande, no Andrew Golota _ opponents who broke
down one way or another against Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, in spite of the big words spoken at a news conference
last week at the Olympic Auditorium to promote the fight, knows
that Lewis could pose the biggest challenge of his career.
</P>
<P>
   And, most significant to the rest of us, we know it too.
</P>
<P>
   It all makes for one of the most compelling heavyweight matchups
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The fight will unify the titles for the first time since Riddick
Bowe tossed the WBC belt into a trash can after he took the three
major championships from Holyfield in 1992. Holyfield now owns the
WBA and IBF versions of the title, Lewis the WBC.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, ungodly sums of money will be reaped by both fighters;
Holyfield $20 million-plus, Lewis $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, this is about more than money and titles _ particularly
in an era when titles have lost their meaning.
</P>
<P>
   In one of its rare triumphs, boxing got it right: This is about
the best against the best, a fight between the two premier
heavyweights on the planet to determine the true king of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win? It's a tossup, which makes the event all the more
tantalizing. A typical discussion about the fight raises more
questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   At 36, how much more fight does Holyfield have in him?
</P>
<P>
   And many bring up Bowe and ask: Will Holyfield struggle again
against a much taller fighter? Holyfield is 6-foot-2, Lewis 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who won, lost and won in three fights against Bowe,
scoffed at the latter notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had problems in the first (Bowe) fight because I fought his
fight. I exchanged (punches) inside,'' Holyfield said. ``I did
better the second fight because I fought my fight. I boxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight will be no problem if I fight my fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions also surround Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, he has never been in the ring with a warrior
like Holyfield. In fact, he hasn't fought any of the top
heavyweights of the past decade: Holyfield, Bowe, Tyson or Michael
Moorer, all of whom he says have avoided him.
</P>
<P>
   Does Lewis have the stomach for such a challenge?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, no heavyweight has the big-fight experience of
Holyfield. How will this disparity play out?
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Lewis is confident but sensible. He seems to have
a keen sense of his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he's not like those other guys,'' said Lewis,
referring to Akinwande, Golota and McCall, the last of whom broke
down in tears during their fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to think that we'd go into the ring and all of a
sudden Evander Holyfield starts crying, or starts holding me. It
would be a shock to me. I know he's going to show true grit. That's
him.''
</P>
<P>
   For Holyfield, this fight could be another significant triumph
in a remarkable career _ or the end. For Lewis, it could be his
long-awaited rise to the top of the sport _ or proof he was never
the fighter he claimed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis can't wait to find out what the answers are.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said be careful what you wish for, but I've been wishing
for this for seven years,'' he said. ``I couldn't be happier my
wish came true.''
</P>
<P>
   We all feel that way.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson watch: Greg Garrison, the man who prosecuted Tyson during
his trail for rape, doesn't believe the fighter's no contest plea
to misdemeanor assault charges in Maryland will send him back to
jail for violation of his parole.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Patricia Gifford, who presided over Tyson's rape trial in
Indianapolis, will determine the fighter's fate after Tyson is
sentenced early next year on the assault charges. He is accused of
kicking and punching two motorists after a traffic accident in
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most NFL players do more than that before lunchtime,''
Garrison told the New York Daily News. ``I'm no fan of his, but I
don't see this being too important at all. (Gifford) sees so many
things worse than this, I can't imagine she would care too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson also could face a jail term based on the incident alone.
</P>
<P>
   Bad move: Oscar De La Hoya should remove those responsible for
removing a KCAL reporter and cameraman at an event to honor the
fighter for asking a question about rape allegations.
</P>
<P>
   You don't tell a reporter not to do his or her job. De La Hoya
should simply have said: ``I'm sorry. My attorneys have advised me
not to comment on this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who said in response to the question that he's had a
difficult time the past few weeks, is accused of raping a girl 2{
years ago in Cabo San Lucas, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: A wonderful card is set for Saturday on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Gatti faces Ivan Robinson in a rematch of their war and
Yory Boy Campas defends his IBF junior middleweight title against
Fernando Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   It's unusual to have one such compelling matchup on a card, let
alone two. . . .
</P>
<P>
   If Vargas takes away Campas' title, his promoter, Dino Duva,
wants to schedule his first defense in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Auditorium is the leading contender in a search for
a site. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Duva and Don King are negotiating a fight between IBF
welterweight champ Felix Trinidad and former champion Pernell
Whitaker, although talks are in the early stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's 50-50 right now that it will happen,'' Duva said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, who has struggled with substance abuse, has been
licensed to fight again and is working out. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Italian judge Franco Priami, who scored Saturday's Johnny
Tapia-Nana Konadu fight even, should have his license revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia pitched a near shutout to win the title. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight contender Ed Mahone faces Booker Word in a 10-round
bout tonight at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   In his last bout, Mahone drew with Al Williams when Williams
claimed he couldn't continue because of an accidental head butt in
the sixth round. The draw ended Mahone's knockout streak at 18. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
