<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5624 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     12-06 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS _ This is how it began: Emmitt Smith took a handoff on
the first play from scrimmage and was nailed by Mark Fields for a
four-yard loss. On the second play, Troy Aikman was called for
intentional grounding out of his end zone, resulting in a safety.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it ended: With Smith getting stopped by Wayne Martin
one yard short of the end zone, finishing a series of eight
straight plays from the eight-yard line and in on which Dallas
couldn't punch the ball across the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the Cowboys were worse.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't merely the notion that the Saints could put an ugly
22-3 tattoo on his team that bothered Chan Gailey. It was the way
they did it that had the first-year head coach seething with anger.
</P>
<P>
   His voice wasn't raised, but his blood pressure certainly was.
He wasn't outwardly hot, just inwardly boiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sorry display of offense we had out there today,'' he
said. ``We got the dog beat out of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of work to do to get to where we think we'll
have a chance to compete in the playoffs. It's not a lot of fun in
our locker room right now, and it won't be until we get this thing
straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Which might not be so easy. Against a New Orleans defense that
is by no means considered awesome, the Cowboys' offense was more
twisted and bent than Quasimodo trying to do a backflip.
</P>
<P>
   But the Saints thoroughly overpowered the Cowboys' offensive
line, stuffed Smith like a Christmas turkey and kept pressure on
Aikman all day long.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly details said Smith carried the ball 15 times and
gained a total of six yards. On a half-dozen occasions, Smith's
efforts resulted in negative yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worst day ever,'' he said. ``Had to be. What could have been
worse?''
</P>
<P>
   How about an entire Cowboys running game that ground out a total
of eight yards? That makes for the single worst rushing day in the
long history of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't take numbers or historical rankings to tell the
story. It only required a glimpse or two or three at the times that
Saints defenders penetrated Dallas' offensive line and delivered
assorted hits that could be felt from the upper decks of the
Superdome all the way to Bourbon Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints came at the offensive line, which used to be the
strength of the Cowboys, with a steady diet of an unexpected run
blitz, and the Cowboys reacted as if they had just been handed a
copy of the Dead Sea Scrolls and asked to translate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make the proper adjustments,'' said Gailey. ``We
didn't do any of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the possibility is that the Cowboys had been checking
out those standings in the NFC Least and, at 8-4 entering the game,
somehow got their inflated record confused with the formerly
dominant Dallas teams of the Super Bowl era.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, they are still an unproven bunch. While capable of
piling up large offensive numbers as they did in the shootout loss
to Minnesota on Thanksgiving, the Cowboys are not that far removed
from the mediocrity that inhabits much of the NFL. Which means that
in order to succeed and win games, they can't afford to come out
with anything less than an all-out effort, no matter whom they are
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be unhappy to hear that anybody on our team took the
Saints lightly,'' said Aikman. ``Maybe it could have happened. I
just know that I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   With Deion Sanders still hobbled, with Kevin Smith emotionally
crippled, with Kevin Mathis trying to play cornerback with a cast
on his right arm, it was expected that the defense would have its
problems. Which it did. The Saints ground out a pair of 12-play
drives covering 80 and 45 yards and also scored on an 89-yard
touchdown pass from Kerry Collins to Andre Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the offensive breakdown that was much more alarming
as Dallas could never get going or score a touchdown. Even just for
pride in the dying minutes of the game. Even when a
pass-interference call in the end zone gave the Cowboys
first-and-goal at the one.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL used the BCS computer to make postseason matchups
like the colleges, just figure the Cowboys would be lucky to make
the Independence Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   They were coming off their annual 10-day break following the
Thanksgiving game and figured to be fresh. They could have won and
officially wrapped up the division title. They could have told
themselves they would be a real factor in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, we went and got embarrassed,'' said left guard Nate
Newton. ``Now, it's a rat race.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes it's hard to tell the vermin apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
