<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BLUE, HEAD FOR SIESTA BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Are you ready for the Doze Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Bowl Championship Series announced Sunday that
deflated UCLA will meet Wisconsin _ the third-best team in the Big
Ten _ in the Rose Bowl on Jan. 1. The Bruins were ranked fifth in
the final BCS poll.
</P>
<P>
   Because no current players have experienced a Rose Bowl, the
Bruins probably will get excited for the game as the New Year
approaches and the sting of Saturday's defeat abates.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, they are disappointed, angry and embarrassed
about their 49-45 loss to Miami in the Orange Bowl _ a loss that
cost them the Fiesta Bowl and cost the Pac-10 $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA locker room was not a pleasant place Saturday
afternoon. The offense blamed the defense, which yielded a
school-record 689 yards. Several players questioned the severity of
linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo's knee injury. (It's a ligament
sprain and he's expected back for the Rose Bowl.) Other players
questioned the attitude and preparation tactics of the young
defensive backs, whose tackling wasn't fit for Pop Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make the tackles we're supposed to, it would have been
different,'' said safety Larry Atkins, one of the few defenders who
played tough and hard. ``We'll use this as something to motivate us
for the Rose Bowl. (Miami) drove up and down the field on us. We
can't let that happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Rifts between offense and defense can destroy a team; just ask
Buddy Ryan. Are the Bruins heading that way? Yes, there was tension
in the locker room, but it appears temporal, and it's up to the
captains and coach Bob Toledo to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the Bruins have been tempting the football fates all
season. You don't win national titles with a defense ranked 91st in
the nation. Deep down, Toledo knows it. But he also knows Cade
McNown is a once-in-a-decade quarterback, and he didn't want to
waste the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The defense should be solid next season. All the offensive skill
players will be back, including Freddie Mitchell. But a new
quarterback (presumably Drew Bennett) makes the equation tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Talent alone doesn't win championships; complementary talent
does. There has to be balance, but UCLA's scale tipped severely to
offense. Not only did the Bruins have two senior starters on
defense, they had two junior starters, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a stat that the worst defense a national-championship
team had was about 40th,'' guard Andy Meyers said. ``We beat that
by 50. You guys (the media) were right. Obviously, we were holding
onto something we couldn't obtain.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said a slew of players _ freshman safety Jason Stephens,
sophomore cornerback Marques Anderson and junior cornerback Ryan
Roques in particular _ took a nonchalant attitude after watching
Syracuse defeat Miami 66-13 last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And privately, several Bruins are wondering if Toledo will fire
first-year defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti. Toledo himself
sparked the speculation when he ripped Aliotti at a press
conference last month, and his ire was obvious Saturday afternoon.
Aliotti deserves another year. He's a good coach with a good system
and a young defense. Not only are there two senior and two junior
starters, but many of the top reserves are first- and second-year
players.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive breakdowns against Stanford and Oregon State were
Aliotti's fault _ too much man-to-man, too many complicated
packages, substitution chaos _ but Saturday's debacle was not. It
was about effort and attitude, or lack thereof.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
