<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTLOOK FOR AD SPENDING; ROSTER CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ky., Mass., Minn., Va.)  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Media Executive Bullish on Spending
</P>
<P>
   Fears that economic turmoil in Asia, Brazil and Russia may cause
an advertising spending recession in 1999 are ``well overdone,''
according to the head of a leading media services agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message from our worldwide network is clear: Advertisers
feel good about the future,'' said John Perriss, chairman and chief
executive at Zenith Media Worldwide in London, a joint venture of
Cordiant Communications Group PLC and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
Perriss is to discuss his predictions Monday morning at the opening
session of the annual Paine Webber media conference in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Though worldwide ad spending in 1998 will show the slowest rate
of increase since the recession early this decade, Perriss said in
remarks prepared for the conference, growth will accelerate in
1999, 2000 and 2001. He attributed the expected gains to stronger
spending by advertisers in Western Europe and North America as well
as improvement in Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   Expanded Roles For 2 Agencies
</P>
<P>
   Two big advertisers have expanded relationships with agencies on
their rosters.
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Forman Beverages Worldwide awarded the Martin Agency in
Richmond, Va., a unit of Interpublic Group of Companies, the
creative duties for Southern Comfort liqueur, Canadian Mist whiskey
and Early Times bourbon. Billings were estimated at more than $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Comfort and Canadian Mist had been handled for six
years by another Interpublic unit _ Hill, Holliday/Altschiller _
which is the New York office of the Boston agency Hill, Holliday,
Connors, Cosmopulos. The decision, which came without a review,
removes that agency from the Brown-Forman Beverages roster. Early
Times had been handled by various agencies on a project basis.
</P>
<P>
   Martin joined the Brown-Forman Beverages roster in May 1997 with
the creative assignment for Finlandia vodka. ``We're pleased with
the work for Finlandia and the results in the marketplace,'' said
Jack Kennard, senior vice president and executive director for
global brand development at Brown-Forman Beverages in Louisville,
Ky., ``and we're enthusiastic about asking Martin to take on these
additional brands.'' Media services for the brands remain at
Advanswers in St. Louis, a unit of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   In the other change, Georgia-Pacific Corp. named the New York
office of the Minneapolis agency Fallon McElligott to handle
advertising for consumer paper product brands like Angel Soft,
Coronet, MD and Sparkle. Recent spending for those brands of
bathroom tissue, napkins and paper towels has run about $13.5
million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The brands had been handled since March by BBDO South in
Atlanta, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of Omnicom, which will
retain the Georgia-Pacific corporate image advertising account. The
Fallon McElligott New York office joined the Georgia-Pacific roster
in June with a branding assignment for the company's packaged
products group.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTS: Cantisano Foods Inc., Fairport, N.Y., has chosen
Greenstone Roberts Advertising, Melville, N.Y., to handle
advertising for Franesco Rinaldi pasta sauces, which had been
handled by Vito Catalano Inc., New York, which closed. Vito
Catalano, who headed that agency, recently joined Greenstone
Roberts as senior vice president. Billings were estimated at more
than $7 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
