<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR GIVES ROBINSON A VOTE OF CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Kings have lost 11 of their past 12
games, but general manager Dave Taylor said Sunday the solution is
not to replace coach Larry Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry is our coach, period,'' Taylor said after Sunday's
practice at the Forum. ``He and I are going to work together to try
to get this situation resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the contract extension offered to Robinson during
training camp _ an extension he chose not to sign at the time _
Taylor said: ``We're talking about it. We've agreed to table it.
The priority is to get the team turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, in his fourth year as Kings coach, is in the final
year of his contract. Of his decision to wait to sign the
extension, Robinson said: ``I've chosen not to do anything. It
doesn't mean I don't want it. I just didn't want to address it now.
If I didn't have confidence in my ability and was afraid of losing
my job, I probably would have jumped on it right away.''
</P>
<P>
   When the extension was offered, job insecurity for Robinson was
a non-issue, because he was coming off a season in which he'd been
a finalist for Coach of the Year honors. Two months later, the
Kings (6-17-3) have the worst record in the NHL. The Kings' next
game is Wednesday night against Washington at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in Robinson's three-plus years as Kings
coach that his long-term future has been in doubt, the other
occasion coming late in his second season.
</P>
<P>
   On April 22, 1997, the day Taylor was promoted to his current
position, the Kings also announced that Robinson had agreed to
remain with the Kings for the final two years of his original
four-year contract. Robinson had wanted his contract renegotiated
to include an escape clause after last season, but Taylor said at
the time Robinson would remain despite not getting that clause.
</P>
<P>
   As for the current state of the Kings, Taylor said: ``You have
to look at the big picture. We went through a series of very tough
injuries and a very tough schedule.... Working together is how
we're going to turn this around _ Larry, his staff, myself and the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Spreading blame: After Saturday's 4-3 loss to Detroit, Robinson
said defenseman Steve Duchesne had committed a ``cardinal sin'' by
abandoning the front of the net to chase forward Doug Brown to the
left boards on the play that resulted in the Red Wings' winning
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a play like this, if you blame a certain person... come in
and tell me in person,'' Duchesne said Sunday when asked about
Robinson's critique. ``Don't go in the paper and say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson softened his position Sunday, saying Duchesne was just
one of a number of players guilty of making mistakes on the goal
that cost the Kings the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen the play (on videotape),'' Robinson said. ``I was
a lot harder on (Duchesne) than I should have been. Having seen the
play, he wasn't the biggest culprit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
