<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS GET TWO DAYS TO PRESENT DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's lawyers braced Sunday for their
last stand before the House Judiciary Committee, as top lawmakers
in both parties said the full House is poised to send at least one
impeachment charge to the Senate for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks after the House appeared certain to reject articles
of impeachment, Clinton's legal team Tuesday is scheduled to launch
a last-ditch, 30-hour marathon presentation aimed at staving off
the first Senate trial of a sitting president in 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee, in a letter Sunday to Clinton's
lawyers, said the White House can make its final arguments to the
panel Tuesday and Wednesday, from 9 a.m. to midnight each day.
</P>
<P>
   As the prospects also seemed to dim for alternatives to a House
vote on impeachment, Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell
Democrat on the Judiciary Committee, said Clinton must act urgently
to salvage the compromise initiative. The panel is expected to
approve at least one impeachment charge against Clinton by the end
of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Support for an alternative to impeachment appears to have
eroded, as GOP moderates and some Democrats criticized Clinton's
legalistic response last month to 81 questions from the committee
asking him to admit numerous details stemming from his sexual
affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has acknowledged misleading people about the
relationship, he has denied allegations by the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, that he committed 11 impeachable offenses in
trying to cover up the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's supporters have begun warning him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical that the White House recognize the fact that the
president needs to admit that his conduct was unacceptable and that
he was wrong,'' Meehan said in an interview. ``He needs to come to
terms with the fact that there needs to be some kind of punishment
short of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet several lawmakers indicated on television news shows Sunday
that the opportunity may already have passed to exert enough
pressure on House leaders to permit a vote on an alternative short
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The House majority whip, Tom DeLay of Texas, ruled out the
possibility of a vote on a compromise plan and said, ``If we voted
Monday, the president would be impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Representative John Conyers Jr., the ranking Democrat
on the Judiciary Committee, said he will continue to fight for a
compromise, he charged that House Republicans are waging a
``psychopathic'' effort to remove Clinton from office. Conyers said
the full House is ``quite likely'' to approve at least one article
of impeachment as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   If impeachment charges pass the House, Senate majority leader
Trent Lott said, the Senate would move ``very briskly'' toward a
trial even though it appears extremely unlikely that supporters of
Clinton's ouster could muster the 67 votes they would need to
remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he hoped the inquiry would be much shorter than the
three-month trial of President Andrew Johnson in 1868, the only
other presidential impeachment trial in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see it lasting just a few days to a few weeks,'' Lott
said.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee plans to begin debating several
impeachment charges on Thursday, after presentations from the White
House and the chief investigators for both parties on the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers had sought four days to present Clinton's
case. But the committee, in altering its original plan for a
one-day presentation by the president's legal team, accused the
White House of creating the problem by flouting the panel's
deadline for scheduling the final argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, you have failed to comply with the committee's
procedures and demonstrated contempt for the committee's process,''
the panel's chief of staff, Thomas E. Mooney, wrote to the White
House lawyers, Charles F.C. Ruff and Gregory B. Craig. ``I am
concerned that your recent maneuvers may be little more than an
attempt to delay the committee and turn attention away from the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee gave Clinton's lawyers until noon Monday to
propose the witnesses they want to call.
</P>
<P>
   The White House responded with disdain and resignation. ``The
independent counsel spent four years and $40 million investigating
the president,'' said James F. Kennedy, special adviser to the
White House counsel. ``The committee is spending four months doing
the same. Our request for just four days has now been cut in half.
Nevertheless, we will work to defend the president despite these
restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said Clinton's lawyers were developing a list of
prospective witnesses to deliver to the committee Monday. As of
late Sunday, he said, the White House had settled on only three:
Nicholas Katzenbach, an attorney general under President Lyndon B.
Johnson; Bruce Ackerman, a Yale law professor; and Sean Wilentz, a
Princeton history professor.
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to argue that Clinton's misdeeds do not meet
the standards for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet several committee Republicans said they expect the panel to
approve at least one count of perjury and possibly charges of
obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   The perjury charge, which will allege that Clinton lied under
oath to a federal grand jury investigating the Lewinsky matter, is
seen as most likely to pass the full House.
</P>
</TEXT>
