<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE'S CREW UNITES U.S.-RUSSIAN MODULES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By MARK CARREAU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Endeavour astronauts joined the first pieces of
the new international space station Sunday night in a seven-hour
orbital display of the right stuff and the new symbolism of
post-Cold War global cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The difficult task united large U.S. and Russian manufactured
modules, forming a single 74-foot-long, nearly 70,000-pound
structural bridge with rudimentary propulsion, electrical power
generation and ground communications. Eventually, station planners
hope, the bridge will join scientific laboratories, crew quarters
and other components from 16 different nations as the outpost grows
to the size of two football fields placed side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's successful operation culminated at 8:07 p.m., CST, as
Endeavour's six astronauts soared 240 miles over the South Pacific
Ocean. A burst of the shuttle's steering thrusters nudged the
docking mechanism of the U.S module locked in Endeavour's cargo bay
into the latching assembly of the Russian module. The Russian
module was suspended inches above the American component in the
grasp of the shuttle's long robot arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have capture,'' Endeavour commander Bob Cabana informed
mission control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We congratulate the crew of the good ship Endeavour,''
responded Chris Hadfield, the shuttle crew's liaison in mission
control. ``That's terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty minutes after the capture, the two modules had been
mechanically matched together with an air-tight seal. This part of
the procedure took longer than anticipated because of a small
temporary misalignment between the two components. Once the robot
arm was released from the Russian module the misalignment
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Joined were:
</P>
<P>
   A 33-foot-long, 25,600-pound American module dubbed ``Unity''
that Endeavour lifted off with early last Friday. The $300 million
module was built for NASA by Boeing. Cylinder-shaped with a stubby
cone at each end, Unity earned its name from its half-dozen docking
ports. The ports were designed to accept the station's future U.S.
research module, airlock, an observation deck, crew quarters and
trusswork for the primary American power generation gear.
</P>
<P>
   A 41-foot-long, 42,600-pound propulsion and power production
module christened ``Zarya,'' Russian for sunrise. Zarya was
launched from Central Asia on Nov. 20 at Russian expense. As the
station's cornerstone, Zarya will generate electrical power and
furnish the propulsive maneuvers needed to keep the Earth's gravity
from pulling the two modules back to the ground. The Russian
aerospace contractor, Krunichev, received $240 million from the
United States to produce it. Eventually, Zarya's responsibilities
will be taken over by other station components and it will become a
storage facility and fuel depot.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's activities required Endeavour's crew of five Americans
and a Russian cosmonaut working with mission control teams in
Houston and suburban Moscow to rendezvous with and capture Zarya
using the shuttle's Canadian-built, 50-foot-long robot arm. The
coordination was painstaking at times, as the fliers and the ground
teams talked back and forth to ensure the docking mechanisms were
accurately aligned before the shuttle initiated the propulsive
latching procedure.
</P>
<P>
   A serious miscalculation would have caused the modules to bounce
dangerously off one another.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, and without a hitch, Cabana and pilot Rick
Sturckow executed a series of carefully timed maneuvers that
brought Endeavour beneath, in front of and finally 10 feet above
Zarya.
</P>
<P>
   Then the shuttle crew waited patiently within grasping distance
for nearly a half-hour until the two high flying spacecraft were
over the Russian ground stations that were to monitor the module's
capture.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:47 p.m., CST, and 242 miles over the border between Russia
and Kazakhstan, Endeavour astronaut Nancy Currie commanded the
55-foot-long robot arm to grab the Russian module. She accomplished
the delicate task two minutes into a 10.5 minute capture period
that expired as Russian ground stations lost contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Zarya firmly attached to the orbiter (Endeavour),'' an
exuberant Cabana radioed mission control. ``We're halfway home for
the day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are exhaling down here,'' responded Chris
Hadfield, the shuttle crew's liaison in mission control. ``That's
great.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Currie had used the robotic arm to position Unity
atop the airlock and docking mechanism in Endeavour's cargo bay to
await the linkup with Zarya. The repositioning left the American
module jutting four stories out of the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The towering Unity module blocked direct views of Zarya from
shuttle windows for both Cabana and Currie as the shuttle crew
conducted its risky, close-up operations with the free-flying
Russian module.
</P>
<P>
   Currie nabbed Zarya relying on closed-circuit television views
beamed from video cameras in the shuttle cargo bay and on the robot
arm. They remained her primary view over the next two hours as she
carefully raised and aligned Zarya atop Unity.
</P>
<P>
   With only inches separating the two modules, Cabana fired the
shuttle's steering thrusters forcing their respective docking
assemblies together in a mechanical clinch that neither station
partner seems likely to break.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew began Sunday trailing Zarya by several thousand
miles.
</P>
<P>
   The rendezvous activities were interrupted briefly early in the
day when U.S. military satellite trackers warned NASA of a
potential ``near miss'' between the shuttle and the third stage of
a commercial Delta II rocket that was launched from Vandenberg Air
Force Base, Calif., on Nov. 6 with several small communications
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Well in advance of a potential convergence, Endeavour's crew
maneuvered to ensure a clearance of at least five miles rather than
the predicted 1.8 miles.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of an abbreviated rest period, the shuttle crew awoke
eager to tackle the most difficult phase of their 12-day mission, a
rendezvous and capture operation for which they had trained two
years. The mission was delayed a year by Russian financial
difficulties that have slowed the development of a future station
component that nonetheless paced the launchings of the first two
modules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreams do come true for all who are persistent and keep the
faith,'' Cabana noted as mission control woke up the astronauts
with ``Somewhere Over the Rainbow'' as sung by Judy Garland.
</P>
<P>
   Three lengthy spacewalks will be required to complete the task
of fully integrating Unity and Zarya.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the excursions is scheduled to begin late tonight
(Monday). Spacewalking astronauts Jerry Ross and Jim Newman plan to
scale the two joined modules, connecting nearly 40 power and
computer data cables.
</P>
<P>
   A second spacewalk is intended to establish a direct, high speed
communications link between the new station and NASA's mission
control.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the two excursions and a third later this week, the
spacewalkers will attach foot and hand holds as they proceed to
secure themselves for the hand-intensive tasks, or they will
position themselves on the end of the shuttle's robot arm ``cherry
picker'' style.
</P>
<P>
   Though tethered while they work, both men will wear a new
jetpack that would permit them to maneuver back to the shuttle if
the safety line snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, the Endeavour crew plans to make their way
through the shuttle's airlock and a succession of hatches into the
interior of Unity and Zarya. They plan to leave tools and supplies
for future shuttle construction crews and the first expedition of
cosmonauts and astronauts who are tentatively scheduled to take up
residence aboard the growing station in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   All told, 45 assembly launches and 162 spacewalks are envisioned
to fully construct the new station over the next six years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
