<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 12/06/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WEST CHESTER, Pa. -- Dec. 6, 1998 --
DISEASE-MANAGED-CARE, 12-06 -- Nick Polidore, 11, who has asthma,
learning to use an inhaler at a West Chester clinic. When he comes
to the clinic, he is examined by his doctor, Brandt Loev, left, and
counseled by the patient educator, Wendy York, in how to deal with
his asthma himself when that is appropriate. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- HILLARY-VOGUE-MEDIA, 12-06
-- Mrs. Clinton joins Harvey Weinstein and Gwyneth Paltrow for
Miramax's ``Shakespeare in Love'' premiere last week. During last
summer's Lewinsky uproar, there was some doubt that Hillary Clinton
would make the cover of Vogue. (She did, in fact, appear on the
cover of Vogue's December issue.) (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) IRVINE, Calif. -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- MICROSOFT-FLAT, 12-06
-- Steve Gibson is one of several researchers who contend that
Microsoft's Cleartype font-resolution technique is based on
previous technology and should not win a patent. ``I'm afraid they
are going to try to claim it as their own,'' says Gibson, a
software developer who wrote programs for the Apple II personal
computer. (Bart Bartholomew/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MILWAUKEE -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- SIX-SIGMA-2, 12-06 --
General Electric, using Six Sigma, corrected early design defects
in its scanner, like the one in use at Froedtert Memorial Lutheran
Hospital in Milwaukee. In practice, Six Sigma is a statistical
quality-control method that combines the art of the efficiency
expert with the science of the computer geek. And a growing group
of big companies swear by it. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MILWAUKEE -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- SIX-SIGMA-1, 12-06 --
General Electric used Six Sigma theories to repair flaws in a tube
(circled, upper right) in its medical scanner. ``Six Sigma has
galvanized our company with an intensity the likes of which I have
never seen in my 40 years at GE,'' says G.E. Chairman John Welch.
(Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- TEAMSTERS-RDP, 12-5 --
James P. Hoffa, center, being congratulated on his election as
president of the teamsters' union after his main opponent, Tom
Leedham, conceded defeat Saturday. The victory returns the Hoffa
name to the head of a union that federal officials had long called
the most corrupt, particularly when Hoffa's father, James R. Hoffa,
led the organization from 1957 to 1971. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BLOOMINGTON, Ind. -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- LAYOFFS-NEWSTYLE,
12-06 -- Rhoda Wright's unemployment insurance will run out six
months before she completes an accounting course, but she is more
worried that her husband, Ronald, might fall ill, forcing her to
quit school. ``I don't have a clue anymore what our income is going
to be, but we'll get by,'' says Mrs. Wright, 49. ``We always
have.'' (Mary Ann Carter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BEIJING -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- CHINA-PETITIONERS-2, 12-06 --
China allows those with grievances against local authorities to
appeal up the chain to county and national officials. In Beijing,
scores have been waiting for decades for recourse in presenting
their petitions to top officials. Sun Yuying, 80, wants his
pension. ``If I spend my time at that office, how can I make any
living?'' he laments. (Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BEIJING -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- CHINA-PETITIONERS-1, 12-06 --
In Beijing, scores have been waiting for decades for recourse in
presenting their petitions to top officials. Dong Xiulan, 78, seeks
her late husband's pension. ``They acted like Lords, demanding that
I give them money,'' she says of the beginning of her quest in the
late 1970s. (Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Dec. 6, 1998 --
FBN-JETS-SEAHAWKS, 12-6 -- New York Jets quarterback Vinny
Testaverde after his 5-yard sneak on fourth down with 20 seconds
left Sunday. The play was ruled a touchdown, giving the Jets a
32-31 decision over the Seattle Seahawks. Television replays
clearly showed that Testaverde hadn't reached the end zone, but
since such replays are no longer used in the NFL, the touchdown
counted. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- ECHO-DANCE-REVIEW, 12-06 --
From left, Edward Franklin, Linda Caceres and Richard Witter of the
Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater perform ``Echo: Far From Home''
during the Friday premier at City Center. Judith Jamison's
production is a new work that gives nonlinear narrative an original
twist. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- KISS-THEATER-REVIEW, 12-06 --
Sandra Oh, left, as Sara, and Jessica Hecht, as Callie, in Diana
Son's ``Stop Kiss'' at the Joseph Papp Public Theater. Manhattan
growls like an underfed pit bull in this sweet, sad and
enchantingly sincere play by the young American writer Diana Son.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) KINSHASA, Congo -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- CONGO-REVIEW-2, 12-06
-- While the whole of Congo is being fought over by fewer than
70,000 men, a child soldier takes a break in Kinshasa. What has
developed in Congo is a tribal war along lines that are almost
biblical -- rulers from Nilotic ethnic groups in Rwanda, Burundi
and Uganda against Bantu peoples of central and southern Africa in
league with Arab rulers of northern Chad and Sudan. Sadly, greed
and hatred are the two strongest, and children suffer the most.
(Robert Grossman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MBUJI-MAYI, Congo -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- CONGO-REVIEW-1,
12-06 -- Impoverished young men search for diamonds in the mud at a
small mine near Mbuji-Mayi. As war grinds on, hope for the future
keeps receding in Congo, the huge central African country formerly
known as Zaire. Every force in the Congo fights for a different
reason. Sadly, greed and hatred are the two strongest, and children
suffer the most. (Robert Grossman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
