   (NYT11) MILWAUKEE -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- SIX-SIGMA-2, 12-06 --
General Electric, using Six Sigma, corrected early design defects
in its scanner, like the one in use at Froedtert Memorial Lutheran
Hospital in Milwaukee. In practice, Six Sigma is a statistical
quality-control method that combines the art of the efficiency
expert with the science of the computer geek. And a growing group
of big companies swear by it. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MILWAUKEE -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- SIX-SIGMA-1, 12-06 --
General Electric used Six Sigma theories to repair flaws in a tube
(circled, upper right) in its medical scanner. ``Six Sigma has
galvanized our company with an intensity the likes of which I have
never seen in my 40 years at GE,'' says G.E. Chairman John Welch.
(Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- TEAMSTERS-RDP, 12-5 --
James P. Hoffa, center, being congratulated on his election as
president of the teamsters' union after his main opponent, Tom
Leedham, conceded defeat Saturday. The victory returns the Hoffa
name to the head of a union that federal officials had long called
the most corrupt, particularly when Hoffa's father, James R. Hoffa,
led the organization from 1957 to 1971. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BLOOMINGTON, Ind. -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- LAYOFFS-NEWSTYLE,
12-06 -- Rhoda Wright's unemployment insurance will run out six
months before she completes an accounting course, but she is more
worried that her husband, Ronald, might fall ill, forcing her to
quit school. ``I don't have a clue anymore what our income is going
to be, but we'll get by,'' says Mrs. Wright, 49. ``We always
have.'' (Mary Ann Carter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BEIJING -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- CHINA-PETITIONERS-2, 12-06 --
China allows those with grievances against local authorities to
appeal up the chain to county and national officials. In Beijing,
scores have been waiting for decades for recourse in presenting
their petitions to top officials. Sun Yuying, 80, wants his
pension. ``If I spend my time at that office, how can I make any
living?'' he laments. (Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BEIJING -- Dec. 6, 1998 -- CHINA-PETITIONERS-1, 12-06 --
In Beijing, scores have been waiting for decades for recourse in
presenting their petitions to top officials. Dong Xiulan, 78, seeks
her late husband's pension. ``They acted like Lords, demanding that
I give them money,'' she says of the beginning of her quest in the
late 1970s. (Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo)
</P>
