<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETTY-DISPUTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORS CRY `ENOUGH CULTURE,' OPPOSE GETTY EXPANSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
By PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A not-in-my-backyard dispute has surfaced in the
tony Pacific Palisades enclave, pitting culture against affluence
and throwing a kink into plans to reopen the original, historic J.
Paul Getty museum as a grander, new Getty Villa.
</P>
<P>
   The Getty Institute proposes combining antiquity exhibitions and
conservation research on its bluff-top estate, which closed as a
museum in 1997, when the Getty Center opened in Brentwood. The new
Getty Villa would place Los Angeles higher on the world's cultural
map, supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans are tempered, however, by neighbors who would just
as soon not have the same headaches as Brentwood residents faced
when the new Getty museum opened a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cie(cq) Allman lives just paces from the Villa's entrance. The
host of a morning television workout show, ``Infinite Power
Workout,'' said it's a shame the Getty was closed, but the
community doesn't need it re-opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have enough culture already,'' she said. ``The
Palisades is not a Mecca. We want to be left alone. That's why
people like Tom Cruise, Tom Hanks and Arnold Schwarzenegger live
here.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The dispute comes to a head Monday, when the Pacific Palisades
Community Council, an advisory panel to the Los Angeles City
Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski, is scheduled to consider approving
the Getty's expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
   The local council last month recommended approval for the
estate's renovation, but it remains opposed to expansion. In the
end, the issue will be resolved by the City Council, which
traditionally listens to the local council members.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the battle is the J. Paul Getty Trust, with its
$170 million plan to revive the 53-year-old site as a museum
devoted to antiquities and the study of ancient art, archeology and
conservation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other is the Palisades council, which believes the
expansion will cause annoying evening tumult and add congestion to
the already gridlocked Pacific Coast Highway.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the issue is a proposed 95,000-square-foot
expansion of the museum at the original estate, which was closed in
1997 when the Getty Center opened.
</P>
<P>
   The site would include a 600-seat outdoor ampitheater, expanded
food and alcohol service and a 610-car parking structure.
</P>
<P>
   Located just off PCH on Coastline Road, the Villa would also
have expanded business hours, improved access for the disabled, a
relocated entrance and wider access for emergency crews, said
Marion True, assistant director of Villa planning.
</P>
<P>
   Purchased in 1945 by Getty as a ranch house and a place to
display his art, the site already has its original museum and two
other buildings serving as art and conservation laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase would be a 45,000-foot expansion. If approved,
the Getty Trust would create a new entry pavillion, a tea room, an
expanded bookstore and an underground auditorium to compliment the
ampitheater.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase would add 50,000 more square feet, including
the parking structure, a garden building and additions to the art
and conservation labs.
</P>
<P>
   The Getty Foundation plans to hold lectures and seminars for
those with interests in antiquities and ancient culture. The
ampitheater will be host to a variety of ancient theater and
symphonic music, True said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Wilson, president of the Pacific Palisades Community
Council, and member Shirley Haggstrom both said they are
``thrilled'' at the thought of breathing new life into the facility
that was shut down in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the council unanimously approved support for two-thirds
of the project at its Nov. 12 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   That vote approved renovation, but expansion is a different
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic is the main reason,'' Wilson said. ``It's a
difficult position to take weighing the benefits of culture against
community impact, but what they are proposing will definitely have
an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   People living in the shadow of the project agreed. Most
residents declined to give their names but said they were against
the project, citing a myriad of expected headaches.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is trying to reach a compromise with the council,
and are dedicated to addressing its concerns, True said.
</P>
<P>
   ``PCH traffic is a delicate issue in the first place, so we're
working to see how we can facilitate this,'' True said. ``We've
always been a good neighbor to the community and we have no
intention of disrupting the quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Miscikowski, who represents the area and lives near the new
Getty Center, is confident both sides will eventually come to
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties have agreed to about 25 of the 30 issues that are
on the table,'' said Linda Bernhardt, Miscikowski's senior planning
deputy. ``The remaining items are hot-button issues that probably
won't be resolved until the very end. I'm sure we'll come to some
middle ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: the Los Angeles City Council will make the
final decision despite lobbying efforts of the Pacific Palisades
Community Council. While it's unlikely, the project can still be
killed altogether, or the Getty Foundation could be allowed to go
forward with few restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   That thought doesn't bother Wilson. The council has been around
for more than 25 years and he is confident its voice will be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the nonpartisan voice of the community and our votes
are an expression of opinion,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no jurisdictional authority and no veto power. But
we've been around a long time and we have a great relationship with
our city councilwoman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
