<SLUG> BC-CAT-BOOK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTER TO FIRST CAT BRINGS FAME TO MISSOURI GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIM KOZLOWSKI  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOONVILLE, Mo. _ At age 9, Anna Campbell already has composed a
poem for a baby's baptism. She has illustrated a book of her own
verses. And after seeing ``Titanic,'' she went straight home and
started a screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   But what has made her famous? The letter she wrote last year to
Socks, the White House cat.
</P>
<P>
   Anna's letter was one of 55 to appear in first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton's new book, Dear Socks, Dear Buddy: Kids' Letters to
the First Pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a writer when I grow up, and I think it's pretty
neat to have something I wrote published in a book,'' said Anna, a
fourth-grader at Barton Elementary School in Boonville in central
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Anna wrote to Socks as part of a school lesson on
letter-writing. Although the book landed in stores Nov. 17, Anna
didn't know until this week that her letter was selected from
300,000 notes and drawings children had sent to the Clintons' pets.
</P>
<P>
   Her letter is the only contribution from a child living in
Kansas or Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Socks,'' begins her letter on Page 93. ``How does it feel
to live in the White House? What is your favorite hiding place in
the White House? Do you shed a lot? Does the president drink alot
of coffee? He might want to switch to decafe! Ha! Ha! Your friend,
Anna Campbell.''
</P>
<P>
   A postscript asked Socks to write back, but Anna isn't expecting
to hear from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a really busy cat,'' Anna said. ``I probably wouldn't be
able to read cat words anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
