<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESPECT CO-WORKERS' OPINIONS ABOUT SHARING POINTS OF VIEW IN
OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Some people like strong, opinionated conversation.
President Clinton? Abortion? Affirmative action? Whatever the
topic, some simply like to debate. Others are passionate about
specific issues and love to proselytize about positions they hold
dear.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those people who shy away from talking about
anything more controversial than the weather. They're uncomfortable
with strongly stated opinions and they're disinclined to share
their own. Where the first camp relishes ``debate,'' this camp
fears ``argument.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens when those two types are thrown together in the
workplace?
</P>
<P>
   Here's one reader's view: ``I suppose that vigorous discussion
can be a good thing in the proper context. However, when these
things are brought into a place where people are supposed to be
working together for some common good, I think they produce ill
will and tension.''
</P>
<P>
   Career paths are made or wrecked because of interpersonal
relationships. Thus, it's important for anyone who cares about
promotability to be sensitive to co-workers' and managers'
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   If you work in a vent-at-will organization, where emotionally
charged dialogue seems to be enjoyed, then you're more free to
share your thoughts. You could be branded, though, as an
out-of-touch liberal in a stable of arch conservatives (or
vice-versa) and lose out in office politics if the opposite school
of thought dominates.
</P>
<P>
   If the climate in your organization is distinctly close-mouthed,
then you may want to keep your thoughts to yourself. If you can't
live with that, an employment change might be the best solution.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace harmony and career images are fragile, flexible
things. They depend partly on the tenor of your organization and
the nature of the managers who make career decisions that affect
you.
</P>
<P>
   You need to know if what you thought was a ``neat lunch
discussion'' was their ulcer-inducing pain that left you with an
unfortunate label.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT &LR;      12-06 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: UNDEMOCRATIC HOUSE OF LORDS DEFENDS PEOPLES' RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are few institutions in the world more venerable than
Britain's House of Lords, whose roots date back to the 11th
century. Now, as that institution is about to be changed almost
beyond recognition, it has emerged as a protector of the rights of
individuals at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Law Lords, a group of five peers who serve as
Britain's highest court, surprised many by ruling that the former
Chilean dictator, Augusto Pinochet, can be extradited to Spain to
stand trial. ``International law has made plain that certain types
of conduct, including torture and hostage-taking, are not
acceptable conduct on the part of anyone,'' wrote Lord Nicholls.
</P>
<P>
   The decision has left Britain's Labor government in an
uncomfortable position as it decides whether to permit the
extradition. The Labor Party has long reviled Pinochet, but Prime
Minister Tony Blair also values good relations with Chile and many
in Britain recall the general's help during the 1982 Falklands war
between Britain and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that the possible discomfort of Blair
played a part in the decision of the Law Lords. But it would be
understandable if some members of the House of Lords were pleased
to see the government squirm. The day before the decision was
announced, Queen Elizabeth II, reading a speech to Parliament that
was written by the government, announced that ``a bill will be
introduced to remove the right of hereditary peers to sit and vote
in the House of Lords.'' She added that it would be the first step
in an effort to make the House more democratic and representative.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, most members of the House of Lords are there by
inheritance, but many were appointed for life by governments chosen
by the Commons. The Law Lords who rendered the Pinochet decision
were appointed to the body.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing hereditary peers to vote is hardly democratic, and
reform is perhaps overdue. But Blair has yet to reveal what further
changes he will make. Having a house composed of only appointed
members is not a model of democracy either.
</P>
<P>
   The powers of the House of Lords are already limited. It cannot
block money bills, and other legislation can be delayed for no more
than two years. As Walter Bagehot, the British journalist and
historian, wrote 126 years ago, ``The House of Lords must yield
whenever the opinion of the Commons is also the opinion of the
nation, and when it is clear that the nation has made up its
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the House of Lords is now involved in what may be
such a fight. It is resisting a government bill _ already approved
by the Commons _ to change the way Britain chooses its delegates to
the European Parliament. The new electoral system would make it all
but impossible for a European Parliament candidate opposed by his
or her party's leaders to win election, thereby making it more
likely delegates would do as they were told. Members of the House
of Lords, that most undemocratic of institutions, say that is not
very democratic. They would seem to have a point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      12-06 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING MONEY IS A MEANS TO AN END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: America's bad saving statistics are useless except to
generate scare headlines that grab the attention of newspaper
readers.
</P>
<P>
   When the personal savings rate recently dived into negative
territory for the first time in 65 years, for instance, it wasn't
nearly as disastrous a development as conventional wisdom
dispensers claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to keep in mind when assessing the significance
of savings data is the fact that savings is a means to an end, not
an end itself. When people save, they're deferring gratification.
Most people deny themselves in the present as a trade-off for a
more rewarding consumption experience in the future. They save to
pay for such things as dream vacations, homes, college for the kids
and better retirements.
</P>
<P>
   What is the optimum savings rate? Who's to say? All that can be
said is that it's just as possible to save too much as it is too
little.
</P>
<P>
   Take Japan, for instance. Although it has one of the highest
savings rates in the world, its economy is a disaster. Its
world-class savings rate has not brought a significantly improved
quality of life, but rather poor business and political decisions
that undermine the well-being of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Japan's excessive savings fed a pool of investment capital
that grew too large to be used productively. Many of the resulting
attempts to put this money to work went into projects that not only
were unproductive, but often counterproductive. The result is a
country awash in bad debts.
</P>
<P>
   As for America's saving situation, is it as bad as convention
would have us believe? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Investor's Business Daily recently trotted out some perspectives
that put the savings picture into better balance.
</P>
<P>
   First, the capital gains windfall from the soaring stock market
has allowed more Americans to achieve their savings goals without
actually saving more money.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department's methodology is such that it
understates what most people would consider savings. The Japanese,
for instance, save more, but America's home ownership rate is much
higher than Japan's.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling component of the analysis was a review of some
figures from a St. Louis Federal Reserve Bank study published in
1989. This research included in its savings component home buying,
durable goods purchases, capital gains and debt reduction. This
more realistic approach showed the savings rate well above what
official calculations showed from the '50s through the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of Social Security's effect on savings.
When this involuntary form of savings was counted by St. Louis Fed
researchers, it showed the total savings rate rising from 13
percent in the '50s to nearly 25 percent in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Something else to remember is that savings takes numerous forms.
When Uncle Sam achieved a $70 billion surplus this fiscal year, for
instance, this was attributable to expanding tax revenues. Thus,
much of that $70 billion represented a transfer of savings from
people to government.
</P>
<P>
   The most important consideration when weighing the implications
of a savings rate statistic is whether a society's growth is strong
enough to deliver enough jobs and higher living standards for all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
