r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      12-06 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTORS AND THEIR OLD TALE BRING ABOUT MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ How can a story that has been told so many
times be made to seem so wholly fresh again?
</P>
<P>
   Partly by the power of the piece itself. And partly through the
craft of the tellers _ in this case, the actors _ who bring it
newly alive.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 155 years and a few days since a debt-burdened
31-year-old English writer put down his pen to let dry the ink on
the last page of a little book he called A Christmas Carol in
Prose, Being a Ghost Story of Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   It was far from the longest book Charles Dickens would write,
and neither the most socially important nor the most lucrative.
Although it sold well, his own monetary returns were disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   But it won for him a fame and affection that has transcended
time, for there have been few works committed to paper that have
lodged so deeply in the public heart.
</P>
<P>
   Over the ensuing century and a half, millions of copies of A
Christmas Carol have been printed in many languages, and the story
has been broadcast uncountable times on the radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   One evening a couple of weeks ago we watched Dickens' vision
given heart and breath on the stage of the Missouri Repertory
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the one-dimensional animated cliche that a piece so
embedded in the popular culture risks becoming. Instead, it was as
original, as new, as true as life itself _ and not just the life of
mid-19th century London, but our contemporary lives as well.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Carol speaks of timeless matters: the disfiguring
influence of greed and loneliness; the saving power of love; the
possibility, in spite of all, of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's magic, of course, was in the actors' art.
</P>
<P>
   Surely there can be few callings that ask as much _ to be able,
night after night, to put one's own identity aside and become
another person. And to do it so completely, with such conviction,
that nothing seems merely rehearsed. So that each gesture is
spontaneous, and every line is spoken for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Several in the cast we know as acquaintances or friends, but
that was quickly forgotten. Because when the curtain opened, they'd
been replaced entirely by their inventions.
</P>
<P>
   We were glad for Scrooge's terror when the ghosts of other
Christmases came to torment him in the night.
</P>
<P>
   We wept at the sweet devotion of the Cratchits, and the
difficulties they bore.
</P>
<P>
   Then old Scrooge was found to be encumbered by sentiment after
all, and we wept again.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bit of singing, and Tiny Tim spoke his expected
line. The lights came up. The audience milled to the exits.
</P>
<P>
   After some minutes, the actors began coming out, too, not
seeming at all, now, like workers of magic. They were just ordinary
people _ different ages and sizes and shapes and genders of them _
mostly in careless dress.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing them that way, it was hard to believe the power they'd
had.
</P>
<P>
   For though the night into which we walked was tepid and
unnatural for the season, for us they'd already rolled the year a
whole month forward and rung the holiday in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
