<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GOMEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS GOMEZ, A TEACHER AND DANCER, 77
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas W. Gomez, a teacher of the Katherine Dunham technique and
a leading dancer with Ms. Dunham's company in the 1940's, died on
Oct. 29 at the Warren Barr Pavilion, a home for the aged, in
Chicago. He was 77 and lived in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was bone cancer, his son, Thomas Gomez III, of Ann
Arbor Mich., said.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, whose stage name was Tommy Gomez, trained in New York at
the schools of Martha Graham and Jose Limon and at the School of
American Ballet. He met Ms. Dunham in 1939 and by the early 1940s
was a prominent member of her troupe, appearing with her on
Broadway, in European tours and in the film ``Stormy Weather.''
</P>
<P>
   A small, lithe and intense performer known for his good-natured
disposition in a company of larger-than-life temperaments, Gomez
first gained fame as the Boy Possessed in the ``Shango'' section of
``Carib Song.'' He also danced the Jealous Husband in
``Rara-Tonga,'' opposite Ramona Erwin as the wife, whom he later
married in real life in an onstage wedding. Gomez also danced lead
roles in Ms. Dunham's ``Flaming Youth'' and ``L'Ag'Ya.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez took over many of the star roles danced by Talley Beatty
when Beatty left the company. He also partnered Ms. Dunham
frequently. He performed on Broadway as a Dunham dancer in ``Cabin
in the Sky'' and ``Tropical Revue.'' He also danced on Broadway in
``On the Town,'' ``Show Boat'' and ``The King and I.'' On film, he
danced in ``Carnival of Rhythm'' and ``Cleopatra.'' He helped Ms.
Dunham choreograph the 1964 production of ``Aida'' at the
Metropolitan Opera House in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez taught at the Dunham School in New York in the 1940's and
was later a master teacher in annual summer Dunham workshops in St.
Louis. He was on the faculties of the Kennedy King College, Truman
College and Joel Hall Dance Center, all in Chicago. In 1984, he
became the artistic director of the Body Language Dance Company in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He was honored in 1980 in ``A Gala Celebration of 50 Years of
Men in Dance'' in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son, he is survived by his wife, Ramona, of
Stamford, Conn.; his mother, Theresa Woosley, of Chicago, and five
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-98 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981206.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-2NDTAK     12-06 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Historians and political scientists, however, will analyze his
record and may be less forgiving. He continues to struggle with
Iraq over biological weapons and with North Korea over nuclear
weapons. He has had more success in his peacemaking efforts in
Bosnia, Northern Ireland and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 20 years, when all the records are available, we will see
in all kinds of ways that we didn't even know about how his
personal problems and domestic policies affected his foreign
policy,'' said Robert Kagan, a senior associate at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace. ``That's inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways there have been at least three Clinton
presidencies. He campaigned as a centrist, a so-called ``New
Democrat,'' but in his first two years got embroiled in costly
political battles over issues viewed as traditionally liberal _ gay
rights and an unsuccessful health-care reform effort.
</P>
<P>
   After a disastrous midterm election in which Democrats lost
majorities in Congress, he tacked toward the center, reaching out
to Republicans with welfare reform and to set a course for budget
surpluses. He won re-election, but a year later, the Lewinsky
scandal controlled the political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given his re-election, he might have been in a position to
have more policy innovation, but almost immediately he got swept up
in these scandals,'' said John Green, director of the Ray C. Bliss
Institute of Applied Politics at the University of Akron. ``I think
it took a lot of his energy. His tremendous political skills were
dedicated to saving his own skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Reforming Social Security looms as Clinton's last major effort
to bolster his legacy. At least to this point, he has no monumental
accomplishment to ground him in the history books, as did President
Truman with the Marshall Plan and Johnson with the Civil Rights
Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historians don't find balanced budgets very sexy,'' Dallek
said, so scandal ``will be a kind of focal point. There are no
big-ticket items. These are not heroic times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
